1. e4 e5
{ Hello and welcome everyone! For those who don't know me, I'm Sam Shankland, I'm a 2700+ player from the USA, and a longtime Chessable author.   I have published a full repertoire series here on Chessable, including 1.d4 part 1, part 2, and part 3 as well as a black repertoire based on the Semi-Slav, a complete repertoire vs the English, Reti, and Sidelines, and the Classical Sicilian vs 1.e4. With a full repertoire complete, the next logical question was what to do next.   Ultimately, I concluded that the best thing to do would be to give another repertoire against 1.e4. I stand by the work I did on the Classical Sicilian, but there is no doubt it is a much more risk-loving opening than the rest of the repertoire, which aims to play more solid, conservative, strategic chess. There is nothing wrong with one opening being a little stylistically different from the rest of a repertoire, and undoubtedly 1.e4 tends to lead to sharper positions. But, I decided it would be nice to counterbalance the very combative and highly unbalanced Classical Sicilian, which I think is a fantastic weapon for playing dynamic games and good for looking for wins even if it means accepting more risk, by choosing the most solid of the solid for its alternative.   The one drawback to the Classical Sicilian is that I would give it a solid 10/10 for its practical value, I think it is only an 8/10 or 9/10 opening in terms of pure objectivity and Black's ability to fight for equality. With the Berlin, we have a totally different scenario. I am not exaggerating when I say I believe this is by far the most solid repertoire you can possibly find against 1.e4. It is an absolute brick wall. The most solid and nitty-gritty players in history have all favored the Berlin at various points in their careers, and this repertoire certainly could show why.   While the Berlin saw some play throughout the 20th century, it was not until Kramnik used it to brickwall Kasparov in their 2000 World Championship match that it suddenly became the new hot thing for the next two decades. At the time, Kasparov was clearly the best player who ever lived, and he lost the match to an opponent that was objectively not as strong a player. The question then becomes, how did Kramnik, the weaker player, manage to beat the greatest of all time in a long match without losing a single game? A big part of it comes down to his match strategy. He clearly had decided to be as solid as humanly possible with the black pieces, prioritizing safety first.   This being the case, it really says a lot that he chose the Berlin as his opening. He clearly felt it was the most solid option Black had against 1.e4, and he proved it by withstanding the repeated scrutiny of the man with the most fearsome opening repertoire who ever lived. Moving on, ever since then, the Berlin has kept its reputation for being notoriously solid. The two matches between Anand and Carlsen saw multiple Berlin Defences played both times, and with both players choosing it as Black. But even more notably, 2016 felt like a repeat of Kasparov-Kramnik. Sergey Karjakin is undoubtedly a fantastic chess player, but he was something of a surprise winner of the Candidates as the lowest rated player, and nobody, myself included, really gave him much of a chance in a match against Magnus. But, of Magnus's 4 World Championship matches played at the time of this writing, Karjakin was the one who came the closest, by far, to winning. Was it because he was a better player than Anand or Caruana? I certainly think not. I think it was because he knew exactly how to play against an objectively much stronger opponent, and the new GOAT at that. He took a page out of Kramnik's book. He played the Berlin exclusively throughout the match, and Magnus completely failed to make any headway.   I was on Magnus' team, helping him prepare, and it was a massively frustrating experience. Eventually, Magnus basically gave up on 1.e4, got tilted from the frustration, and chose to play some funky lines with 1.d4 that were not wildly impressive. He went on to lose game 8 with White, and Karjakin became the only player to take a lead against him to date. Magnus finally struck blood in game 10, defeating Karjakin's Berlin for the first time. I was the mastermind behind his brilliant opening choice, and I mean that in only the most sarcastic possible way. The idea we had come up with was totally harmless objectively, Black would have been totally fine with correct play, but I somehow believed that it was not an easy way for a human to find. Karjakin did not play the best.   But this brings us to another point of the Berlin. It is so solid that even if you get caught in the opening unprepared and react in a less than perfect way, the worst thing that will ever happen to you will be that you will be slightly worse with a lot of chess left to be played. This is in stark contrast to a line like the Najdorf, where if you react poorly to a new move or forget your preparation, you can lose without any fight whatsoever. Karjakin later had a chance to equalize, and missed it. Who knows what the history books would have looked like if he had drawn this game!   For a long time, it has been really hard to come up with any kind of credible book on the Berlin for one simple reason. I have no idea why, but normal engines without any AI influence, such as Stockfish without NNUE evaluation capabilities, are approximately useless in the Berlin Endgame. It has since been revolutionized by Lc0 and Stockfish NNUE, which have completely changed the landscape of how the endgame should be approached, for both colors. I pity those who tried to publish material on the Berlin before 2019. There is almost no chance it will stand up to the scrutiny of modern machines!   Upon studying closely with these engines, I feel I have a much better understanding of the Berlin Endgame, and I am confident I have produced an absurdly solid and bulletproof repertoire that will stand the test of time. With this repertoire, it will be an absolute nightmare for your opponents to be able to put you under any pressure at all. There is not a single place anywhere in the repertoire where Black's king is even remotely unsafe. If you are hit with a new move at some point, the worst possible thing that can happen is you will end up a little worse with a still solid position.   When it comes to objectivity vs practicality, I turned the dial as far as I could towards objectivity and then turned it even further until it broke. The drawback of playing chess this way with the Black pieces is that it is very hard to play for a win. I cannot begin to count the number of lines in this course that lead to very sterile equality. As such, I made absolutely zero attempt to prevent White from forcing a draw if he wants it, and chose the most solid possible lines at every juncture.   If you are looking to play for a win on command with Black or even just reach some more interesting positions, I would definitely think my Classical Sicilian repertoire would be more appropriate, and the Berlin is a poor choice for that game. As such, I don't think it makes sense to try to shake things up within the Berlin- just play a more dynamic opening instead. All that said, I actually think this is a fantastic repertoire to play for a win, but only against a certain kind of opponent. If you are playing someone a bit weaker, they will probably be fine with a draw and not try too hard.   But if you are playing someone stronger, or someone super ambitious, they will become VERY frustrated very fast. The only ways for White to try to imbalance the game in this repertoire tend to involve taking on a lot of risk, leading to positions where things can go very wrong for him very fast. Additionally, playing a boring, equal position against a frustrated opponent often leads them into making poor decisions, trying desperately to somehow shake up the game.   Furthermore, most people who play the Berlin reasonably frequently find that people quickly start playing 1.d4 against them. I remember in my match with Karjakin at the World Cup, I took about 5 minutes looking into his Berlin before I decided to abort the plan and open with 1.c4 instead- call it PTSD if you want! In hindsight, it was clearly the right decision as I went on to win the game.   Long story short, I think this repertoire is a fantastic tool to use under the right circumstances. It is extremely good for making easy draws against stronger players, shutting down people who really thrive in attacking positions, and playing for a win against people who will be frustrated by their inability to put you under pressure as well as people who just plain struggle in dry positions without much going on. I think it complements the Classical Sicilian very well, and choosing between these two options can give you the best of both worlds. The below lines are covered in the course. }
2. Nf3
{ 2.f4  d5  3.exd5  exf4  .  I always liked this way of playing against the King's Gambit, with Nf6 coming next to pressure d5.   2.d4  exd4  3.Qxd4  Nc6  .   2.Bc4  .  This is mainly used as an anti-Petroff weapon, and this does not bother us since we did not want to play the Petroff anyway.  2...Nf6  3.d3  Nc6  .   2.c3  Nf6  .   2.Nc3  Nf6  .  Now, Black should be playing d7-d5 against either g2-g3 or f2-f4.  3.f4  d5!  .   3.g3  d5  . }
2... Nc6 3. Bb5
{ 3.Bc4  Bc5  I prefer this move order in the Italian.  4.c3  Nf6  5.d4   5.d3  O-O  Black will play for d7-d5.  5...exd4  6.e5  d5  .   3.d4  exd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  .  I don't believe in other options against the Scotch. This is the move. }
3... Nf6 4. O-O
{ 4.d3  Bc5  5.Bxc6  dxc6  I always aim to castle long in these positions.   5.c3  d5!  I like breaking in the center right away. }
4... Nxe4 5. d4
{ 5.Re1  Nd6  6.Nxe5  Be7  7.Bf1  Nxe5  8.Rxe5  O-O  Black should be able to reorganize his knight here to get d7-d5 through and equalize. }
5... Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ Black plays Ke8 against any legal move. } *

