1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3
{ The Glek variation has its proponents, but it is not too scary. I like being direct and striking in the center right away. }
3... d5 4. exd5 Nxd5 5. Bg2
{ 5.Nf3  Nxc3  6.bxc3  Nc6  7.Bg2  Bd6  Transposes. } 5... Nxc3 6. bxc3 Nc6 7.
Nf3 Bd6 8. O-O O-O
{ Black has easy equality with Re8 and Bf5 next. I really don't see much sense in White's position, and Iike putting the bishop on d6 where it does not lose a tempo to d4 or a d3/Nd2 regrouping. }
9. d4 Bf5
{ All too easy. All of Black's pieces are nice and active and there is nothing to worry about. }
