[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ The bishop's opening is mainly used as an anti-Petroff weapon, aiming to steer the game more towards an Italian. Since we did not want to play the Petroff in the first place, I can't see much point in it.   2.c4  Nc6  Black already has a nice position with Bf8-c5 and Ng8-e7 coming next. }
2... Nf6 3. d3
{ 3.Nc3  Nc6  4.Nf3   4.a3  Na5  Transposes.  4...Nxe4!  Transposes tothe Four Knights. }
3... Nc6
{ I see no reason to avoid this move. White should probably play Ng1-f3, transposing to the Italian, but he does have a couple of extra options. }
4. Nc3
{ Now, Black can go bishop grabbing.   4.Nf3  Bc5  Takes us to the Italian. }
4... Na5 5. Nge2
{ Now, one key point is I think Black should not rush to take on c4. The bishop is not going anywhere, and White's queen would not mind getting the d3 square. Wait for White to push a2-a3 or a2-a4, and once the bishop is threatening to escape, then we take it. This will force White to spend a tempo on his a-pawn rather than developing his pieces. }
5... c6 6. O-O Bc5
{ White would very much like to play Qd1-d3 and Bc1-e3 here to complete his development and contest the bishop pair. Since we were patient about taking on c4, he cannot do that just yet. }
7. a3 Nxc4 { Of course. } 8. dxc4 d6
{ Black has easy play and a happy development scheme. } *

