1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ Apart from the four main moves of Bb5, Bc4, d4, and Nc3, White has played 23 other options here. I refuse to analyze all of them or even most of them. If you face a3, b4, g4, Ng1, or even Ke2 @@StartBracket@@all of these moves have been played before!@@EndBracket@@, just play chess and forget about preparation. But I did check the more relevant sidelines a bit. }
3. c3
{ If White categorically refuses to play any kind of mainline, this could be seen as a sensible move. He is obviously aiming for d2-d4 next, but it is nothing to be afraid of.   3.d3  Nf6  4.c3  d5  Transposes to the 3.c3 move order. }
3... Nf6 4. d4 exd4
{ This strikes me as the easiest solution. The position almost resembles some kind of strange Alapin Sicilian, but I like the pawn on c7 more than on e7. }
5. e5
{ I struggle to imagine anything else.   5.cxd4  Nxe4  Black is a clean pawn up. }
5... Nd5 6. Bc4 Nb6 7. Bb3 d5 8. cxd4 Bg4
{ Black is ready for Qd8-d7 and O-O-O next, with a very easy position. We will see Magnus put on a clinic in the illustrative gamessection. }
