1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ Now, of course White's three main moves by far are Bb5, Bc4, and d4. But, he does have some extraneous options, including the notorious 4 knights variation. }
3. Nc3 Nf6
{ It really says a lot about how much White is grasping at straws against lines like the Berlin and Petroff that he is sometimes looking in this direction even at top level chess.   The symmetrical nature of the position is hard to break. Now, the two main moves by far are 4.d4 and 4.Bb5, but there are some other options Black should be ready for too. In general, he will be looking to meet most silly looking moves with d7-d5, and quite a few silly looking moves have been tried here! }
4. Bb5
{ This is probably the most challenging try. Now, Black is very fine, but should remember some lines. }
4... Nd4 5. Nxe5 Qe7
{ This somewhat surprising move puts White in a bad way already. } 6. f4 Nxb5
7. Nxb5 d6 { Things get a little sharp now, but Black is surely better. } 8.
Nf3 Qxe4+ 9. Kf2 Ng4+
{ An important move. White's king must either find safety on g1, when we no longer have to worry about Rh1-e1, or he will have to adventure into the wilderness. }
10. Kg3 Qg6 11. Nh4 Qf6
{ g5 is on the way, and White should be careful not to die immediately. } 12.
h3
{ A sad necessity. g5 was about to really hurt. In fact, it still does!   12.Nxc7+  Kd8  Transposes tothe 11.Nxc7+ line. }
12... g5 13. Qe2+
{ White takes the e5-square under his control before hoping to take on g5 next. }
13... Ne5 { A nice trick. The knight is immune from capture. } 14. Nf3
{ A sad necessity.   14.fxe5?  Qf4  This is, quite literally, checkmate. }
14... gxf4+ 15. Kh2 Qe7
{ He still looks worse to me. Black is ready for a7-a6, Bc8-e6, and O-O-O when he will have the safer king and healthy bishop pair. }
