1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ Now, of course White's three main moves by far are Bb5, Bc4, and d4. But, he does have some extraneous options, including the notorious 4 knights variation. }
3. Nc3 Nf6
{ It really says a lot about how much White is grasping at straws against lines like the Berlin and Petroff that he is sometimes looking in this direction even at top level chess.   The symmetrical nature of the position is hard to break. Now, the two main moves by far are 4.d4 and 4.Bb5, but there are some other options Black should be ready for too. In general, he will be looking to meet most silly looking moves with d7-d5, and quite a few silly looking moves have been tried here! }
4. Bb5
{ This is probably the most challenging try. Now, Black is very fine, but should remember some lines. }
4... Nd4 5. Ba4
{ This is the main move by some margin, but actually might be inaccurate thanks to a recent computer idea. }
5... c6
{ I like this move a lot. Black is ready for a7-a5 next, and all of a sudden it will be very hard to save the a4-bishop. }
6. Nxe5
{ White can at least clip a pawn for his troubles, but does not solve his issues. }
6... d6 7. Nd3 b5 8. Bb3 a5 9. a3
{ The bishop is super loose on b3, and Black has a great way to take advantage. }
9... d5 10. e5
{ 10.exd5  Bd6  White will get demolished in short order. Stockfish already claims -4! }
10... Bg4 { Forcing f2-f3, weakening the king further... } 11. f3 Bf5 12. exf6
Qxf6
{ Despite the piece up, White is completely powerless to stop the direct threats. Moving the d3-knight will allow a5-a4 and crashing through on c2, and otherwise, how can he deal with the simple threat of Nxb3? }
