[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Italian Sidelines: 4.c3 and 5.d4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ For a long time, the Spanish was thought of as clearly White's best attempt to fight for an opening advantage. In recent times though, there has been a real Italian Renaissance and Bc4 is looking like every bit as serious an attempt to fight for an advantage. We certainly must be ready. }
3... Bc5 4. c3 Nf6
{ Now, the main move by far is  5.d3  , which will be the subject of the next section. }
5. d4
{ In recent times, this move has become quite popular. It is very forcing, but should not be too threatening if Black is well prepared.   5.d3  O-O  will be covered inChapter 6. }
5... exd4 6. cxd4 Bb4+ 7. Bd2 { This is the main move in modern times. } 7...
Nxe4 { Now things get very forced. } 8. Bxb4 Nxb4 9. Bxf7+ Kxf7 10. Qb3+ Kf8
{ This strikes me as the easiest option. Once the queens are off the board, Black will not have to worry about his king, and he may well end up happy that he did not advance d7-d5, weakening the e5-square. }
11. Qxb4+ Qe7 { Off with the queens! } 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7 13. O-O Kd8 14. Re1 Nf6
{ If Black's pawn were on d5 in a position like this one, a knight coming to e5 could get very annoying very fast. As is, Black has a perfectly solid position and an easy plan to complete his development. Someday the better structure might matter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Italian Sidelines: 4.c3 and 5.d4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ For a long time, the Spanish was thought of as clearly White's best attempt to fight for an opening advantage. In recent times though, there has been a real Italian Renaissance and Bc4 is looking like every bit as serious an attempt to fight for an advantage. We certainly must be ready. }
3... Bc5 4. c3 Nf6
{ Now, the main move by far is  5.d3  , which will be the subject of the next section. }
5. d4
{ In recent times, this move has become quite popular. It is very forcing, but should not be too threatening if Black is well prepared.   5.d3  O-O  will be covered inChapter 6. }
5... exd4 6. e5
{ This is the modern main move, and the one recommended by Wesley So in his course here on Chessable. }
6... d5 { A typical motif. Now, White has to choose where to put the bishop. }
7. Bb5
{ This is definitely the most challenging move. The bishop on b5 is very good prophlaxis against the f7-f6 break later on. }
7... Ne4 8. cxd4 Bb6
{ The one drawback of the bishop on b5 is that the Bg4 pin can be pretty annoying. In modern times, White has tried to solve this problem by delaying castling for awhile. }
9. Nc3
{ In modern times, this has emerged as the main move. White is a bit reluctant to castle short so soon.   9.Be3  O-O  White has nothing better than Nc3 or O-O, transposing to the 9.Nc3 and 9.O-O lines. }
9... O-O 10. Be3 Bg4 11. h3 Bh5 12. Qc2
{ This is exactly the kind of position where it becomes clear that there was some merit to delaying castling. Black would love to take f3, take d4, and go give a check on g5, but the last part of that plan is not a thing until White has put his king on g1. Black has to be careful here to avoid a seriously unpleasant position, but I think he has a nice solution. }
12... Ba5
{ The bishop was not doing much on b6, and now it pins the knight. Of course the pin is temporary, but this encourages White's king to go to g1, which he may regret later on. }
13. Bxc6
{ This doesn't make much sense here. White normally takes on c6 for one of two reasons. One would be to bury the b6 bishop, and the other would be to take back on e5 with the knight. Since Black has not played f7-f6 and his a5-bishop clearly will be exchanged, I don't see much point in this one. }
13... bxc6 14. Nd2 Bg6 { c5 is coming soon and White is already worse. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "The Italian Game: 6.O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3
{ At long last, we are in the mainline Italian. The positions are extremely rich, with lots of subtle move order tricks involving plans with a6/Ba7, a6 and then provoking a4 to play a5, timing of Ne7... endless subtleties and nuances. And I am going to be blunt and direct and ignore all of them!   The easiest way for Black to equalize is to push d7-d5 in one go, and not play d7-d6. I would encourage the reader to investigate some of these d7-d6 plans on their own to find lines with better chances of playing for a win, and to learn about a fascinating middlegame that will improve your overall understanding, but here I am going to stick with the same attitude as the rest of the repertoire and try to find the most solid and forcing way to reach an equal position. }
5... O-O
{ Now, the default is to push d7-d5 next. If Black is allowed to do this comfortably, he will be absolutely fine. }
6. O-O d5 7. exd5 Nxd5
{ Now, if Black is able to consolidate his position, he will be very easily fine thanks to his slightly superior structure and more active pieces. But, it looks a little loose for the moment, and White has a few interesting tries that we definitely need to be ready for. }
8. a4
{ I played this move against Hikaru once in a rapid playoff game at the 2015 World Cup. It was fresh then and his reaction wasn't fantastic, but nowadays it is hardly a big surprise. White's point is that if Black responds in kind with a7-a5, then in a lot of lines the bishop is much more secure on b5. }
8... Bf5
{ I like this direct move. Black gets out a new piece, and is ready for Nd5-b6 to come next. }
9. a5
{ This makes a lot of sense, both stopping Nd5-b6 and threatening a5-a6 in some cases. Now, we cannot allow White to take too mush space. }
9... a6 10. Nbd2 { Now, Nb6 is not possible... for the moment. } 10... b5
{ Black kicks the c4-bishop all the same, and after } 11. axb6 Nxb6
{ White will not save the d3-pawn. Black is fine. } *

