1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ Now, White's two main moves by far are O-O and d3, but he does have a couple extraneous options that Black should be ready for. }
4. Qe2
{ This strikes me as a pretty dumb way to defend the e4-pawn. The queen can easily end up misplaced on the e-file. }
4... Bd6
{ I like this odd looking move. Black will castle next, and then he can follow up with Ne7 and c6, aiming to play a kind of reversed Italian where his bishop reaches the ideal c7 square in two moves rather than 3. Black is very comfortable. }
5. O-O O-O 6. d3 Ne7 7. c3 c6 8. Ba4 Bc7 { Black is already better. } *

