[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ Now, White's two main moves by far are O-O and d3, but he does have a couple of extraneous options that Black should be ready for. }
4. d4
{ Grabbing the whole center is not the dumbest thing White can try, but Black is quite fine if he knows what to do.   4.Nc3  Transposes to the 4 knights variation. }
4... Nxd4 5. Nxd4
{ Now, I like including a little nuance in what might otherwise look like a totally forced decision. }
5... c6
{ Before taking back on d4, Black makes sure to include c7-c6 so that White is unable to push e4-e5. }
6. Bc4 exd4 7. Qxd4 { This is prudent, but unimpressive. } 7... Qb6
{ White's queen turns out to be a bit unstable. } 8. Qxb6
{ This only helps Black by opening his rook and allowing him to capture towards the center. }
8... axb6 9. e5 d5 { A common motif. White is already quite a bit worse. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "The Berlin with 4.d3 and 5.Bxc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6
{ This move looks a little strange, playing some kind of Exchange Spanish where Black has not had to burn a tempo on a7-a6. But, there is some logic to it. In a lot off lines in the Exchange Spanish, Black's knight actually wants to go to e7, and the bishop often wants to go to d6.   Surely Black can play Bc5-d6, claiming that playing Bf8-c5-d6 is not substantially worse than playing Bf8-d6 in one move but also spending a tempo on a7-a6, but the f6 knight can end up feeling misplaced and often needs to be rerouted. As such, it is a serious chance for White to fight for an advantage, and one we need to be ready for. }
5... dxc6
{ The setup I want to achieve is Be6, Bd6, and Nd7. then, Black can castle long. In general, I think he should be very happy to put the king on the queenside in all of these positions, as the 4 pawn cover is very safe.   White has tried a ton of different moves here, though I believe that the two most challenging by far are O-O and Nbd2. Our default next move is Bc8-e6, getting us closer to the ideal coordination. I don't spend much time here explaining how Black should play once he reaches the right setup, but we will see some examples in the illustrative games section. }
6. Be3
{ This used to be one of the main moves, but when we see that Black is often retreating Bc5-d6 voluntarily, it's not hard to see that here he should have a comfortable position. }
6... Bd6 7. h3
{ Black has tried a bunch of different moves here, but I like staying consistent with the main plan.   7.Nbd2?  Ng4!  Black grabs the second bishop and is already a bit better. }
7... Be6 8. O-O Qe7
{ Black is ready to castle long next. Then, he can consider h7-h6, both to prevent Nf3-g5 and to prepare g7-g5, and his kingside attack should play itself. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "The Berlin with 4.d3 and 5.Bxc6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6
{ This move looks a little strange, playing some kind of Exchange Spanish where Black has not had to burn a tempo on a7-a6. But, there is some logic to it. In a lot off lines in the Exchange Spanish, Black's knight actually wants to go to e7, and the bishop often wants to go to d6.   Surely Black can play Bc5-d6, claiming that playing Bf8-c5-d6 is not substantially worse than playing Bf8-d6 in one move but also spending a tempo on a7-a6, but the f6 knight can end up feeling misplaced and often needs to be rerouted. As such, it is a serious chance for White to fight for an advantage, and one we need to be ready for. }
5... dxc6
{ The setup I want to achieve is Be6, Bd6, and Nd7. then, Black can castle long. In general, I think he should be very happy to put the king on the queenside in all of these positions, as the 4 pawn cover is very safe.   White has tried a ton of different moves here, though I believe that the two most challenging by far are O-O and Nbd2. Our default next move is Bc8-e6, getting us closer to the ideal coordination. I don't spend much time here explaining how Black should play once he reaches the right setup, but we will see some examples in the illustrative games section. }
6. O-O
{ In recent years, this has emerged as the main move. It seems a little inflexible as there are some lines where White can consider castling queenside instead, but I find those to be less than threatening. The biggest point of castling right away is that White is now threatening to take on e5 for real since Qd4 is not coming in response, and this means Black is not in time to defend the e5 pawn with the ideal coordination of Be6 and Nd7. }
6... Bg4
{ Black has other moves, but I found this one to be the most satisfying. To be clear, I don't necessarily think the bishop is amazingly placed on g4. But, it gets it off of c8, which means he can defend the e5-pawn with Nf6-d7 next without blocking it in, and then the bishop will come back to e6 later. }
7. h3
{ Obviously, chasing the bishop is a critical move. It cannot go all the way back to g6. }
7... Bh5 8. g4 Nxg4
{ No choice on this one- we were not going to let White take on e5 for nothing. }
9. hxg4 Bxg4
{ Black is a piece down, but has an incredibly powerful pin on the f3-knight and White is badly missing his light squared bishop. f7-f5 is on the way. }
10. Be3 Be7
{ An important detail. Black cannot put the bishop on the generally more desirable d6 square because he needs the d-file open in one key variation. }
11. Kg2
{ This is a natural move. White looks to overprotect the f3-knight and then move the queen to break the pin. Black should be energetic. }
11... f5 12. Qe1
{ This position was featured in Leela vs Stockfish and Giri vs Tari. It quickly becomes a strange balance. }
12... Bxf3+ 13. Kxf3 f4 14. Bd2 g5
{ The following line is not forced, but illustrative. } 15. Bc3 Qd6 16. Nd2 Qe6
17. Ke2 h5 18. f3 g4 19. Nc4 Bf6 20. Rh1 O-O-O 21. Qf2 Kb8 22. Qg2 g3 23. Qh3
Qe7
{ Still following the machine vs machine encounter. Every engine insists the position is absolutely equal, and starts moving back and forth with both sides.   I thought for a long time about this position on my own, and I could not for the life of me find any kind of a plan for either side to make any progress- every time I tried, I would end up worsening my position. Time to just shuffle back and forth until a 3fold repetition, the 50 move rule, or of course wait for White to do something dumb! }
*

