[Black "The Berlin with 4.d3 and 5.Nbd2"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5
{ In this chapter, we will look at what happens if White chooses not to take on c6 and keeps the pawn structure unchanged, aiming to play something that looks a bit like an Italian. I don't find these options too scary. }
5. Nbd2
{ This move is actually quite annoying. Black is unable to play d7-d5 as I would like to, but if he castles short, then White will be able to take on c6 and reach the dxc6 structure where Black has already committed to castling short. There is not a single spot in that entire chapter where this would be my plan. }
5... O-O
{ Now, Black is ready for Nc6-d4 next without anything bad happening to him. If White prevents it with c2-c3, then d7-d5 transposes to the mainline, but Black also should be ready for Bb5xc6. }
6. Bxc6
{ This is the most challenging move. It is probably okay to take back with the d-pawn, but it gets to the kinds of positions I would really rather avoid. I only like the dxc6 structure for Black if he can castle long, and this is not the case here. So, we need to be a bit more ambitious.   6.c3  d5  Transposes to the mainline. }
6... bxc6
{ Black is ready to overprotect the e5-pawn with Rf8-e8 next, and then d7-d5 will come, and White can end up worse real quick. It really seems like White should go grab this pawn. }
7. Nxe5 Re8 8. Nef3
{ Now, Black needs to be very energetic to not just end up a clean pawn down. }
8... d5 9. O-O Bg4 10. h3 { White has never tried anything else. } 10... Bh5
11. e5 { This forces a draw. } 11... Rxe5 12. g4 Nxg4 13. Nxe5 Qh4 14. hxg4
Qg3+ { The game ends with a perpetual check. } *

