[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5
{ In this chapter, we will look at what happens if White chooses not to take on c6 and keeps the pawn structure unchanged, aiming to play something that looks a bit like an Italian. I don't find these options too scary. }
5. c3
{ This is the main move by far, which I recently used to beat Shahkriyar Mamedyarov, and it has been recommended by Nils Grandelius in his own recent Chessable course. }
5... d5 { I like striking in the center right away. } 6. exd5
{ This is the most critical move, and the recommendation of Nils Grandelius in his course here on Chessable. Black should be ready, but he is certainly fine. }
6... Qxd5 7. Bc4 Qd6 8. b4
{ This is a very serious attempt for White. He immediately goes chasing the bishop. }
8... Bb6 9. a4 { 9.Nbd2  Bf5  Transposesto 8.Nbd2. } 9... O-O
{ Now things get very forcing. } 10. Nbd2 Bf5 { Very energetic. } 11. Ba3
{ White now has a ton of threats, b4-b5 being the biggest one. Black should be very direct.   11.Qe2  e4!  White is still not prepared for the center to open like this. }
11... e4 { Now the next few moves are absolutely forced. } 12. dxe4 Nxe4 13.
Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Qxd6 cxd6 15. O-O-O { Definitely the most challenging. } 15...
Rac8 16. Bd5 { This is main by far but Black should also be ready for Bc4-b3. }
16... Bxd5 17. Rxd5 Ne5 { Black simplifies the position to equality. } 18. Nxe5
dxe5 19. Kb2
{ Black still needs to be careful here. If White is allowed to slam a rook onto the seventh rank, there could be some real problems, as his queenside pawn mass is more advanced than Black's 4 on 3 in the kingside/center. }
19... Rfd8 20. Rxe5 Rxc3
{ An important resource. The position is now symmetrical, and Black equalizes thanks to the fork on d4. }
