{  } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5
{ In this chapter, we will look at what happens if White chooses not to take on c6 and keeps the pawn structure unchanged, aiming to play something that looks a bit like an Italian. I don't find these options too scary. }
5. c3
{ This is the main move by far, which I recently used to beat Shahkriyar Mamedyarov, and it has been recommended by Nils Grandelius in his own recent Chessable course. }
5... d5 { I like striking in the center right away. } 6. Nbd2
{ This is the move White normally plays if he just wants to get a position with pieces on the board, and Black still has some work to do before he can claim full equality since the knight on c6 is a little misplaced. }
6... dxe4 7. dxe4 O-O 8. O-O
{ Now, I think Black should prevent White from gaining space with b2-b4. } 8...
a5 9. Bxc6
{ Of course, we should be ready for White taking the pawn, but it is nothing to be scared of. }
9... bxc6 10. Nxe5 Re8 { Natural enough. } 11. Nb3
{ This has been the favorite as of late, but I have no idea why. } 11... Qxd1
12. Rxd1 Bb6 13. Nc4 Nxe4 14. Nxb6 cxb6
{ I absolutely do not care that the machine gives White some 0.2 here. Symmetrical structure, equal pawns, opposite bishops... This is obviously a draw. }
