[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "The Berlin with 6.Nxe5 7.Bd3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1
{ This is a very safe move for White, and is frequently the one chosen by well prepared players who are looking to take no risks at all. Unlike some of White's other quiet and risk free attempts, this one is not entirely toothless, and Black will have to know his stuff reasonably well to equalize because his pieces start out a little uncoordinated. }
5... Nd6 6. Nxe5
{ 6.Bf1  Be7  White has nothing better than taking on e5, transposing to the mainlines.   6.Ba4  Be7  7.d4  e4  8.Ne5  Transposes tothe 5.d4 sidelines chapter. }
6... Be7 7. Bd3
{ This retreat has been seen from time to time. It is a much more aggressive option for White, who is looking to launch a direct kingside attack with some combination of b2-b3, Bc1-b2, and Qd1-h5, when Black will obviously have to pay some attention to not get mated. But, it also blocks in the d-pawn and is a strategically dubious decision, so if Black doesn't get mated, he should be in good shape. And as far as I can tell, he does not get mated. }
7... Nxe5 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. Nc3 c6
{ Black prevents the knight from reaching d5. Next up, he will regroup with Nd6-e8 and d7-d5, a theme that will be seen a lot in the Re1 chapter. }
10. b3
{ 10.Qf3  Ne8  White has only ever played  11.b3  here, transposing to the 10.b3 lines. }
10... Ne8 { An important move. } 11. Bb2 d5
{ White's position looks very menacing, with seemingly all of his pieces ready to jump on the black kingside, but concretely, there is nothing to worry about. Black will kick the rook away with Be7-d6, and then can consider g7-g6 and Ne8-g7 to keep everything rock solid. Eventually, taking more space in the center may count for something. }
12. Qf3 Bd6 { Black executes his plan. } 13. Re2
{ It's tempting to try to double on the e-file, but White now is actually in big trouble. }
13... Qh4 14. h3 Nc7 { Who is attacking who? } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "The Berlin with 6.Nxe5 7.Bf1 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1
{ This is a very safe move for White, and is frequently the one chosen by well prepared players who are looking to take no risks at all. Unlike some of White's other quiet and risk free attempts, this one is not entirely toothless, and Black will have to know his stuff reasonably well to equalize because his pieces start out a little discoordinated. }
5... Nd6 6. Nxe5
{ 6.Bf1  Be7  White has nothing better than taking on e5, transposing to the mainline.   6.Ba4  Be7  7.d4  e4  8.Ne5  Transposes to the 5.d4 sidelines chapter. }
6... Be7 7. Bf1
{ Now, the structure resembles the ED variation of the French Defense, which stands for exd5 and only exd5 and nothing else that might be abbreviated to ED. But, there is a key difference here. Black's knight on d6 is obviously misplaced, as it prevents his d-pawn from moving forward. One bad piece makes a bad position, and if Black can fix the problem knight, he should be absolutely fine. But, White can try to prevent this from happening. }
7... Nxe5
{ Before anything else, Black should trade off the e5-knight before White can push d2-d4 to take back with the pawn. }
8. Rxe5 O-O
{ Now, if Black is able to play Nd6-e8 and d7-d5, he will equalize easily. White has to do something to try to stop this from happening. }
9. d4
{ This is the main move. White is hoping to advance d4-d5 before Black can play d7-d5 himself. }
9... Bf6
{ It is possible to play Ne8 instead, but I am not convinced that Black will equalize after d4-d5. I like being a bit more direct. }
10. Re1 Re8
{ An important move. Black offers the exchange of rooks, and White doesn't have a great response. Taking on e8 will allow Black to recapture with the knight to get d7-d5 in next, and allowing Rxe1+ instead coule cost him the d4-pawn. }
11. c3
{ This is the most common and most solid move, but it's pretty soft and should fizzle to equality soon enough. After }
11... Rxe1 12. Qxe1 Ne8
{ Black is ready for d7-d5 next, and White is not ready to play d4-d5 himself. So, Black should be fine. }
13. Nd2 d5 14. Nf3 Bf5
{ Black is quite fine, with c7-c6 and Ne8-c7-e6 coming next. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "The Berlin with 6.Nxe5 7.Bf1 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1
{ This is a very safe move for White, and is frequently the one chosen by well prepared players who are looking to take no risks at all. Unlike some of White's other quiet and risk free attempts, this one is not entirely toothless, and Black will have to know his stuff reasonably well to equalize because his pieces start out a little discoordinated. }
5... Nd6 6. Nxe5
{ 6.Bf1  Be7  White has nothing better than taking on e5, transposing to the mainlines.   6.Ba4  Be7  7.d4  e4  8.Ne5  Transposes to the 5.d4 sidelines chapter. }
6... Be7 7. Bf1
{ Now, the structure resembles the ED variation of the French Defense, which stands for exd5 and only exd5 and nothing else that might be abbreviated to ED. But, there is a key difference here. Black's knight on d6 is obviously misplaced, as it prevents his d-pawn from moving forward.   One bad piece makes a bad position, and if Black can fix the problem knight, he should be absolutely fine. But, White can try to prevent this from happening. }
7... Nxe5
{ Before anything else, Black should trade off the e5-knight before White can push d2-d4 to take back with the pawn. }
8. Rxe5 O-O
{ Now, if Black is able to play Nd6-e8 and d7-d5, he will equalize easily. White has to do something to try to stop this from happening. }
9. d4
{ This is the main move. White is hoping to advance d4-d5 before Black can play d7-d5 himself. }
9... Bf6
{ It is possible to play Ne8 instead, but I am not convinced that Black will equalize after d4-d5. I like being a bit more direct. }
10. Re1 Re8
{ An important move. Black offers the exchange of rooks, and White doesn't have a great response. Taking on e8 will allow Black to recapture with the knight to get d7-d5 in next, and allowing Rxe1+ instead coule cost him the d4-pawn. }
11. Nc3
{ This is probably White's most challenging option. He brings his pieces out as fast as possible, hoping to take advantage of his lead in development while Black is busy fixing his d6-knight by retreating it to the back rank. }
11... Rxe1 12. Qxe1
{ Now, we are not in time to play the strategically desirable Nd6-e8, as White is too fast with Nc3-d5 in response. So we have to go pawn grabbing. }
12... Bxd4 13. Bf4 Ne8 14. Nd5
{ White is playing very energetically, and it is not too hard to imagine Black getting smashed by some combination of Qe4, Re1, and Bd3. Black should be very careful here. }
14... c6 15. Ne7+
{ 15.Rd1?!  Bc5!  The ship has sailed on Nd5-e7+, and White has to find some funky moves to not become worse. }
15... Kf8 16. Nxc8
{ Now, it looks like all is well in the world for White. Once Black takes back on c8, either Qe4 or Qb4 will recapture the lost pawn and leave him with a crushing position thanks to his lead in development and healthy bishop pair. Black has to play very energetically and precisely to stay in the game, but he is quite fine if he does. }
16... Qf6
{ A very important move. Black activates the queen and makes trouble on f2 before taking back the doomed knight on c8. }
17. Qb4+ { This is the most challenging move. } 17... c5 18. Qd2
{ Provoking the pawn to c5 makes it harder for Black's bishop to remain on the excellent a7-g1 diagonal. }
18... Rxc8 19. Re1
{ Now, Black's bishop is in some danger or being trapped after c2-c3. He needs to remember one final accurate move to equalize. }
19... g5
{ It is important to flick this move in, pushing White's bishop back to g3 with a gain of tempo. Then, he will be able to play d7-d6 and Bd4-e5 without fearing for the bishop's safety after a subsequent f2-f4. }
20. Bxg5 Bxf2+ 21. Qxf2 Qxg5
{ White has full compensation for the pawn, but certainly nothing more. Black is ready for Nd6 and Re8 next, and he need not fear much for his king's safety thanks to the reduced material. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "The Berlin Endgame: 9.Rd1+"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5
8. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ This is the start of the Berlin Endgame, and in my opinion, White's best try to fight for an edge. The position is more unbalanced than the symmetrical structures we frequently come across in other lines, and both sides have their trumps.   Black has a healthy bishop pair and the e5-pawn is overextended, while White enjoys a better long term pawn structure as the 4 on 3 queenside majority is unable to give Black a passed pawn under normal circumstances, and White has a big lead in development. The endgame is very complex, and Black has several plans at his disposal for how to arrange his pieces.   The biggest question is what Black will do with his king, which surely cannot remain on d8. The most double edged plans involve trying to play Bd7 and Kc8, while the most solid ones tend to see Black's king going kingside instead. There's a long list of reasons I chose to recommend a plan with Ke8, but the biggest one is that it is much easier to be consistent and not have to remember a lot of move order tricks.   Generally speaking, the plan for Black is to play Ke8, Be7, and Be6. This may seem a bit risky upon a surface level examination because White will be able to play Bg5, halving the bishop pair.   It is very important to note that the inclusion of h2-h3 and h7-h5 is heavily in Black's favor when the resulting positions arise, and he should be a bit wary of allowing the bishop exchange if White has not included these moves. We will see a lot more strategic ideas later on down the lines, but this is a good place to start. }
9. Rd1+
{ This is a reasonably common move, and a very sensible one if White does not want our king to go to c8. For our repertoire, this is not a real appeal for him since we are going to e8 anyway, but it still has some points to it. }
9... Ke8 10. Nc3
{ Now, Black is in a little bit of a tough spot. Since White has not played h2-h3, I really dislike playing Bf8-e7 and allowing a bishop exchange on g5. I think those positions can be quite dangerous for him if h2-h3 and h7-h5 has not been included. But, he has another option that I quite like. }
10... Ne7
{ Since White has not committed to h3, we have to do a different plan. Luckily, I think this is a very good version for Black. Normally, White's best option against the Ne7-g6 regrouping involves playing Ra1-d1 rather than Rf1-d1, and then he can play moves like Nf3-d4 and f2-f4-f5. Since he already committed the f-rook to d1, that ship has sailed. }
11. h3
{ Now this move makes perfect sense. Normally, the inclusion of h2-h3 and h7-h5 is double edged, as it weakens the g5-square for Black but also gives him the option of h5-h4 to clamp down on the kingside structure. Now, Black can't quite get away with h7-h5 since Bc1-g5 will cause major problems. But, he should have a fine position all the same. }
11... Ng6 12. b3
{ Kamsky played this against me once, but as always, I really don't think the bishop on b2 makes any sense against the king on e8. }
12... Bd7 13. Bb2 Rd8
{ Black has an easy plan to put the knight on e6 and the bishop on e7, and White has no sensible way to try to make progress.   We'll see my aforementionedencounter with Kamsky in the illustrative games section. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "The Berlin Endgame: 9.h3 with 11.Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5
8. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ This is the start of the Berlin Endgame, and in my opinion, White's best try to fight for an edge. The position is more unbalanced than the symmetrical structures we frequently come across in other lines, and both sides have their trumps.   Black has a healthy bishop pair and the e5-pawn is overextended, while White enjoys a better long term pawn structure as the 4 on 3 queenside majority is unable to give Black a passed pawn under normal circumstances, and White has a big lead in development. The endgame is very complex, and Black has several plans at his disposal for how to arrange his pieces.   The biggest question is what Black will do with his king, which surely cannot remain on d8. The most double edged plans involve trying to play Bd7 and Kc8, while the most solid ones tend to see Black's king going kingside instead. There's a long list of reasons I chose to recommend a plan with Ke8, but the biggest one is that it is much easier to be consistent and not have to remember a lot of move order tricks.   Generally speaking, the plan for Black is to play Ke8, Be7, and Be6. This may seem a bit risky upon a surface level examination because White will be able to play Bg5, halving the bishop pair.   It is very important to note that the inclusion of h2-h3 and h7-h5 is heavily in Black's favor when the resulting positions arise, and he should be a bit wary of allowing the bishop exchange if White has not included these moves. We will see a lot more strategic ideas later on down the lines, but this is a good place to start. }
9. h3
{ In recent years, this has become the main move as it is White's best way to play against Black's plans involving Bd7 and Kc8. That is entirely irrelevant to us as our whole plan is to play with Ke8 anyway. }
9... Ke8
{ Same move every time.   9...h5  There is nothing wrong with this move order either, but I like starting with  Ke8  just for simplicity's sake.  Playing Ke8 against every single move just makes one less thing to remember. }
10. Nc3 h5
{ Black prevents g4, and can look to complete his development with some combination of Be7 and Be6, or potentially b6 and Bb7, depending on what White does.   According to my database, White has tried 12 different moves here. It is senseless to try to memorize all of them. What we need to do instead is look at the most critical ones, understand the subtle differences between moves like Bf4, Bg5, Rd1 first and then Bg5, serious moves like these, and then just trust ourselves to play the positions well once we understand the key themes if White resorts to something silly like Bd2 or a4 without burdening our memory any further. }
11. Bg5
{ This is a very natural move now that h7-h6 is not a thing any more. White prevents Be7 for the moment, but there is also has a drawback. Black can bring his bishop to e6 without fear of Ng5. }
11... Be6 12. Rad1
{ In general, I think White should be putting the a-rook on d1.   12.Rfd1  Transposesto 11.Rd1. }
12... Be7 13. Bxe7 Kxe7
{ It is very important to understand why Black has a totally acceptable position here when on the surface, it looks like he should be worse because he has lost his bishop pair, has no major counterplay, and White has retained the better long term pawn structure.   It all comes down to the move h2-h3. Once Black plays h5-h4, White's supposedly healthy kingside pawn structure will be every bit as unable to make a passed pawn as Black's majority on the queenside is. Had the pawn stood on h2 instead, White would have a long term plan of f2-f4, Kg1-f2, g2-g3, h2-h3, g3-g4, etc. }
14. Rd2 Rad8 { I like trading one pair of rooks here. } 15. Rfd1 Rxd2 16. Rxd2
h4
{ There is no way on earth White can ever get his kingside majority moving. The pawn on h3 ruins any chance of advancing g2-g4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "The Berlin Endgame: 9.h3 with 11.Bf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5
8. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ This is the start of the Berlin Endgame, and in my opinion, White's best try to fight for an edge. The position is more unbalanced than the symmetrical structures we frequently come across in other lines, and both sides have their trumps.   Black has a healthy bishop pair and the e5-pawn is overextended, while White enjoys a better long term pawn structure as the 4 on 3 queenside majority is unable to give Black a passed pawn under normal circumstances, and White has a big lead in development. The endgame is very complex, and Black has several plans at his disposal for how to arrange his pieces.   The biggest question is what Black will do with his king, which surely cannot remain on d8. The most double edged plans involve trying to play Bd7 and Kc8, while the most solid ones tend to see Black's king going kingside instead. There's a long list of reasons I chose to recommend a plan with Ke8, but the biggest one is that it is much easier to be consistent and not have to remember a lot of move order tricks.   Generally speaking, the plan for Black is to play Ke8, Be7, and Be6. This may seem a bit risky upon a surface level examination because White will be able to play Bg5, halving the bishop pair.   It is very important to note that the inclusion of h2-h3 and h7-h5 is heavily in Black's favor when the resulting positions arise, and he should be a bit wary of allowing the bishop exchange if White has not included these moves. We will see a lot more strategic ideas later on down the lines, but this is a good place to start. }
9. h3
{ In recent years, this has become the main move as it is White's best way to play against Black's plans involving Bd7 and Kc8. That is entirely irrelevant to us as our whole plan is to play with Ke8 anyway. }
9... Ke8
{ Same move every time.   9...h5  There is nothing wrong with this move order either, but I like starting with  Ke8  just for simplicity's sake.  Playing Ke8 against every single move just makes one less thing to remember. }
10. Nc3 h5
{ Black prevents g4, and can look to complete his development with some combination of Be7 and Be6, or potentially b6 and Bb7, depending on what White does.   According to my database, White has tried 12 different moves here. It is senseless to try to memorize all of them. What we need to do instead is look at the most critical ones, understand the subtle differences between moves like Bf4, Bg5, Rd1 first and then Bg5, serious moves like these, and then just trust ourselves to play the positions well once we understand the key themes if White resorts to something silly like Bd2 or a4 without burdening our memory any further. }
11. Bf4
{ This is the main move by some margin. White can't count on anything by exchanging the dark squared bishops, so he makes sure to keep the g5-square clear for his knight instead, aiming to destabilize the light squared bishop when it inevitably comes to e6. }
11... Be7 12. Rad1 { This is the main move by a lot. } 12... Be6
{ Now, since White has the d4-square under control, he is able to play Ng5 directly without having to worry about Nd4 in response. }
13. Ng5
{ White harasses the e6-bishop, and Black cannot take on g5. But, he has a nice resource to activate a piece that otherwise tends to have trouble joining the game when Black brings the king to e8. }
13... Rh6 14. g3
{ This was an old main move that has since mostly been forgotten in favor of Rfe1, but it is still challenging and Black should know his stuff. }
14... Bxg5
{ Now this is possible because Black can kick the bishop off of the all-important diagonal. }
15. Bxg5 Rg6 16. h4
{ If Black were to twiddle his thumbs and wait for even one move, he would immediately lose the game to Ne2. Furthermore, White could also simply double on the d-file and basically deliver mate. Strategically, taking on g5 is a very poor decision, but luckily a direct move saves the day. }
16... f6 17. exf6 gxf6 18. Bf4 Nxh4 19. f3
{ White has tried this position several times at a high level, including a notable game from one of the Carlsen-Anand matches. It's a little uncomfortable for Black but he should hold with a couple decent moves. }
19... Rd8
{ We often see that in the Berlin endgame with the king on e8, Black is very happy to trade off the passive a8-rook. }
20. Kf2 { White breaks the pin with a gain of tempo. } 20... Rxd1
{ An important resource. Black should take d1 right now to prevent White from taking back with the rook. }
21. Nxd1 Nf5 22. Rh1 Bxa2 { Black can and should take this pawn. } 23. Rxh5 Be6
{ Now, all Black needs to remember to comfortably hold is that he should play Rh6 whenever given the option, and not to worry about the c7-pawn. }
24. g4 { 24.Bxc7  Rh6!  Case in point, this is a dead draw. } 24... Nd6 25. Rh7
{ Black still has to be a little careful, though it has to be said that he has multiple ways to hang on. I like sticking with the main principle- get ready for Rh6, and don't bother about the c7-pawn. }
25... Nf7 26. Ne3 b6
{ I am at a loss for how White can do anything useful. In order to mobilize his kingside he will need to get the bishop off of f4, and the second it leaves, Rh6 comes. Black is making an easy draw. }
