1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4
{ The Center Game is not as dumb as it might appear. Sure, White will lose a tempo with his queen, but only one. Then she can sit comfortably on e3 and White can hope to castle long. Still, Black has to be fine, and the mainline is an easy solution. }
3... Nc6 4. Qe3 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 6. Bd2 O-O 7. O-O-O Re8
{ White will struggle to defend his e4-pawn, and he should probably sacrifice it to try to get some attacking chances. Still, I don't think he will equalize. }
8. Qf4
{ This is the modern trend that Nepo has been playing a bit. It makes more sense in the mainline with Qg3 because Black seemingly has to give up the bishop pair on c3 in order to win the e4-pawn, but I think there is a nice alternative available. }
8... Ne5
{ Black is ready for Ng6 next, when White's queen will rapidly run out of squares. }
9. h4
{ This is the machine's recommendation, making room for the queen on h2. After }
9... Ng6 10. Qh2 Nxe4
{ Black was able to clip the e4-pawn without allowing White an unopposed dark squared bishop. }
11. h5 Nf8
{ White got more play than he would in the mainline with 8.Qg3, but I really can't believe he has enough for a pawn here and the attack doesn't look that scary with all the pieces on the back rank. }
*

