1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4
{ I think this is known as the Vienna Gambit, but much like the King's Gambit, I like striking in the center directly.   3.d4  exd4  4.Qxd4  Nc6  5.Qe3  Bb4  Transposes to 2.d4.   3.Bc4  Nc6  Transposes to the 2.Bc4 move order. }
3... d5 4. exd5
{ This can get funky, but White has a lot more to worry about than Black does. }
4... Nxd5 5. fxe5 { 5.Nf3  exf4  Transposes to the King's Gambit. } 5... Nxc3
6. dxc3 Qh4+ 7. Kd2 Qg5+ { Nice and simple. } 8. Ke1 Qxe5+ 9. Qe2 Qxe2+
{ Black gets a reverse Berlin Endgame where he managed to trade off the lousy e-pawn and still has the bishop pair. Seems easy enough to me. }
*

