{ I think this is known as the Vienna Gambit, but much like the King's Gambit, I like striking in the center directly.   3.d4  exd4  4.Qxd4  Nc6  5.Qe3  Bb4  Transposes to 2.d4.   3.Bc4  Nc6  Transposes to the 2.Bc4 move order. }
3... d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Qf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 Nxc3 7. dxc3
{ Now, Black needs to know an important maneuvre to keep a nice position. Funnily enough, I had no clue of its existence until a 9 year old student under 1000 told me about it! }
7... Qh4+ 8. g3 Qe4+ 9. Qxe4 dxe4
{ Black is ready for Bd7 and O-O-O next.   Bringing the pawn to e4 means White cannot play Nf3 and will struggle to defend e5. Plus, provoking g2-g3 means that h5-h4 can be a very problematic resource to deal with. Black is already a little more comfortable. }
