[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ The King's Gambit always has had a special place in chess history, with romantic games of wild king hunts being shown to children in their first chess classes every day. But unfortunately, there is not much place for it in modern chess. }
2... d5
{ Taking f4 is surely fine, but this strikes me as easier and more direct. White will be afforded absolutely no attacking chances. }
3. exd5
{ 3.Nf3  exf4  White needs to take on d5, transposing to the mainline. } 3...
exf4 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ Now, if Black is allowed tot ake back on d5 with the knight, he will be able to hold onto his f4-pawn with a bit more force. White usually tries to bolster the pawn with c2-c4 or to force its exchange with Bf1-bb5+, but neither move impresses. }
5. Bc4 Nxd5 6. O-O
{ This is a somewhat better version for White than it would be with d2-d4 instead of O-O, but still, Black is in good shape. }
6... Be6 7. Qe2 Nc6 8. d4 Qd6
{ As usual, I like castling long when White allows Nxd5. } 9. Nbd2 O-O-O 10.
Ne4 Qe7
{ White will struggle to get the f4 pawn back without losing the bishop pair, and h7-h6 and g7-g5 is coming. }
*

