1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ The King's Gambit always has had a special place in chess history, with romantic games of wild king hunts being shown to children in their first chess classes every day. But unfortunately, there is not much place for it in modern chess. }
2... d5
{ Taking f4 is surely fine, but this strikes me as easier and more direct. White will be afforded absolutely no attacking chances. }
3. exd5
{ 3.Nf3  exf4  White needs to take on d5, transposing to the mainline. } 3...
exf4 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ Now, if Black is allowed to take back on d5 with the knight, he will be able to hold onto his f4-pawn with a bit more force. White usually tries to bolster the pawn with c2-c4 or to force its exchange with Bf1-b5+, but neither move impresses. }
5. Bb5+
{ This forces us to allow White to trade off the weak d5-pawn, but still the position ends up quite nice. We get to keep f4. }
5... c6 6. dxc6 Nxc6 7. d4 Bd6
{ Material is equal, but keeping the f4-pawn alive restricts White's pieces significantly, and Black can plan a kingside attack of his own after O-O, h6, and g5. }
*

