{ 3.Nc3  Nc6  4.Nf3   4.a3  Na5  Transposes.  4...Nxe4!  Transposes tothe Four Knights.   3.d4?  This leads to a bad version of the Italian sidelines chapter for White.  3...exd4  4.e5  d5-+  Black is already much better, as his knight is not yet committed to c6. He is ready for Nfd7 next and White is falling dangerously behind on development. }
3... Nc6
{ I see no reason to avoid this move. White should probably play Ng1-f3, transposing to the Italian, but he does have a couple of extra options. }
4. Nc3
{ Now, Black can go bishop grabbing.   4.Nf3  Bc5  Takes us to the Italian. }
4... Na5 5. Nge2
{ Now, one key point is I think Black should not rush to take on c4. The bishop is not going anywhere, and White's queen would not mind getting the d3 square.   Wait for White to push a2-a3 or a2-a4, and once the bishop is threatening to escape, then we take it. This will force White to spend a tempo on his a-pawn rather than developing his pieces. }
5... c6 6. a4 Nxc4
{ Of course, we grab the bishop once it is threatening to move. } 7. dxc4
{ Now, Black has a simple development scheme with Bf8-c5, O-O, and d7-d6. }
7... Bc5 8. O-O O-O 9. Qd3
{ If we had this position with White to move and his pawn back on a2, he would be ready for Bc1-e3 and a rook to d1 before we could comfortably defend the d6 pawn. As is, it is our move, and Black is in time to consolidate. }
9... d6 10. Be3 Bxe3 11. Qxe3 Qb6
{ Black is easily fine with good squares for all of his pieces. This is exactly the kind of position I mean when we see that a2-a4 was less useful than a rook coming to d1- that would be a different story! }
*

