[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 3 - Four Knights"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3
{ In this chapter, we will cover the Four Knights variation. The positions have a high tendency to be very equal and drawish, as White is not doing anything to try to break the symmetry. }
3... Nf6
{ Now, White's most challenging move is surely  4.Bb5  , when we will have to remember some key lines.   4.d4  tends to lead to pretty dry positions where Black is fine, but should be careful about not getting too ambitious.  Any move other than Bb5 or d4 will likely be met with d7-d5.   Then, we will have the same kind of dry equal positions as we see when White plays 4.d4, but with colors reversed. They remain playable from that side as well, as they are generally very equal. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 3 - Four Knights"]
[Black "Four Knights: 4.Bc4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ Now, of course, White's three main moves by far are Bb5, Bc4, and d4. But, he does have some extraneous options, including the notorious Four Knights variation. }
3. Nc3 Nf6
{ It really says a lot about how much White is grasping at straws against lines like the Berlin and Petroff that he is sometimes looking in this direction even at top level chess. The symmetrical nature of the position is hard to break.   Now, the two main moves by far are  4.d4  and  4.Bb5  ,  but there are some other options Black should be ready for too. In general, he will be looking to meet most silly looking moves with d7-d5, and quite a few silly looking moves have been tried here! }
4. Bc4 { This allows a nice trick to give Black a big share of the center. }
4... Nxe4 5. Bxf7+ Kxf7 6. Nxe4 d5 7. Neg5+ Kg8
{ Black's skeptical looking king is hardly an issue, and the big pawn center is completely decisive. }
*

