[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 3 - Four Knights"]
[Black "Four Knights: 4.a4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ Now, of course White's three main moves by far are Bb5, Bc4, and d4. But, he does have some extraneous options, including the notorious 4 knights variation. }
3. Nc3 Nf6
{ It really says a lot about how much White is grasping at straws against lines like the Berlin and Petroff that he is sometimes looking in this direction even at top level chess. The symmetrical nature of the position is hard to break.   Now, the two main moves by far are  4.d4  and  4.Bb5  ,  but there are some other options Black should be ready for too. In general, he will be looking to meet most silly looking moves with d7-d5, and quite a few silly looking moves have been tried here! }
4. a4
{ This move looks absurd to me, but anything Magnus plays, even in rapid, needs to be taken seriously. But I am not sure I understand what his big idea is. We continue along with the normal move order.   4.a3  d5!  d7-d5 is our default next move if White does something silly looking, and this is no exception. }
4... d5 5. Bb5 { This is a little tricky but nothing we can't handle. } 5...
Nxe4 6. Nxe5 Qf6
{ An important move. White's menacing looking knight is forced backwards. } 7.
Nf3 Be6 { With Bd6 and O-O coming next, Black is easily and obviously fine. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 3 - Four Knights"]
[Black "Four Knights: 4.Be2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ Now, of course White's three main moves by far are Bb5, Bc4, and d4. But, he does have some extraneous options, including the notorious 4 knights variation. }
3. Nc3 Nf6
{ It really says a lot about how much White is grasping at straws against lines like the Berlin and Petroff that he is sometimes looking in this direction even at top level chess. The symmetrical nature of the position is hard to break.   Now, the two main moves by far are  4.d4  and  4.Bb5  ,  but there are some other options Black should be ready for too. In general, he will be looking to meet most silly looking moves with d7-d5, and quite a few silly looking moves have been tried here! }
4. Be2
{ This move is actually trickier than it looks. White has not given up on the plan of d2-d4, and wants to wait for Black to burn a tempo with his f8-bishop going to a square other than b4. But, we can beat him to the punch.   4.g3  d5  5.exd5  Nxd5  6.Bg2  Nxc3  7.bxc3  Transposes to theSecond Move Sidelines chapter, 2.Nc3. }
4... d5 5. exd5 Nxd5
{ Black has taken a big share of the center, and the threat of Nd5xc3 followed by e5-e4 should be enough to convince White to play Be2-b5, effectively giving us the white side of the 4.d4 positions. }
6. Bb5 Nxc3 7. bxc3 Bd6
{ Now, we are playing White. We are playing a toothless variation, but an equal one, and we are playing the white side of it. This is easily enough for comfortable equality. }
8. d4 exd4 9. cxd4 O-O 10. O-O Bg4
{ With Qf6 to come next, this position has been seen countless times and we will also be playing it with colors reversed. It is extremely equal. }
*

