[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ Now, of course White's three main moves by far are Bb5, Bc4, and d4. But, he does have some extraneous options, including the notorious 4 knights variation. }
3. Nc3 Nf6
{ It really says a lot about how much White is grasping at straws against lines like the Berlin and Petroff that he is sometimes looking in this direction even at top level chess. The symmetrical nature of the position is hard to break.   Now, the two main moves by far are  4.d4  and  4.Bb5  ,  but there are some other options Black should be ready for too. In general, he will be looking to meet most silly looking moves with d7-d5, and quite a few silly looking moves have been tried here! }
4. Be2
{ This move is actually trickier than it looks. White has not given up on the plan of d2-d4, and wants to wait for Black to burn a tempo with his f8-bishop going to a square other than b4. But, we can beat him to the punch.   4.g3  d5  5.exd5  Nxd5  6.Bg2  Nxc3  7.bxc3  Transposes to the 2.Nc3 chapter. }
4... d5 5. exd5 Nxd5
{ Black has taken a big share of the center, and the threat of Nd5xc3 followed by e5-e4 should be enough to convince White to play Be2-b5, effectively giving us the white side of the 4.d4 positions. }
6. O-O Nxc3 7. bxc3 e4 8. Ne1 f5
{ I like this modern twist. Most of the time Bf8-d6 is played, which is surely a fine move, but my point is that now we can meet f2-f3 with Bf8-c5+ instead, and White will not be able to prevent us from castling. Any other move will be met with Bf8-d6. I like this added flexibility, and I already prefer Black. }
