[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ Now, of course White's three main moves by far are Bb5, Bc4, and d4. But, he does have some extraneous options, including the notorious 4 knights variation. }
3. Nc3 Nf6
{ It really says a lot about how much White is grasping at straws against lines like the Berlin and Petroff that he is sometimes looking in this direction even at top level chess. The symmetrical nature of the position is hard to break.   Now, the two main moves by far are  4.d4  and  4.Bb5  ,  but there are some other options Black should be ready for too. In general, he will be looking to meet most silly looking moves with d7-d5, and quite a few silly looking moves have been tried here! }
4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5
{ This tricky move is not quite as dumb as it looks, but Black is still in great shape. Black has a surprisingly powerful move in response. }
5... Nb4
{ I like this move, challenging the d5-knight directly. White does not really want to take on either f6 or b4, but what else can he do? }
6. Bc4 Nbxd5
{ Black takes with the right knight. His whole point behind Nc6-b4 was to challenge the d5-knight without losing time thanks to his c6-knight getting attacked after e4xd5. }
7. exd5 Bb4+
{ Black remains a pawn up, and is not behind in development. White should be precise to hang on. }
8. Bd2 Qe7+ { I like continuing to harass White's king before he can castle. }
9. Qe2 Bxd2+ { Now, we start trading. } 10. Kxd2 Qxe2+ 11. Kxe2
{ If White could take back on d4 next, I suppose you could argue he has a space advantage, though even that is not scary. Still, I like making him work for it. }
11... c5
{ Now Black will keep his extra pawn if White does not capture en passant. }
12. dxc6 bxc6
{ Black can already ambitiously capture towards the center and avoid the dry symmetry that would arise after dxc6 instead. }
13. Nxd4 d5
{ Black is ready for c6-c5 next, taking more space in the center. White is in no position to take advantage of the hanging pawns, and thanks to the absense of queens, Black can run his king up to d6 rather than castling. }
*

