1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ Now, of course White's three main moves by far are Bb5, Bc4, and d4. But, he does have some extraneous options, including the notorious 4 knights variation. }
3. Nc3 Nf6
{ It really says a lot about how much White is grasping at straws against lines like the Berlin and Petroff that he is sometimes looking in this direction even at top level chess. The symmetrical nature of the position is hard to break.   Now, the two main moves by far are  4.d4  and  4.Bb5  ,  but there are some other options Black should be ready for too. In general, he will be looking to meet most silly looking moves with d7-d5, and quite a few silly looking moves have been tried here! }
4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4
{ Now, White is forced to take on c6 directly to avoid losing a pawn. } 6. Bg5
h6
{ Forcing White to lose the pawn anyway, or to give up a very healthy bishop pair. }
7. Bh4 { Now, Black can and should break the pin to win the e4-pawn. } 7... g5
8. Bg3 { Now that the knight is free, e4 is ripe for the taking. } 8... Nxe4 9.
Nxc6 { White's only chance to show any compensation. } 9... bxc6 10. Qd4
{ This looks scary as White's queen is attacking 3 pieces, but we can get out of it easily enough. }
10... Bxc3+
{ First, we exchange off the hanging bishop, then we castle to clear the rook off of the hanging square and indirectly save the knight next. }
11. bxc3 O-O
{ The knight on e4 is immune, and it is up to White to show his compensation. This is not so easy to do as his king is no safer than Black's, either in the center or on the queenside. }
