[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ Now, of course White's three main moves by far are Bb5, Bc4, and d4. But, he does have some extraneous options, including the notorious 4 knights variation. }
3. Nc3 Nf6
{ It really says a lot about how much White is grasping at straws against lines like the Berlin and Petroff that he is sometimes looking in this direction even at top level chess. The symmetrical nature of the position is hard to break.   Now, the two main moves by far are  4.d4  and  4.Bb5  ,  but there are some other options Black should be ready for too. In general, he will be looking to meet most silly looking moves with d7-d5, and quite a few silly looking moves have been tried here! }
4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4
{ Now, White is forced to take on c6 directly to avoid losing a pawn. } 6. Nxc6
{ 6.Bd3?  Nxd4  Oops. } 6... bxc6 7. Bd3
{ Now, White would have a nice position if he could consolidate his center, but we are just in time to get castled and push d7-d5. }
7... O-O 8. O-O
{ Now, Black should not miss his last chance to stake his own spot in the center. }
8... d5 9. exd5 Bg4
{ There is nothing wrong with taking back cxd5 instead, and we will play that position with colors reversed in other lines, but somehow the white side feels just a tiny bit more comfortable to me. I like being very direct and forcing. }
10. Ne2 cxd5
{ Black has a very solid and easy position. Exchanging Bg4 for Ne2 has to be in his favor. }
