8... d5 9. exd5 Bg4
{ There is nothing wrong with taking back cxd5 instead, and we will play that position with colors reversed in other lines, but somehow the white side feels just a tiny bit more comfortable to me. I like being very direct and forcing. }
10. f3
{ This has to be the critical move. White aims to hang onto his extra pawn. }
10... Bh5 11. Bg5
{ This is the trickiest try, and was used to some success when Yu Yangyi beat Mamedyarov. Black should be ready, but he is certainly fine. }
11... Qd6 { This seems like an easy enough solution. } 12. Bxf6
{ 12.dxc6?  Qc5+  Oops! } 12... Qxf6 13. dxc6 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Qxc3
{ Black takes on c6 next, with absolute equality.   15.Be4  Bg6  never helped anybody. }
