1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ Now, of course White's three main moves by far are Bb5, Bc4, and d4. But, he does have some extraneous options, including the notorious 4 knights variation. }
3. Nc3 Nf6
{ It really says a lot about how much White is grasping at straws against lines like the Berlin and Petroff that he is sometimes looking in this direction even at top level chess. The symmetrical nature of the position is hard to break.   Now, the two main moves by far are  4.d4  and  4.Bb5  ,  but there are some other options Black should be ready for too. In general, he will be looking to meet most silly looking moves with d7-d5, and quite a few silly looking moves have been tried here! }
4. Bb5
{ This is probably the most challenging try. Now, Black is very fine, but should remember some lines. }
4... Nd4 5. Nxe5 Qe7
{ This somewhat surprising move puts White in a bad way already. } 6. Nf3 Nxb5
7. Nxb5 Qxe4+ { White cannot avoid a queen exchange. } 8. Qe2
{ 8.Kf1  Qc4!  White is forced to play Qe2, transposing to the 8.Qe2 on the previous move. }
8... Qxe2+ 9. Kxe2 Nd5
{ Black is ready for a6 next, and is already better thanks to the uncompensated pair of bishops. }
