1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch game is a very sharp and ambitious opening. White aims to take a bigger share of the center directly without bothering to develop the light squared bishop first, and he does so in a way where dragging his queen out to d4 will not lose him any time. Black is forced into playing very active chess, as otherwise, he will simply be worse with a bit less space. }
3... exd4 4. Bc4
{ This is known as the Scotch Gambit. I like bypassing it completely. } 4...
Bc5
{ This seems like a very easy solution. White is best advised to play c2-c3, when after Ng8-f6, we transpose to the upcoming Italian section. }
5. O-O d6
{ Black keeps his extra pawn. He is ready to meet c2-c3 with Bc8-g4, and otherwise he just plays Ng8-f6 and O-O. White is worse. }
