[White "Ch. 4 - The Scotch "]
[Black "The Scotch: 4.Bc4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch game is a very sharp and ambitious opening. White aims to take a bigger share of the center directly without bothering to develop the light squared bishop first, and he does so in a way where dragging his queen out to d4 will not lose him any time. Black is forced into playing very active chess, as otherwise, he will simply be worse with a bit less space. }
3... exd4 4. Bc4
{ This is known as the Scotch Gambit. I like bypassing it completely. } 4...
Bc5
{ This seems like a very easy solution. White is best advised to play c2-c3, when after Ng8-f6, we transpose to the upcoming Italian section. }
5. Ng5
{ If White wants to avoid transposing to the Italian, he can try this option, but it is not particularly scary.   5.c3  Nf6!  Transposes to the Italian. }
5... Nh6
{ If Black is allowed to castle next, he will basically just be a pawn up. White should force matters. }
6. Nxf7 Nxf7 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qh5+ g6 9. Qxc5
{ Now, Black has one last important move to remember. } 9... d5
{ White is not too happy about this one, as he can't take on d5 thanks to the open e-file. }
10. Qxd5+ Qxd5 11. exd5 Nb4
{ Black wins his pawn back with a fantastic endgame thanks to his much more active pieces. }
