[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 4 - The Scotch "]
[Black "The Scotch: 6.Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch game is a very sharp and ambitious opening. White aims to take a bigger share of the center directly without bothering to develop the light squared bishop first, and he does so in a way where dragging his queen out to d4 will not lose him any time. Black is forced into playing very active chess, as otherwise, he will simply be worse with a bit less space. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ The most direct move, and the best one. Black targets the e4-pawn and asks White how he wants to defend it. Now, the most critical move by far is Nxc6 followed by the e4-e5 push. }
5. Nxc6
{ 5.Nc3  Bb4  Transposes to the Four Knights.   5.f3?  d5  The center is opening up and White will regret pushing his f-pawn.   5.Bg5?  h6  White will either lose the e4-pawn or give Black a very powerful bishop pair. Black is already clearly better. }
5... bxc6
{ Now, e4-e5 is surely the most critical test, but White does have a couple other tricky moves. }
6. Bd3
{ I tried this move myself a couple of times in blitz games at the Grand Chess Tour. It's a somewhat tricky line and Black can end up worse if he doesn't know what to do, but objectively it is certainly nothing to be scared of. }
6... d5 7. exd5 cxd5 8. O-O Be7 9. b3 O-O 10. Bb2 c5 11. Nd2 Be6
{ Black has a very solid position and is obviously fine. He can potentially look for some kind of Ra8-c8 and c5-c4 next, and he is happy to push d5-d4 if White plays c2-c4 himself first. }
*

