[White "Ch. 4 - The Scotch "]
[Black "The Scotch: 6.Qe2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch game is a very sharp and ambitious opening. White aims to take a bigger share of the center directly without bothering to develop the light squared bishop first, and he does so in a way where dragging his queen out to d4 will not lose him any time. Black is forced into playing very active chess, as otherwise, he will simply be worse with a bit less space. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ The most direct move, and the best one. Black targets the e4-pawn and asks White how he wants to defend it. Now, the most critical move by far is Nxc6 followed by the e4-e5 push. }
5. Nxc6
{ 5.Nc3  Bb4  Transposes to the Four Knights.   5.f3?  d5  The center is opening up and White will regret pushing his f-pawn.   5.Bg5?  h6  White will either lose the e4-pawn or give Black a very powerful bishop pair. Black is already clearly better. }
5... bxc6
{ Now, e4-e5 is surely the most critical test, but White does have a couple other tricky moves. }
6. Qe2
{ This is aimed at playing e4-e5 next, and obviously is prophylaxis against d7-d5, but it's hard for me to believe it can be best.   After all, after the main move with  6.e5  , we are willing to play  6...Qe7  ,  disturbing our own development, to provoke White's queen to e2, and he just placed it there voluntarily. }
6... Bc5 { Nice and easy. Black completes his development. } 7. e5
{ This is White's last opportunity to push e4-e5 before it will be met with Rf8-e8, so he really should do it now.   7.Nc3?  O-O  White lost out on his chance to play e4-e5 before it will be met with Rf8-e8, so he really should do it now. }
7... Nd5
{ Now, White fixes his coordination with Qe2-g4, and he can choose whether or not to include c2-c4 first. It looks a little menacing but I find it hard to believe White can avoid developing any minor pieces in an open position and still fight for an edge. }
8. Qg4 O-O
{ This is not an attacking repertoire, but if I am provoked enough, I just can't help myself. }
9. Bh6 g6 10. Bxf8 Bxf8
{ d7-d6 comes next, Black will almost certainly win at least a pawn, and White is badly lagging behind in development. The position more or less plays itself, and Black has full compensation for the exchange. }
*

