[White "Ch. 4 - The Scotch "]
[Black "The Scotch: Mainline 6.e5 with 8.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch game is a very sharp and ambitious opening. White aims to take a bigger share of the center directly without bothering to develop the light squared bishop first, and he does so in a way where dragging his queen out to d4 will not lose him any time. Black is forced into playing very active chess, as otherwise, he will simply be worse with a bit less space. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ The most direct move, and the best one. Black targets the e4-pawn and asks White how he wants to defend it. Now, the most critical move by far is Nxc6 followed by the e4-e5 push. }
5. Nxc6
{ 5.Nc3  Bb4  Transposes to the Four Knights.   5.f3?  d5  The center is opening up and White will regret pushing his f-pawn.   5.Bg5?  h6  White will either lose the e4-pawn or give Black a very powerful bishop pair. Black is already clearly better. }
5... bxc6
{ Now, e4-e5 is surely the most critical test, but White does have a couple other tricky moves. }
6. e5 { 6.Nc3  Bb4  Transposes to the Four Knights. } 6... Qe7 7. Qe2
{ 7.f4?  d6  White will regret not breaking the pin. He is already noticeably worse. }
7... Nd5
{ This is the main tabiya of the Scotch. White's two main tries are the old move in  8.c4  and the trendy modern one with  8.h4  ,  but he also has some other move order tricks we should be ready for.   In general, the plan we want to execute is g7-g6, Bf8-g7, O-O and Re8. This will likely lead to the fall of the e5-pawn. Often we are meeting c2-c4 with Bc8-a6, gaining further time for our development. }
8. g3
{ I'm not sure what the point of this specific move order is, but it has no independent value. }
8... g6
{ The computer is pretty adamant that White should play c2-c4, transposing to the mainlines. }
9. b3 Bg7 10. Bb2 O-O
{ Black is ready for Rf8-e8 and Bg7xe5 next, and he will scoop up a clean pawn for nothing if White now does not take his last opportunity to play c2-c4, transposing to the mainline. }
11. c4 Ba6 { Transposes tothe mainline. } *

