{ I like this direct move. In the mainline, had White chosen 9.b3 instead, 10.Ba3! would be a real nuisance. Now, that obviously is not happening, and we can attack the center directly. }
10. Qe4 Nb6 11. exf6 Qxe4+ 12. Nxe4 { Now things get pretty forced. } 12...
gxf6 13. Nxf6+
{ 13.Be3  Bxc4  Black is quite fine. His pawn mass is certainly not worse than White's. }
13... Kf7 14. Ng4
{ Now Black needs one last important move. Taking on c4 is not to be recommended thanks to a check on e5, so we take the square under our control first. }
14... Re8+ 15. Ne3 Bxc4
{ I tried this position from the White side against Dariusz Swiercz, and got absolutely nowhere. Black has a nice, healthy central pawn mass and I might even prefer his position in practice. }
