5. Nxc6
{ 5.Nc3  Bb4  Transposes to the Four Knights.   5.f3?  d5  The center is opening up and White will regret pushing his f-pawn.   5.Bg5?  h6  White will either lose the e4-pawn or give Black a very powerful bishop pair. Black is already clearly better. }
5... bxc6
{ Now, e4-e5 is surely the most critical test, but White does have a couple other tricky moves. }
6. e5 { 6.Nc3  Bb4  Transposes to the Four Knights. } 6... Qe7 7. Qe2
{ 7.f4?  d6  White will regret not breaking the pin. He is already noticeably worse. }
7... Nd5
{ This is the main tabiya of the Scotch. White's two main tries are the old move in  8.c4  and the trendy modern one with  8.h4  ,  but he also has some other move order tricks we should be ready for.   In general, the plan we want to execute is g7-g6, Bf8-g7, O-O and Re8. This will likely lead to the fall of the e5-pawn. Often we are meeting c2-c4 with Bc8-a6, gaining further time for our development. }
8. c4 Ba6 9. b3
{ 9.g3  g6  White is best advised to play b2-b3, transposing to the mainline. }
9... g6
{ Black sticks with his main plan. It is up to White to figure out how to not lose the e5-pawn. }
10. Bb2 Bg7 11. g3 { Now things get forcing. } 11... O-O 12. Bh3
{ This has been tried from time to time, aimed as prophylaxis against putting the rook on e8 as the pawn on d7 can hang. But the bishop has its drawbacks here as well. }
12... f6 13. Qd2
{ This would work well if White's bishop were on g2, but here it is too greedy. }
13... fxe5 14. cxd5 Qf7
{ Bh6 or Qf3 is coming next and White's position will collapse with his king stuck in the soon to be wide open center. }
