10. Bb2 Bg7 11. g3 { Now things get forcing. } 11... O-O 12. Bh3
{ This has been tried from time to time, aimed as prophylaxis against putting the rook on e8 as the pawn on d7 can hang. But the bishop has its drawbacks here as well. }
12... f6 13. e6 f5 14. O-O { Now, I like forcing a transformation once again. }
14... Qxe6
{ Black forces another 2 pieces vs rook and pawns ending, and this one with an even healthier structure. }
15. Qxe6+ { Otherwise White will remain a pawn down. } 15... dxe6 16. Bxg7 Kxg7
{ Much like the mainline, we see that now that the queens are off, the c4-pawn is unpinned to a degree. }
17. cxd5 Bxf1 18. Bxf1 cxd5
{ Black has a better structure than he does in the mainline, and this looks quite pleasant for him. The minor pieces really fail to impress. c7-c5 is coming next. }
