[White "Ch. 4 - The Scotch "]
[Black "The Scotch: Mainline 6.e5 with 8.c4 #17"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch game is a very sharp and ambitious opening. White aims to take a bigger share of the center directly without bothering to develop the light squared bishop first, and he does so in a way where dragging his queen out to d4 will not lose him any time. Black is forced into playing very active chess, as otherwise, he will simply be worse with a bit less space. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ The most direct move, and the best one. Black targets the e4-pawn and asks White how he wants to defend it. Now, the most critical move by far is Nxc6 followed by the e4-e5 push. }
5. Nxc6
{ 5.Nc3  Bb4  Transposes to the Four Knights.   5.f3?  d5  The center is opening up and White will regret pushing his f-pawn.   5.Bg5?  h6  White will either lose the e4-pawn or give Black a very powerful bishop pair. Black is already clearly better. }
5... bxc6
{ Now, e4-e5 is surely the most critical test, but White does have a couple other tricky moves. }
6. e5 { 6.Nc3  Bb4  Transposes to the Four Knights. } 6... Qe7 7. Qe2
{ 7.f4?  d6  White will regret not breaking the pin. He is already noticeably worse. }
7... Nd5
{ This is the main tabiya of the Scotch. White's two main tries are the old move in  8.c4  and the trendy modern one with  8.h4  ,  but he also has some other move order tricks we should be ready for.   In general, the plan we want to execute is g7-g6, Bf8-g7, O-O and Re8. This will likely lead to the fall of the e5-pawn. Often we are meeting c2-c4 with Bc8-a6, gaining further time for our development. }
8. c4 Ba6 9. b3
{ 9.g3  g6  White is best advised to play b2-b3, transposing to the mainline. }
9... g6
{ Black sticks with his main plan. It is up to White to figure out how to not lose the e5-pawn. }
10. Bb2 Bg7 11. g3 { Now things get forcing. } 11... O-O 12. Bg2 Rfe8
{ Now, the e5-pawn is hanging, and White has no business trying to save it. He should instead accept the transformation of the position as a lot of pieces leave the board. }
13. O-O
{ Now, White is ready to consolidate the position with Rf1-e1 next. We have to take on e5 and provoke a massive exchanging operation. }
13... Bxe5 14. Qxe5 Qxe5 15. Bxe5 Rxe5
{ Black won the e5-pawn, but in doing so, he traded the queens. This unpins the c4-pawn to take the knight on d5 without catastrophic material losses, but it is still not an entirely free knight. }
16. cxd5 Bxf1 17. Kxf1 cxd5
{ Up to here, the last few moves have been forced. Practice has shown that Black is absoultely fine in this endgame. He has a very simple plan of bolstering the center with c7-c6, sticking the king on d6, and potentially playing a7-a5 to gain queenside space.   It is certainly equal but I actually think Black's position is easier to play in practice, as he has no weaknesses and an easy plan. We will see an illustrative game in this line. White only has one move to try to imbalance the game and shake things up, and while we need to be ready, it is nothing to be scared of. }
18. f4
{ White wins the d5-pawn, but it is nothing to be worried about.   18.Nc3  c6  Black is good to go with the aforementioned plan. }
18... Re3 19. Bxd5 c6
{ Black has a lot of counterplay with Rae8 coming next. White has one tricky idea. }
20. Bf3
{ Ths bishop is immune from capture as the rook then gets trapped, but it's nothing to be concerned about. }
20... Rae8 21. Kf2 Re1
{ White is totally paralyzed thanks to the pin on the first rank, and may as well resign. }
