[White "Ch. 5 - Italian Sidelines "]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5
{ Chapter 6 will cover the Italian Game where White avoids his most common continuation by far, which is c2-c3 followed by d2-d3.   There are some passive lines that can be dealt with strategically, but for the most part, we will be dealing with aggressive tries such as c2-c3 followed by d2-d4, aiming to immediately take the whole center. White will be better if he can pull this off, so Black should know the best ways to fight back in the center and reach a decent position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 5 - Italian Sidelines "]
[Black "Italian Sidelines: 4.b4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ For a long time, the Spanish was thought of as clearly White's best attempt to fight for an opening advantage. In recent times though, there has been a real Italian Renaissance and Bc4 is looking like every bit as serious an attempt to fight for an advantage. We certainly must be ready. }
3... Bc5 4. b4
{ The Evans Gambit is another one of those openings that had its day, but did not stand the test of time that well. It is still seen reasonably often because White is not worse, but he is certainly not better either. }
4... Bxb4 5. c3 Be7
{ This seems solid enough. The bishop coming to c5 would only lose time to d2-d4. }
6. d4 Na5
{ I like immediately kicking the bishop off of the dangerous a2-f7 diagonal. Black will play d7-d6 next, giving back the extra pawn but accelerating his development and leaving White with a questionable structure. }
7. Be2 { This was Kasparov's choice in his famous game with Anand. } 7... d6
{ I see no reason not to stick with the main plan. } 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qxd8+
{ 9.Qa4+  c6  Transposes to8.Qa4+. } 9... Bxd8 10. Nxe5 Nf6
{ Black is quite comfortable in this endgame. He has no long term weaknesses, but White does. It's a little surprising to me that the machine calls it equal. }
*

