{ This seems solid enough. The bishop coming to c5 would only lose time to d2-d4. }
6. d4 Na5
{ I like immediately kicking the bishop off of the dangerous a2-f7 diagonal. Black will play d7-d6 next, giving back the extra pawn but accelerating his development and leaving White with a questionable structure. }
7. Be2 { This was Kasparov's choice in his famous game with Anand. } 7... d6
{ I see no reason not to stick with the main plan. } 8. Qa4+ c6 9. dxe5 dxe5
10. Nxe5 Nf6
{ Black has an easy development scheme for all of his pieces and no weaknesses. In the long run, he probably is a bit more comfortable thanks to White's split queenside. I find it unsurprising that he has a plus score from this position in human practice, though the machine insists it is equal. }
