[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ For a long time, the Spanish was thought of as clearly White's best attempt to fight for an opening advantage. In recent times though, there has been a real Italian Renaissance and Bc4 is looking like every bit as serious an attempt to fight for an advantage. We certainly must be ready. }
3... Bc5 4. c3 Nf6
{ Now, the main move by far is  5.d3  , which will be the subject of the next section. }
5. d4
{ In recent times, this move has become quite popular. It is very forcing, but should not be too threatening if Black is well prepared.   5.d3  O-O  will be covered in the next chapter. }
5... exd4 6. b4
{ This move is a little too wild to be good. If Black is unprepared he can get into trouble and Karjakin went down hard when he wasn't ready for it, but if Black has checked with the machine, it is nothing to be concerned with. }
6... Be7 { This strikes me as the safest option. } 7. e5
{ Now this move makes a bit more sense as d7-d5 is not a feasible response thanks to the hanging bishop on e7, but Black still seems comfortable enough. }
7... Ng4
{ I like this odd looking move. Normally, the knight would be badly misplaced here as h2-h3 would kick it back to the horrific h6 square, but this is a different scenario, all thanks to the b2-pawn going to b4. }
8. cxd4 Bxb4+
{ This check actually proves really annoying for White to deal with. The absense of the b2-pawn means that Nc3 is not a thing, and any other way of blocking the check would allow the g4-knight to safely retreat to h6. }
9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O
{ Black is ready for d7-d6 next, and I really struggle to see the compensation. White might just find himself a pawn down in short order. }
*

