1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ For a long time, the Spanish was thought of as clearly White's best attempt to fight for an opening advantage. In recent times though, there has been a real Italian Renaissance and Bc4 is looking like every bit as serious an attempt to fight for an advantage. We certainly must be ready. }
3... Bc5 4. c3 Nf6
{ Now, the main move by far is  5.d3  , which will be the subject of the next section. }
5. d4
{ In recent times, this move has become quite popular. It is very forcing, but should not be too threatening if Black is well prepared.   5.d3  O-O  will be covered in the next chapter. }
5... exd4 6. cxd4 Bb4+ 7. Nbd2 { This is not too scary. } 7... Nxe4
{ Of course we should grab the pawn. } 8. d5
{ White is a pawn down and should be playing energetically. } 8... Ne7 9. O-O
{ Now, all Black has to do to basically win is get castled and push d7-d6 without anything bad happening to him. }
9... Nxd2 { First off, we trade off the hanging knight. } 10. Nxd2
{ Now, Black is unable to play d7-d6 thanks to a check on a4. } 10... O-O
{ If Black can play d7-d6 next, he should be a pawn up for very questionable compensation. White can just barely hang on. }
11. a3 Bc5 12. Ne4
{ White hits the bishop, and it cannot retreat again without allowing d5-d6. So we have to let him take it, but we remain a pawn up. }
12... d6
{ Black looks happy enough to me. Once White takes on c5, he can maneuvre Ne7-f5-d6. At some point, the extra pawn should matter, and White certainly has no concrete way to make any trouble. }
