6... d5 { A typical motif. Now, White has to choose where to put the bishop. }
7. Be2
{ Black has often taken his chance to change the structure with d4-d3 here, starting some wild complications after exf6, but I find this totally unnecessary. We can just stick to the plan. }
7... Ne4 { The knight is well placed here. } 8. cxd4 Bb6 9. O-O O-O 10. Nc3
{ 10.Be3  This was Feedoseev's move order. I don't think it changes much:  10...f6! }
10... Be6
{ We want to play f7-f6 next and to be able to take back with the queen and not hang the d-pawn. }
11. Be3 f6
{ I think a position like this one clearly highlights why White would much rather have his bishop on b5. He would very much like to meet f6xe5 with Bb5xc6 and then Nf3xe5, but this will not happen. }
12. exf6 Qxf6 13. Bb5
{ Now, of course we don't allow White to take c6 and go Ne5. } 13... Ne7
{ Black can regroup with c7-c6 and Bb6-c7 next. He has a fine position. } *

