[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 5 - Italian Sidelines "]
[Black "Italian Sidelines: 4.c3, 5.d4 exd4 with 6.e5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ For a long time, the Spanish was thought of as clearly White's best attempt to fight for an opening advantage. In recent times though, there has been a real Italian Renaissance and Bc4 is looking like every bit as serious an attempt to fight for an advantage. We certainly must be ready. }
3... Bc5 4. c3 Nf6
{ Now, the main move by far is  5.d3  , which will be the subject of the next section. }
5. d4
{ In recent times, this move has become quite popular. It is very forcing, but should not be too threatening if Black is well prepared.   5.d3  O-O  will be covered in the next chapter. }
5... exd4 6. e5
{ This is the modern main move, and the one recommended by Wesley So in his course here on Chessable. }
6... d5 { A typical motif. Now, White has to choose where to put the bishop. }
7. Be2
{ Black has often taken his chance to change the structure with d4-d3 here, starting some wild complications after exf6, but I find this totally unnecessary. We can just stick to the plan. }
7... Ne4 { The knight is well placed here. } 8. cxd4 Bb6 9. O-O O-O 10. Nc3
{ 10.Be3  This was Feedoseev's move order. I don't think it changes much:  10...f6! }
10... Be6
{ We want to play f7-f6 next and to be able to take back with the queen and not hang the d-pawn. }
11. Be3 f6
{ I think a position like this one clearly highlights why White would much rather have his bishop on b5. He would very much like to meet f6xe5 with Bb5xc6 and then Nf3xe5, but this will not happen. }
12. Na4 { The machine claims this is best.   12.Bb5  Bg4! } 12... Bg4
{ Black takes advantage of his bishop no longer being needed on e6 to defend d5, and he is ready for Bxf3 and fxe5 next, with a fine position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
