1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ For a long time, the Spanish was thought of as clearly White's best attempt to fight for an opening advantage. In recent times though, there has been a real Italian Renaissance and Bc4 is looking like every bit as serious an attempt to fight for an advantage. We certainly must be ready. }
3... Bc5 4. c3 Nf6
{ Now, the main move by far is  5.d3  , which will be the subject of the next section. }
5. d4
{ In recent times, this move has become quite popular. It is very forcing, but should not be too threatening if Black is well prepared.   5.d3  O-O  will be covered in the next chapter. }
5... exd4 6. e5
{ This is the modern main move, and the one recommended by Wesley So in his course here on Chessable. }
6... d5 { A typical motif. Now, White has to choose where to put the bishop. }
7. Bb5
{ This is definitely the most challenging move. The bishop on b5 is very good prophlaxis against the f7-f6 break later on. }
7... Ne4 8. cxd4 Bb6
{ The one drawback of the bishop on b5 is that the Bg4 pin can be pretty annoying. In modern times, White has tried to solve this problem by delaying castling for awhile. }
9. Nc3
{ In modern times, this has emerged as the main move. White is a bit reluctant to castle short so soon.   9.Be3  O-O  White has nothing better than Nc3 or O-O, transposing to the 9.Nc3 and 9.O-O lines. }
9... O-O 10. Be3 Bg4 11. h3 Bh5 12. Qc2
{ This is exactly the kind of position where it becomes clear that there was some merit to delaying castling. Black would love to take f3, take d4, and go give a check on g5, but the last part of that plan is not a thing until White has put his king on g1. Black has to be careful here to avoid a seriously unpleasant position, but I think he has a nice solution. }
12... Ba5
{ The bishop was not doing much on b6, and now it pins the knight. Of course the pin is temporary, but this encourages White's king to go to g1, which he may regret later on. }
13. O-O Bxf3 14. gxf3 Ng5 15. Kg2
{ Now, Black should be careful. If White takes on c6 next and then moves his c3- knight out of the way, we may find ourselves with a buried bishop before we know it.   15.f4?  Nxd4!  White loses material. }
15... Bxc3
{ Black trades off the bishop before it becomes a piece of dead wood. } 16.
bxc3 { Still following Wesley's repertoire. } 16... Ne6 17. f4 f5
{ Now, Black's position is extremely solid, and the closed nature means that the knights certainly should not be worse than the bishops. }
18. Qa4
{ This is the most direct move. More than anything else, it is prophylaxis against the Nc6-e7 regrouping thanks to the surprisingly annoying recource Bb5-d7. }
18... Qh4 { Qa4 came at a cost- White's kingside is starting to feel lonely. }
19. Bxc6 bxc6 20. Qxc6 Rae8
{ g5 is coming and the attack is very powerful. Wesley actually won a nice game on the black side of this position- having recommended the repertoire for White, he surely had a good idea of where Black's best chances for equality lay, and it says a lot that this is what he chose. }
21. Qxd5
{ Pichot took this pawn,  but after  21...g5!  White's position is incredibly dangerous and he could get mated on the g-file before he knows it. }
21... g5
{ In the game, that is exactly what happened, though the machine still calls it equal. }
