1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ For a long time, the Spanish was thought of as clearly White's best attempt to fight for an opening advantage. In recent times though, there has been a real Italian Renaissance and Bc4 is looking like every bit as serious an attempt to fight for an advantage. We certainly must be ready. }
3... Bc5 4. d3 Nf6
{ Now, of course O-O and c2-c3 are the main moves, but there is another one that will always haunt me. }
5. Bg5 O-O
{ Now, it is hard for me to believe that White can avoid castling for too long here, and the positions will soon transpose to what we see in  5.O-O  O-O  6.Bg5  . But I did check his alternatives. }
6. Nc3 { 6.O-O  h6  Transposes toline 5.d3 O-O 6.Bg5. } 6... h6 7. Bxf6
{ This makes a little more sense now since Nc3-d5 comes quickly, but I don't think it's an issue. }
7... Qxf6 8. Nd5 Qd8 9. c3 a6 10. d4 exd4 11. cxd4 Ba7
{ White's center looks impressive, but it is actually not as secure as it might seem at first glance. Black has his ways of attacking it, and the machines insist he is totally fine. }
