1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ For a long time, the Spanish was thought of as clearly White's best attempt to fight for an opening advantage. In recent times though, there has been a real Italian Renaissance and Bc4 is looking like every bit as serious an attempt to fight for an advantage. We certainly must be ready. }
3... Bc5 4. d3 Nf6
{ Now, of course O-O and c2-c3 are the main moves, but there is another one that will always haunt me. }
5. Nc3
{ This was the move Anish played against me in the infamous game where I resigned a drawn position. It shouldn't be too scary to see White continue to play symmetrically, but Black should still be a bit careful not to become worse. }
5... a6
{ I like clearing the a7-square for the bishop so as not to fear any Nc3-a4. }
6. O-O d6 { Now that e5 is defended, Nc6-a5 is a real idea. } 7. Bg5
{ This is really asking for trouble. I don't think Bg5 and Nc3 get along very well. }
7... h6 8. Bh4
{ 8.Bxf6  Qxf6  9.Nd5  Qd8  was seen in Maghsoodloo, P. vs. Shankland, S., see theModel Games chapter. }
8... g5
{ Even when Black castles short, it is often difficult to attack his king in these g7-g5 positions. Here, obviously there is no attack whatsoever, and after }
9. Bg3 Bg4
{ White is facing multiple threats that prove very hard to meet. He should be careful not to lose immediatelty. }
