[White "Ch. 5 - Italian Sidelines "]
[Black "Italian Sidelines: 4.O-O with 5.d3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ For a long time, the Spanish was thought of as clearly White's best attempt to fight for an opening advantage. In recent times though, there has been a real Italian Renaissance and Bc4 is looking like every bit as serious an attempt to fight for an advantage. We certainly must be ready. }
3... Bc5 4. O-O
{ 4.d4  exd4  Transposes to the Scotch.   4.Nc3  Nf6  5.d3  a6  Transposes to 4.d3 with 5.Nc3. }
4... Nf6 5. d3 O-O
{ White's most common move here by a wide margin is c2-c3, transposing to the mainlines, but he does have some extraneous options we should be ready for. }
6. Bg5
{ Since our default next move was going to be d7-d5, this move makes some sense as that will obviously not happen anymore. }
6... h6 7. Bh4 Be7
{ The machines often give a slight edge in positions like this one with White's bishop coming back to g3. Perhaps I am not objective enough, but it is hard for me to believe Black can be worse against this maneuvre. }
8. Nc3 d6 9. h3 Na5
{ Black grabs the bishop pair and is already better. In general, White should take care to always watch out for Na5 once the e5-pawn is protected. }
