[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 5 - Italian Sidelines "]
[Black "Italian Sidelines: 4.O-O with 5.d3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ For a long time, the Spanish was thought of as clearly White's best attempt to fight for an opening advantage. In recent times though, there has been a real Italian Renaissance and Bc4 is looking like every bit as serious an attempt to fight for an advantage. We certainly must be ready. }
3... Bc5 4. O-O
{ 4.d4  exd4  Transposes to the Scotch.   4.Nc3  Nf6  5.d3  a6  Transposes to 4.d3 with 5.Nc3. }
4... Nf6 5. d3 O-O
{ White's most common move here by a wide margin is c2-c3, transposing to the mainlines, but he does have some extraneous options we should be ready for. }
6. h3
{ Apart from c3, this is the most sensible move. White keeps in line with his normal plan, but switches the move order to make it harder for us to advance d7-d5. Plus, the main reason not to advance h2-h3 is that if Black has not castled yet, a g7-g5-g4 attack could be very dangerous. This is clearly no longer relevant. }
6... h6
{ I like responding in kind with a useful waiting move. We are still aiming to play d7-d5, but we'd like White to commit to c2-c3 first. }
7. c3 d5 8. exd5 Nxd5
{ The position takes on a similar character to what we will see in the mainline next chapter, but the inclusion of h2-h3 and h7-h6 changes things a lot. }
9. b4 { This wins a pawn, but at a heavy cost. } 9... Be7 10. b5 Na5 11. Nxe5
Nxc4 12. Nxc4 { 12.dxc4  Nb6  . } 12... a6
{ Surprisingly, White is dead lost thanks to his numerous weaknesses and Black's superior activity. }
