6. b4
{ This move has picked up quite a following recently, but I can't say I am sure I understand it. }
6... Be7
{ There is not a single spot in the entire repertoire where Black's bishop meets b4 with remaining on the a7-g1 diagonal. Makes things a lot simpler! d7-d5 is coming next. }
7. Nbd2 d5 8. Bb3
{ Compared to the position without b2-b4 and Bc5-e7 included, this is a clear step in the right direction for White. Not only has he kicked Black's bishop off of the active c5-square, but he also has denied Black the option of Qd8-e7 and Bc8-e6. Nonetheless, Black has to be fine, and I found a pretty clean route to equality. }
8... dxe4 9. dxe4 Qd3 10. Bb2 a5
{ I like this direct move, aiming to take advantage of White's pushing for queenside play before he has castled. Furthermore, we get this move in before the queen can be forced to a6. }
11. a3
{ This is the best move. White is potentially ready for Bf1-c4 and 0-0 to follow, and if he can pull this off, he may end up better. I like diasallowing it. }
11... b5
{ Now White's bishop must retreat to a much more passive square to get his king over to g1. }
12. Bc2 Qd6 13. O-O
{ Now, Black needs to remember one last important move. I don't really want to take on b4 and open up the b2-bishop, but a3-a4 is a big threat, and we need to play prophylactically. }
13... Rb8
{ Black overprotects the b5-pawn, and I can't see any great plan for White if he is unable to push a2-a4. Black can look for Nf6-h5 and Qd6-g6 to come next. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 6 - The Italian Game"]
[Black "The Italian Game: 6.Nbd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3
{ At long last, we are in the mainline Italian. The positions are extremely rich, with lots of subtle move order tricks involving plans with a6/Ba7, a6 and then provoking a4 to play a5, the timing of Ne7... endless subtleties and nuances.   And I am going to be blunt and direct and ignore all of them! The easiest way for Black to equalize is to push d7-d5 in one go, and not play d7-d6. I would encourage the reader to investigate some of these d7-d6 plans on their own to find lines with better chances of playing for a win, and to learn about a fascinating middlegame that will help your understanding overall, but here I am going to stick with the same attitude as the rest of the repertoire and try to find the most solid and forcing way to reach an equal position. }
5... O-O
{ Now, the default is to push d7-d5 next. If Black is allowed to do this comfortably, he will be absolutely fine. }
6. Nbd2
{ This plan, in connection with aiming to play Nd2-f1-g3 before 0-0, can be dangerous in some cases. But I find it to be pretty toothless against the d7-d5 plan. }
6... d5 { Of course. } 7. Bb3 dxe4 { The simplest. } 8. dxe4 Qe7
{ Black is ready for a7-a5 and Bc8-e6 next, with easy equality. } *

