{ Now, if Black is able to consolidate his position, he will be very easily fine thanks to his slightly superior structure and more active pieces. But, it looks a little loose for the moment, and White has a few interesting tries that we definitely need to be ready for. }
8. Re1
{ This is the best and most critical move. Black has a little bit of a hard time defending the e5-pawn, and is forced to play very precisely. }
8... Bg4
{ The bishop is not great here, but we did not have much choice. e5 had to be protected. }
9. h3 Bh5 10. Nbd2 Nb6 { Black chases the bishop. } 11. Bb5
{ This has been most common historically and I even tried it once myself against Sevian, but as of late it is very clear with  11.Bb3  is the more challenging option. }
11... Bd6
{ Black defends the e5-pawn. He is ready for f7-f5 next and already looks a little more comfortable to me. }
12. Ne4 f5 13. Ng3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Qd7
{ Black is ready for a7-a6 next, taking back his bishop pair, and he looks better thanks to the extra space. We will see Vidit put on a clinic in the illustrative games section. }
