1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3
{ At long last, we are in the mainline Italian. The positions are extremely rich, with lots of subtle move order tricks involving plans with a6/Ba7, a6 and then provoking a4 to play a5, the timing of Ne7... endless subtleties and nuances.   And I am going to be blunt and direct and ignore all of them! The easiest way for Black to equalize is to push d7-d5 in one go, and not play d7-d6. I would encourage the reader to investigate some of these d7-d6 plans on their own to find lines with better chances of playing for a win, and to learn about a fascinating middlegame that will help your understanding overall, but here I am going to stick with the same attitude as the rest of the repertoire and try to find the most solid and forcing way to reach an equal position. }
5... O-O
{ Now, the default is to push d7-d5 next. If Black is allowed to do this comfortably, he will be absolutely fine. }
6. O-O d5 7. exd5 Nxd5
{ Now, if Black is able to consolidate his position, he will be very easily fine thanks to his slightly superior structure and more active pieces. But, it looks a little loose for the moment, and White has a few interesting tries that we definitely need to be ready for. }
8. Re1
{ This is the best and most critical move. Black has a little bit of a hard time defending the e5-pawn, and is forced to play very precisely. }
8... Bg4
{ The bishop is not great here, but we did not have much choice. e5 had to be protected. }
9. h3 Bh5 10. Nbd2 Nb6 { Black chases the bishop. } 11. b4 Be7
{ This is almost always the best square for the bishop to go after b2-b4. Sometimes f8 may be better, but here that is not yet legal. }
12. b5 Na5 13. Rxe5 { 13.g4  Bg6  Transposesto 12.g4. } 13... Bg6
{ Bf6 is coming next, and White's position is extremely loose. He will almost certainly lose back his extra pawn and his development is seriously lacking. He should be careful not to become worse. }
