1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3
{ At long last, we are in the mainline Italian. The positions are extremely rich, with lots of subtle move order tricks involving plans with a6/Ba7, a6 and then provoking a4 to play a5, the timing of Ne7... endless subtleties and nuances.   And I am going to be blunt and direct and ignore all of them! The easiest way for Black to equalize is to push d7-d5 in one go, and not play d7-d6. I would encourage the reader to investigate some of these d7-d6 plans on their own to find lines with better chances of playing for a win, and to learn about a fascinating middlegame that will help your understanding overall, but here I am going to stick with the same attitude as the rest of the repertoire and try to find the most solid and forcing way to reach an equal position. }
5... O-O
{ Now, the default is to push d7-d5 next. If Black is allowed to do this comfortably, he will be absolutely fine. }
6. O-O d5 7. exd5 Nxd5
{ Now, if Black is able to consolidate his position, he will be very easily fine thanks to his slightly superior structure and more active pieces. But, it looks a little loose for the moment, and White has a few interesting tries that we definitely need to be ready for. }
8. Re1
{ This is the best and most critical move. Black has a little bit of a hard time defending the e5-pawn, and is forced to play very precisely. }
8... Bg4
{ The bishop is not great here, but we did not have much choice. e5 had to be protected. }
9. h3 Bh5 10. Nbd2 Nb6 { Black chases the bishop. } 11. Bb3
{ This trendy move is surely White's best try to fight for an advantage, and it has been tried by all of the top players. White offers the exchange of the e5 and d3-pawns, and hopes that he can take advantage of the misplaced bishop on h5. }
11... Qxd3 { I think Black can and should take the plunge. } 12. Nxe5 Qf5 13.
Nef3
{ And here we see the point of White's play. He has provoked Black's bishop to h5 and now is threatening g2-g4 next, which leads to a possibly favorable 3 pawns vs piece scenario.   Additionally, if Black were to move the queen or bishop away, a well timed Nc3-e4 can gain a tempo on the c5-bishop, and Black's pieces generally feel scattered and a bit clumsy despite the symmetrical structure. We need to be precise to hold on, but the moves are there. }
13... Rad8
{ I like starting with this one. The rook is obviously well placed on d8, we do not need to fear g2-g4 just yet, and the queen can hide away on c8 next without blocking the rook in. }
14. Qe2 { Now g2-g4 is a scary move again. } 14... Nd5
{ Again, Black prevents g2-g4 through tactical means rather than retreating his queen. }
15. Ne4
{ Now, we are going to lose the bishop pair. But, we can shatter the kingside structure first. }
15... Bxf3 16. Qxf3
{ Of course white exchanges the queens.   16.gxf3?  Nobody will be this stupid.  16...Ne5  White can resign. }
16... Qxf3 17. gxf3 Bb6
{ Now, it is very important that White is not able to cause trouble with a bishop coming to g5. Our next move should be h7-h6, and we need not fear Bxh6 because of the desperado Nd5xc3. }
18. Bg5
{ This would be the way for White to try to punish us, getting the bishop to b5 before we could play h7-h6. But, we are fine, if we are ready. }
18... Nde7
{ This is a tough move to play since it looks like we are begging for a tactic on the e-file, but there is nothing there. }
19. Ng3 Rfe8
{ Black is ready with Kg8-f8 to break the pin on the f7-pawn and keep everything nice and solid. The annoying bishop on g5 will soon be kicked away, and it does not have a great square to go to since f4 is unstable thanks to the Ne7-g6 resource. }
