[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 7 - Berlin Fourth Moves "]
[Black "Berlin Fourth Moves: 4.Qe2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ Now, White's two main moves by far are O-O and d3, but he does have a couple of extraneous options that Black should be ready for. }
4. Qe2
{ This strikes me as a pretty dumb way to defend the e4-pawn. The queen can easily end up misplaced on the e-file. }
4... Bd6
{ I like this odd-looking move. Black will castle next, and then he can follow up with Ne7 and c6, aiming to play a kind of reversed Italian where his bishop reaches the ideal c7 square in two moves rather than 3. Black is very comfortable. }
5. O-O O-O 6. Bxc6 bxc6
{ As we will often see, I don't like taking back with the d-pawn if Black is castling short. Here he has an easy plan to take the whole center. }
