[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 8 - Berlin 4.d3 Bc5 5.Bxc6 "]
[Black "Berlin 4.d3 Bc5 5.Bxc6: 6.Nbd2 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6
{ This move looks a little strange, playing some kind of Exchange Spanish where Black has not had to burn a tempo on a7-a6. But, there is some logic to it.   In a lot of lines in the Exchange Spanish, Black's knight actually wants to go to e7, and the bishop often wants to go to d6. Surely Black can play Bc5-d6, claiming that playing Bf8-c5-d6 is not substantially worse than playing Bf8-d6 in one move but also spending a tempo on a7-a6, but the f6 knight can end up feeling misplaced and often needs to be rerouted. As such, it is a serious chance for White to fight for an advantage, and one we need to be ready for. }
5... dxc6
{ The setup I want to achieve is Be6, Bd6, and Nd7. then, Black can castle long. In general, I think he should be very happy to put the king on the queenside in all of these positions, as the 4 pawn cover is very safe. White has tried a ton of different moves here, though I believe that the two most challenging by far are O-O and Nbd2. Our default next move is Bc8-e6, getting us closer to the ideal coordination.   I don't spend much time here explaining how Black should play once he reaches the right setup, but we will see some examples in the illustrative games section. }
6. Nbd2
{ For a long time, this was considered the main move, but I think it is less challenging than the direct  6.O-O  .  Since White is still not threatening to capture the e5-pawn, I am very happy to get the bishop to e6. }
6... Be6 7. Qe2
{ This move is generally played in connection with the plan of castling long and launching a kingside attack, but since we are not castling kingside, Black has nothing to worry about. }
7... Nd7 8. Nb3 Bb6
{ As usual, we are ready for Qe7 and O-O-O. Black will probably be better if he can pull this off. }
9. Ng5 { Otherwise White's position makes no sense. } 9... Nf8
{ We see this same motif again. White takes back the bishop pair, but once Black's knight takes back on e6, he will control the d4 and f4 squares far too well for White to organize a pawn break. }
10. Nxe6 Nxe6
{ Black will castle long soon enough, and he looks absolutely fine to me. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 8 - Berlin 4.d3 Bc5 5.Bxc6 "]
[Black "Berlin 4.d3 Bc5 5.Bxc6: 6.Nbd2 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6
{ This move looks a little strange, playing some kind of Exchange Spanish where Black has not had to burn a tempo on a7-a6. But, there is some logic to it.   In a lot of lines in the Exchange Spanish, Black's knight actually wants to go to e7, and the bishop often wants to go to d6. Surely Black can play Bc5-d6, claiming that playing Bf8-c5-d6 is not substantially worse than playing Bf8-d6 in one move but also spending a tempo on a7-a6, but the f6 knight can end up feeling misplaced and often needs to be rerouted. As such, it is a serious chance for White to fight for an advantage, and one we need to be ready for. }
5... dxc6
{ The setup I want to achieve is Be6, Bd6, and Nd7. then, Black can castle long. In general, I think he should be very happy to put the king on the queenside in all of these positions, as the 4 pawn cover is very safe. White has tried a ton of different moves here, though I believe that the two most challenging by far are O-O and Nbd2. Our default next move is Bc8-e6, getting us closer to the ideal coordination.   I don't spend much time here explaining how Black should play once he reaches the right setup, but we will see some examples in the illustrative games section. }
6. Nbd2
{ For a long time, this was considered the main move, but I think it is less challenging than the direct  6.O-O  .  Since White is still not threatening to capture the e5-pawn, I am very happy to get the bishop to e6. }
6... Be6 7. O-O
{ The main move by far. Now that White is threatening to take on e5, we have to defend the pawn.   7.Ng5?  White can't go chasing the bishop...  7...Bxf2+!  Oops! }
7... Bd6
{ Unfortunately, Black is not able to play Nf6-d7 as easily in this position, as Nd2-b3 comes pretty fast. Now, if White makes some non-move, Black is ready for Nd7 next, and then Qe7 and O-O-O with a great position. White should be very direct. }
8. d4
{ White makes use of his lead in development and looks to blast open the center before Black is ready to deal with it. We have to be precise not to get run over. }
8... Nd7
{ Now, White's only sensible choice is to take twice on e5 and push f4. He has no other way to get his pieces out and pressure Black's center, and if Black is given time to play Qe7 and O-O-O, White will have a horrible position. }
9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Bxe5 11. Nf3 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Bd6
{ Black is ready for O-O-O next, with a nice version of the Berlin Endgame since castling is legal. White should be careful not to become worse. }
*

