7... Bd6
{ Unfortunately, Black is not able to play Nf6-d7 as easily in this position, as Nd2-b3 comes pretty fast. Now, if White makes some non-move, Black is ready for Nd7 next, and then Qe7 and O-O-O with a great position. White should be very direct. }
8. b3
{ For better or for worse, this is the most common move, but in my opinion, it is extremely cooperative. The bishop will hardly be a superstar on b2, and it doesn't do a thing to prevent Black from reaching his ideal coordination.   8.Ng5  This never makes any sense if Black's knight is still on f6. After  8...Bg4  Black saves his bishop and White should probably repeat the position with Ng5-f3. }
8... Nd7 9. Nc4
{ Now, Black must lose one of his bishops. I like messing up White's pawn structure a little rather than letting him take on d6. }
9... Bxc4 10. bxc4 Qe7
{ Black is ready to castle long next, with a solid position and he can eventually look for an f7-f5 break. He certainly looks happy enough to me. }
