[White "Ch. 8 - Berlin 4.d3 Bc5 5.Bxc6 "]
[Black "Berlin 4.d3 Bc5 5.Bxc6: 6.Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6
{ This move looks a little strange, playing some kind of Exchange Spanish where Black has not had to burn a tempo on a7-a6. But, there is some logic to it.   In a lot of lines in the Exchange Spanish, Black's knight actually wants to go to e7, and the bishop often wants to go to d6. Surely Black can play Bc5-d6, claiming that playing Bf8-c5-d6 is not substantially worse than playing Bf8-d6 in one move but also spending a tempo on a7-a6, but the f6 knight can end up feeling misplaced and often needs to be rerouted. As such, it is a serious chance for White to fight for an advantage, and one we need to be ready for. }
5... dxc6
{ The setup I want to achieve is Be6, Bd6, and Nd7. then, Black can castle long. In general, I think he should be very happy to put the king on the queenside in all of these positions, as the 4 pawn cover is very safe. White has tried a ton of different moves here, though I believe that the two most challenging by far are O-O and Nbd2. Our default next move is Bc8-e6, getting us closer to the ideal coordination.   I don't spend much time here explaining how Black should play once he reaches the right setup, but we will see some examples in the illustrative games section. }
6. Bg5 Qd6
{ In general, whenever the bishop goes to g5 for White, Black normally wants to put his queen on d6 rather than e7, as then he can go Be6 and O-O-O next without dropping the e5-pawn.   This position is no exception, there is not a thing White can do to prevent Black from reaching the ideal setup, and Black is already doing great. }
