{ Black has other moves, but I found this one to be the most satisfying.   To be clear, I don't necessarily think the bishop is amazingly placed on g4. But, it gets it off of c8, which means he can defend the e5-pawn with Nf6-d7 next without blocking it in, and then the bishop will come back to e6 later. }
7. h3
{ Obviously, chasing the bishop is a critical move. It cannot go all the way back to g6. }
7... Bh5 8. g4 Nxg4
{ No choice on this one- we were not going to let White take on e5 for nothing. }
9. hxg4 Bxg4
{ Black is a piece down, but has an incredibly powerful pin on the f3-knight and White is badly missing his light squared bishop. f7-f5 is on the way. }
10. Nbd2
{ This is too optimistic, as now White will defend against the kingside attack without his queenside pieces. }
10... f5 11. Qe1 O-O
{ White is facing a vicious attack with Rf8-f6 potentially on the agenda, and White already has to walk a tightrope not to lose immediately. }
12. Kh1 Rf6 13. Nh2 Rh6 14. f3 Bh3 15. Nb3 Rg6 16. Nxc5
{ If White had made any other move on his previous 5 decisions, he would already be dead and buried. Thanks to his good defense, now we make a draw. }
16... Bg2+ 17. Kg1 Bh3+ { The game ends with perpetual check. } *

