[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 9 - Berlin 4.d3 Bc5 without Bxc6"]
[Black "Introduction "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5
{ In this chapter, we will look at what happens when White plays 4.d3 but does not take on c6 next.   In general, Black would like to play Nc6-d4. This will force an exchange of the potentially misplaced c6-knight and allow him to push c7-c6 next to fight for a bigger share of the center. White can prevent this with c2-c3, but then we can respond by pushing d7-d5 and taking back with the queen. This is possible specifically because of c2-c3. White will not have Nb1-c3 to develop with tempo, and the d3-pawn can become a weakness.   There are a few forcing lines to know, but most of this chapter is reasonably strategic. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 9 - Berlin 4.d3 Bc5 without Bxc6"]
[Black "Berlin 4.d3 Bc5 with 5.Nbd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5
{ In this chapter, we will look at what happens if White chooses not to take on c6 and keeps the pawn structure unchanged, aiming to play something that looks a bit like an Italian. I don't find these options too scary. }
5. Nbd2
{ This move is actually quite challenging. Black is, in theory, unable to play d7-d5 as I would like to, but if he castles short, then White will be able to take on c6 and reach the dxc6 structure where Black has already committed to castling short. There is not a single spot in that entire chapter where this would be my plan. But, I think we can call the bluff and castle anyway, making use of quick development to justify capturing back with the b-pawn instead. }
5... O-O
{ Now, Black is ready for Nc6-d4 next without anything bad happening to him. If White prevents it with c2-c3, then d7-d5 transposes to the mainline, but Black also should be ready for Bb5xc6. }
6. O-O Nd4 { Black is ready for this move, and he easily equalizes. } 7. Nxd4
Bxd4 8. c3 Bb6 9. Nc4 d5 10. exd5 Qxd5 11. Nxb6 axb6 12. Bc4 Qd6
{ Black is obviously fine with Bc8-e6 coming next. I might even prefer his position in practice, though the machine insists on absolute equality. }
