[Result "*"]

{  } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5
{ In this chapter, we will look at what happens if White chooses not to take on c6 and keeps the pawn structure unchanged, aiming to play something that looks a bit like an Italian. I don't find these options too scary. }
5. O-O
{ This has been played a bit, but it strikes me as a poor version of 5.Nbd2.  Black is able to solve all of his problems by trading off the skeptical c6-knight. }
5... Nd4 6. Bc4 d6
{ This would be a normal Italian position, but Black got the move Nc6-d4 for free, something he basically never gets to do since White normally beats him to the punch with c2-c3.   As such, he has already solved the problem of the bad knight, and should be absolutely fine with O-O and c7-c6 coming next. }
