5... Nd4 6. Nxd4 Bxd4 7. c3 Bb6 8. d4
{ I think this position is actually quite dangerous for Black if White had played Nd2 instead of O-O. As is, because the e4-pawn is loose, Black is easily fine. After }
8... O-O
{ White is not able to take on e5 for free just yet, but if he burns a tempo on defending e4, Black will easily equalize with d7-d6. }
9. dxe5
{ 9.Nd2  d6=  White can hardly mantain his d4-pawn, and should take on e5 with sterile equality.   9.Re1?  Even in position like this one, one innocent looking move can lead to a disaster. It's amazing how bad White's position is after  9...d5!  when Stockfish insists Black is absolutely winning. }
9... Nxe4 10. Nd2 d5
{ The last important move. The position is very dry, and very equal. } *

