[White "Ch. 9 - Berlin 4.d3 Bc5 without Bxc6"]
[Black "Berlin 4.d3 Bc5 with 5.Ba4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5
{ In this chapter, we will look at what happens if White chooses not to take on c6 and keeps the pawn structure unchanged, aiming to play something that looks a bit like an Italian. I don't find these options too scary. }
5. Ba4
{ This move has been seen from time to time, but it doesn't scare me much. I am happy to castle, thanks in no small part to Bxc6 not being a thing. }
5... O-O 6. O-O d5
{ This is very similar to the c3 lines, but White has played Ba4 instead of c3. The only way he can try to make this work in his favor is to use the c3-square for his knight, but the lost tempo on Ba4 means Black is very fine. }
7. exd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3 Qd6 9. Nd2 Bg4
{ Black's queen will be well placed on e6 to avoid any harassment from the knights, and he got the bishop outside of the pawn chain first. Black is easily fine and can continue with moves like Rfe8 and Rad8, centralizing the rooks. }
