1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4
{ Now, we are finally at the main starting position of the proper Berlin Wall. White's two main tries here are the endgame and  5.Re1  , each of which has their own chapter, but there are some extraneous sidelines to be ready for.   A bunch of them come from  5.d4  ,  but where White does not force the endgame. They tend to be non-threatening and one prime example is the Qd4-e4-d4 draw that some particular players love to do as a sign of total disrespect to organizers, fans, and the game itself, but White does have some more feisty attempts at his disposal.   There's not much to know or be scared of here and it is a relatively short chapter, but are definitely things that Black should know. }
*

