[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 10 - Berlin 4.O-O Sidelines"]
[Black "Berlin 4.O-O Sidelines: 5.Qe2 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Qe2
{ This move has been tried from time to time, but it is far from intimidating. I like a slightly unusual response. }
5... Ng5 6. Nxg5 Qxg5 7. d4 Qe7
{ Now, White can take on c6, but this will leave us in the typical scenario that works so well- the dxc6 pawn structure with queens onboard, and Black castling long. }
8. dxe5
{ Now, Black has some sharp options with Nc6-d4, which should be fine, but I like a simpler solution. }
8... a6 { Nice and simple. White's bishop will get kicked around. } 9. Bc4
{ This would be the ideal square. } 9... Nxe5
{ But now Black wins a tempo on the bishop, and White is unable to make trouble on the e-file before we can deal with it. Furthermore, since the bishop is no longer on b5, we can bolster the knight with d7-d6 as needed. }
10. Bb3 d6 11. Re1 Be6
{ Just in time. Black clogs the d-file and is ready to castle long next. White should be careful not to become worse. }
