[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6
{ Now, White's main move by far is Bxc6, for obvious reasons. But, he does have a few miscellaneous options we should at least be ready for. }
6. Bg5
{ This odd move was tried against me once by Joel Benjamin. It's nothing to be overly concerned about. }
6... Be7
{ Black can reach a more adventurous position with f7-f6, but keeping in line with the plan of playing simple, solid chess whenever possible, I like this easy move. }
7. Bxe7
{ 7.dxe5  Nxb5  8.Bxe7  Qxe7  9.a4  d6  Transposes to the current variation. }
7... Qxe7 8. dxe5
{ This can be played without Bg5 and Be7 included, but here it is a bad version for White. }
8... Nxb5 9. a4 d6 10. e6 fxe6 11. axb5
{ This position with the dark squared bishops still onboard and the queen back on d8 is quite dangerous for Black, as his knight will lack a good square and he is a long way from castling.   As is, after  11...Nd8  he easily castles next. }
11... Nd8 { And White is just a pawn down. } *

