[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 10 - Berlin 4.O-O Sidelines"]
[Black "Berlin 4.O-O Sidelines: 5.d4 Nd6 with 6.Ba4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6
{ Now, White's main move by far is Bxc6, for obvious reasons. But, he does have a few miscellaneous options we should at least be ready for. }
6. Ba4
{ This has been tried a bit recently, and it is an interesting practical try, but Black has to be fine. }
6... e4 { This is the simplest solution. } 7. Ne5
{ 7.Re1  Be7  8.Ne5  Transposes. } 7... Be7 8. Re1 O-O 9. Nc3 f5
{ White certainly has some compensation for the pawn, but I don't think it is enough for an advantage. Black looks to take on e5 next, with Nf7 to follow. }
10. Bb3+
{ 10.Bf4  Kh8  White has nothing better than Bb3, transposingto 10.Bb3+. }
10... Kh8 11. Qh5
{ This prevents Nxe5 followed by Nf7, but it is hardly intimidating. Just be sure not to blunder mate on g6! }
11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qe8
{ The final important move. White has to trade queens, and Black is absolutely fine. }
13. Qxe8 Nxe8 14. Nd5 Bd8
{ White can't do much with his extra space and central control, and it isn't too hard to imagine him ending up a pawn down for more or less nothing once Black gets his pieces back in play.   The machine calls it equal but I'd be worried with White here. }
*

