[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 10 - Berlin 4.O-O Sidelines"]
[Black "Berlin 4.O-O Sidelines: 5.d4 Nd6 with 6.dxe5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6
{ Now, White's main move by far is Bxc6, for obvious reasons. But, he does have a few miscellaneous options we should at least be ready for. }
6. dxe5
{ This move is the favorite of the vultures of chess, looking to force a draw without playing a game.   Let me take this opportunity to make a simple and straightforward suggestion to avoid this problem: anyone who plays this move aiming for the 10 move draw should never be invited to another tournament. Playing the black pieces, there is not much you can do against opponents like that, and if you are aiming to play for a win on command with the black pieces against an opponent who specifically needs a draw, the Berlin is a poor opening choice.   We have to let the draw happen, but we also should pay heed to some of White's options down the line where he wants to keep the game going. }
6... Nxb5 7. a4 { Black loses his piece back, but equalizes easily. } 7... Nbd4
8. Nxd4 d5
{ Now, almost every game continues with exd6 and a prompt draw, but Black should be ready for a couple of other options. Still, there is nothing to be scared of, and long term his position is fantastic thanks to the overextended e5-pawn and his bishop pair. Most of the time White forces a draw here. }
9. Nxc6
{ If White wants to continue the game, this is his best way, but I think it is mostly just asking for trouble. }
9... bxc6 10. Nd2
{ This has been tried from time to time as well, but it strikes me as unimpressive. If Black can get castled, he has to be in good shape, but there are still some details to know. }
10... Be7 11. Nb3
{ Now, we need to not allow White to play Bc1-e3 to clamp down on the dark squares. }
11... c5 12. Na5
{ It's a little annoying to deal with the threat of Na5-c6, since neither Bc8-b7 or Bc8-d7 are possible, but I think I found a nice easy solution.   12.Be3?  Too late for this.  12...d4 }
12... d4
{ In the past, Black only ever tried Qd8-d7, which makes some sense, but leads to awkward coordination and can become vulnerable to f4-f5. I like gaining more space in the center, getting the pawns onto dark squares, and telling White to do his worst with Na5-c6. }
13. Qf3 Be6
{ Black is ready for Qd8-d5 next, and White is lucky to have a draw available. }
14. Qc6+ Bd7
{ 14...Kf8!?  This is a fine option to continue the game, though throughout this repertoire, I am not making any particular effort to prevent White from making a draw if he so desires. }
15. Qe4
{ Black can certainly take his chances with 0-0, but f4-f5 looks a little scary. I don't mind just ending the game immediately. }
15... Be6
{ White should make the draw with Qc6+ or else he will just be worse after Qd8-d5. }
