[Black "Berlin 4.O-O Sidelines: 5.d4 Nd6 with 6.dxe5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6
{ Now, White's main move by far is Bxc6, for obvious reasons. But, he does have a few miscellaneous options we should at least be ready for. }
6. dxe5
{ This move is the favorite of the vultures of chess, looking to force a draw without playing a game.   Let me take this opportunity to make a simple and straightforward suggestion to avoid this problem: anyone who plays this move aiming for the 10 move draw should never be invited to another tournament. Playing the black pieces, there is not much you can do against opponents like that, and if you are aiming to play for a win on command with the black pieces against an opponent who specifically needs a draw, the Berlin is a poor opening choice.   We have to let the draw happen, but we also should pay heed to some of White's options down the line where he wants to keep the game going. }
6... Nxb5 7. a4 { Black loses his piece back, but equalizes easily. } 7... Nbd4
8. Nxd4 d5
{ Now, almost every game continues with exd6 and a prompt draw, but Black should be ready for a couple other options. Still, there is nothing to be scared of, and long term his position is fantastic thanks to the overextended e5-pawn and his bishop pair. Most of the time White forces a draw here. }
9. Nxc6
{ If White wants to continue the game, this is his best way, but I think it is mostly just asking for trouble. }
9... bxc6 10. Qd3
{ This is the main move, for two reasons. First off, it prevents both Bf5 and Ba6, but it also discourages Be7 since it would run into Qg3, and Black is not in time to castle out of it. }
10... Qd7
{ I like this surprising move a lot. The main point is that Black wants to play Be7 next and to be ready to meet Qd3-g3 with Qd7-g4. }
11. Nd2
{ 11.b3  was seen in Nepomniachtchi, I. vs. Eljanov, P., see theModel Games chapter. }
11... Be7 12. f4
{ This has seen play from time to time and it makes perfect sense- go push f5 and give mate, what could be more natural. But Black has a nice way to keep things under control. }
12... a5
{ The threat of Bc8-a6 is very annoying to deal with, and White does not really want to leave the f-file with his rook, as then f4-f5 will not be a thing anymore. }
13. Qc3
{ The queen is not stable here. Black is already better after the next move. }
13... d4
{ When he can stick the queen on d5 next, which will make f4-f5 nothing more than a pipe dream thanks to the pressure on the e5-pawn. }
