[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 11 - Berlin 4.O-O Nxe4 5.Re1 "]
[Black "Introduction "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 Nd6
{ In this chapter, we will cover the 5.Re1 line. It is a very safe move for White as it leads to a symmetrical structure, but unlike some of the symmetrical lines truly fit for a chicken that we see before, this one can be a serious attempt to fight for an advantage thanks to the misplaced d6-knight. }
6. Nxe5
{ 6.Bf1  Be7  White has nothing better than taking on e5, transposing to the mainlines.   6.Ba4  Be7  7.d4  e4  8.Ne5  Transposes to the5.d4 sidelines chapter. }
6... Be7 7. Bf1 Nxe5 8. Rxe5 O-O
{ Black's default plan is Be7-f6, Rf8-e8, trade the rooks, and then fix the bad knight with Nd6-e8 and push d7-d5. If he pulls all of this off, he should equalize easily, but it is not the fastest plan and White has some serious attempts to prevent us from fixing our coordination.   There are some lines that just need to be memorized, and while this is not a fun variation for Black to face, he should be confident of equalizing if he knows what to do. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 11 - Berlin 4.O-O Nxe4 5.Re1 "]
[Black "Berlin 4.O-O Nxe4 5.Re1: 6.a4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1
{ This is a very safe move for White, and is frequently the one chosen by well prepared players who are looking to take no risks at all. Unlike some of White's other quiet and risk free attempts, this one is not entirely toothless, and Black will have to know his stuff reasonably well to equalize because his pieces start out a little discoordinated. }
5... Nd6 6. a4
{ This move has been tried a few times, but it doesn't make much sense to me. The bishop isn't so fantastic on b5 that it should be maintained. }
6... Be7 7. Nxe5 Nxe5 8. Rxe5 Nxb5 9. axb5 O-O
{ Black is very happy to have traded off the misplaced d6-knight, and he is absolutely fine. He can look to complete his development with d7-d6 and Bc8-e6. }
