[White "Ch. 11 - Berlin 4.O-O Nxe4 5.Re1 "]
[Black "Berlin 4.O-O Nxe4 5.Re1: 6.a4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1
{ This is a very safe move for White, and is frequently the one chosen by well prepared players who are looking to take no risks at all. Unlike some of White's other quiet and risk free attempts, this one is not entirely toothless, and Black will have to know his stuff reasonably well to equalize because his pieces start out a little discoordinated. }
5... Nd6 6. a4
{ This move has been tried a few times, but it doesn't make much sense to me. The bishop isn't so fantastic on b5 that it should be maintained. }
6... Be7 7. Nc3
{ White is aiming to play for compensation, not spending time taking on e5 but rather blasting open the center with d2-d4 and crashing through with Nc3-d5. I like giving the pawn back under good circumstances. }
7... a6
{ First, we kick the bishop away from c6. Once Black plays d7-d5, the bishop would have been annoying. }
8. Bxc6 dxc6 9. Nxe5 O-O
{ Even with a tempo spent on a7-a6, I prefer Black. Bishop pair in the long run, and White has nothing to show for it whatsoever. }
*

