{ This is a very safe move for White, and is frequently the one chosen by well prepared players who are looking to take no risks at all. Unlike some of White's other quiet and risk free attempts, this one is not entirely toothless, and Black will have to know his stuff reasonably well to equalize because his pieces start out a little discoordinated. }
5... Nd6 6. Nxe5
{ 6.Bf1  Be7  White has nothing better than taking on e5, transposing to the mainlines.   6.Ba4  Be7  7.d4  e4  8.Ne5  Transposes to the5.d4 sidelines chapter. }
6... Be7 7. Bd3
{ This retreat has been seen from time to time. It is a much more aggressive option for White, who is looking to launch a direct kingside attack with some combination of b2-b3, Bc1-b2, and Qd1-h5, when Black will obviously have to pay some attention to not get mated. But, it also blocks in the d-pawn and is a strategically dubious decision, so if Black doesn't get mated, he should be in good shape. And as far as I can tell, he does not get mated. }
7... Nxe5 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. Nc3 c6
{ Black prevents the knight from reaching d5. Next up, he will regroup with Nd6-e8 and d7-d5, a theme that will be seen a lot in the Re1 chapter. }
10. b3
{ 10.Qf3  Ne8  White has only ever played  11.b3  here, transposing to the 10.b3 lines. }
10... Ne8 { An important move. } 11. Bb2 d5
{ White's position looks very menacing, with seemingly all of his pieces ready to jump on the black kingside, but concretely, there is nothing to worry about. Black will kick the rook away with Be7-d6, and then can consider g7-g6 and Ne8-g7 to keep everything rock solid. Eventually, taking more space in the center may count for something. }
12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. Qh5
{ Now, just be careful not to blunder into mate with g7-g6, allowing Qh5xh7+. }
13... Nf6 { White is out of steam. } *

