[Black "Berlin 4.O-O Nxe4 5.Re1: 6.Nxe5 Mainline with 10.Bd3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1
{ This is a very safe move for White, and is frequently the one chosen by well prepared players who are looking to take no risks at all. Unlike some of White's other quiet and risk free attempts, this one is not entirely toothless, and Black will have to know his stuff reasonably well to equalize because his pieces start out a little discoordinated. }
5... Nd6 6. Nxe5
{ 6.Bf1  Be7  White has nothing better than taking on e5, transposing to the mainlines.   6.Ba4  Be7  7.d4  e4  8.Ne5  Transposes to the5.d4 sidelines chapter. }
6... Be7 7. Bf1
{ Now, the structure resembles the ED variation of the French Defense, which stands for exd5 and only exd5 and nothing else that might be abbreviated to ED. But, there is a key difference here. Black's knight on d6 is obviously misplaced, as it prevents his d-pawn from moving forward.   One bad piece makes a bad position, and if Black can fix the problem knight, he should be absolutely fine. But, White can try to prevent this from happening. }
7... Nxe5
{ Before anything else, Black should trade off the e5-knight before White can push d2-d4 to take back with the pawn. }
8. Rxe5 O-O
{ Now, if Black is able to play Nd6-e8 and d7-d5, he will equalize easily. White has to do something to try to stop this from happening. }
9. d4
{ This is the main move. White is hoping to advance d4-d5 before Black can play d7-d5 himself. }
9... Bf6 10. Bd3 { This is a bit too spirited to be any good. } 10... Bxe5
{ Of course Black takes the material. } 11. dxe5 Ne8 12. Qh5 g6 13. Qh6
{ This might look scary, but Black is safe enough. } 13... d5 14. Bg5 f6 15.
exf6 Nxf6
{ Black's position looks shaky, but White doesn't have any direct way through and the exchange will count sooner rather than later. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 11 - Berlin 4.O-O Nxe4 5.Re1 "]
[Black "Berlin 4.O-O Nxe4 5.Re1: 6.Nxe5 Mainline with 10.Re2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1
{ This is a very safe move for White, and is frequently the one chosen by well prepared players who are looking to take no risks at all. Unlike some of White's other quiet and risk free attempts, this one is not entirely toothless, and Black will have to know his stuff reasonably well to equalize because his pieces start out a little discoordinated. }
5... Nd6 6. Nxe5
{ 6.Bf1  Be7  White has nothing better than taking on e5, transposing to the mainlines.   6.Ba4  Be7  7.d4  e4  8.Ne5  Transposes to the5.d4 sidelines chapter. }
6... Be7 7. Bf1
{ Now, the structure resembles the ED variation of the French Defense, which stands for exd5 and only exd5 and nothing else that might be abbreviated to ED. But, there is a key difference here. Black's knight on d6 is obviously misplaced, as it prevents his d-pawn from moving forward.   One bad piece makes a bad position, and if Black can fix the problem knight, he should be absolutely fine. But, White can try to prevent this from happening. }
7... Nxe5
{ Before anything else, Black should trade off the e5-knight before White can push d2-d4 to take back with the pawn. }
8. Rxe5 O-O
{ Now, if Black is able to play Nd6-e8 and d7-d5, he will equalize easily. White has to do something to try to stop this from happening. }
9. d4
{ This is the main move. White is hoping to advance d4-d5 before Black can play d7-d5 himself. }
9... Bf6
{ It is possible to play Ne8 instead, but I am not convinced that Black will equalize after d4-d5. I like being a bit more direct. }
10. Re2
{ Magnus tried this move once, and it has to be taken very seriously. His point is that after the generally desirable Rf8-e8, White's queen will land on e2 rather than e1, and this causes some serious problems. As such, even though the move looks similar to Rf1-e1, we have to react differently. }
10... Nc4
{ I like this move a lot. Black takes advantage of the rook's placement on e2 and puts the knight on a square that would be unavailable in the mainline. The pressure on the b2-pawn means that d4-d5 is not possible, and Black is soon ready for d7-d5 himself. }
11. b3
{ This is surely the most challenging move.   11.Nc3  d5=  Black is totally fine. }
11... Nb6 12. Nc3
{ This is also possible, trying to prevent Black's knight from reaching d5.   12.c3  was seen in Fedoseev, V. vs. Kramnik, V., see theModel Games chapter. }
12... d5 13. a4 Bg4
{ Black was in time to get his bishop off of c8 before a4-a5 could come. This promises Black's knight a secure route back to an ideal post. }
14. f3 Be6 15. a5 Nc8
{ The problem knight regroups to d6 and Black is totally fine. } *

