{ This is surely the most challenging move.   11.Nc3  d5=  Black is totally fine. }
11... Nb6 12. a4
{ White chases the knight around a bit, and makes sure to do so before Black can play d5, get his bishop off of c8, and his knight back to c8 and then d6. It looks a little awkward but Black is fine with accurate play. }
12... Nd5 13. Re1 c6 14. c3
{ We are still following an Anand-Karjakin encounnter. } 14... Re8
{ A typical move, trading off the passive rook for the active one. } 15. Rxe8+
Qxe8 16. Qf3
{ Vishy was likely prepared to this point, and is playing all the best moves. Now, Karjakin's Nc7 was not bad, but I think there is an easier route to equality. }
16... Ne7
{ Black is ready for d7-d5 next, and then Ne7-g6 and Bc8-e6 will follow.   Stockfish gives white a small edge, but I have no idea why. Black has solved all of his normal problems connected to his uncoordinated pieces, and White has nothing great to play for. The longer the machine runs the closer it gets to zeroes, and Leela is not nearly as optimistic. I think Black should be fine. }
