[Black "Berlin 4.O-O Nxe4 5.Re1: 6.Nxe5 Mainline with 11.Bf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1
{ This is a very safe move for White, and is frequently the one chosen by well prepared players who are looking to take no risks at all. Unlike some of White's other quiet and risk free attempts, this one is not entirely toothless, and Black will have to know his stuff reasonably well to equalize because his pieces start out a little discoordinated. }
5... Nd6 6. Nxe5
{ 6.Bf1  Be7  White has nothing better than taking on e5, transposing to the mainlines.   6.Ba4  Be7  7.d4  e4  8.Ne5  Transposes to the5.d4 sidelines chapter. }
6... Be7 7. Bf1
{ Now, the structure resembles the ED variation of the French Defense, which stands for exd5 and only exd5 and nothing else that might be abbreviated to ED. But, there is a key difference here. Black's knight on d6 is obviously misplaced, as it prevents his d-pawn from moving forward.   One bad piece makes a bad position, and if Black can fix the problem knight, he should be absolutely fine. But, White can try to prevent this from happening. }
7... Nxe5
{ Before anything else, Black should trade off the e5-knight before White can push d2-d4 to take back with the pawn. }
8. Rxe5 O-O
{ Now, if Black is able to play Nd6-e8 and d7-d5, he will equalize easily. White has to do something to try to stop this from happening. }
9. d4
{ This is the main move. White is hoping to advance d4-d5 before Black can play d7-d5 himself. }
9... Bf6
{ It is possible to play Ne8 instead, but I am not convinced that Black will equalize after d4-d5. I like being a bit more direct. }
10. Re1 Re8
{ An important move. Black offers the exchange of rooks, and White doesn't have a great response. Taking on e8 will allow Black to recapture with the knight to get d7-d5 in next, and allowing Rxe1+ instead coule cost him the d4-pawn. }
11. Bf4
{ This move makes some sense, but still fails to impress. White develops a new piece and the threat of taking on d6 to cripple the structure strongly dissuades Black from taking on d4, but he can still equalize pretty easily. }
11... Rxe1 12. Qxe1
{ Now, Black should not get greedy and take on d4, as this would allow his structure to be butchered with Bf4xd6 and he would be hard pressed to find a way to get his light squared bishop into the game. Instead, Black should parry the threat and get ready for d7-d5. }
12... Ne8
{ Taking advantage of White's inability to play d4-d5 thanks to the hanging b2-pawn. White has nothing better than c2-c3, when Black will transposeto the mainline with d7-d5. }
*

