{ Now, the structure resembles the ED variation of the French Defense, which stands for exd5 and only exd5 and nothing else that might be abbreviated to ED. But, there is a key difference here. Black's knight on d6 is obviously misplaced, as it prevents his d-pawn from moving forward.   One bad piece makes a bad position, and if Black can fix the problem knight, he should be absolutely fine. But, White can try to prevent this from happening. }
7... Nxe5
{ Before anything else, Black should trade off the e5-knight before White can push d2-d4 to take back with the pawn. }
8. Rxe5 O-O
{ Now, if Black is able to play Nd6-e8 and d7-d5, he will equalize easily. White has to do something to try to stop this from happening. }
9. d4
{ This is the main move. White is hoping to advance d4-d5 before Black can play d7-d5 himself. }
9... Bf6
{ It is possible to play Ne8 instead, but I am not convinced that Black will equalize after d4-d5. I like being a bit more direct. }
10. Re1 Re8
{ An important move. Black offers the exchange of rooks, and White doesn't have a great response. Taking on e8 will allow Black to recapture with the knight to get d7-d5 in next, and allowing Rxe1+ instead coule cost him the d4-pawn. }
11. c3
{ This is the most common and most solid move, but it's pretty soft and should fizzle to equality soon enough. }
11... Rxe1 12. Qxe1 Ne8
{ Black is ready for d7-d5 next, and White is not ready to play d4-d5 himself. So, Black should be fine. }
13. d5
{ This is probebly the best try, but still nothing to be too concerned about. }
13... c6
{ White cannot maintain the d5 pawn, and has to either exchange on c6 or let it get taken. The latter is probably more challenging, but still hardly makes me quiver in my boots. }
14. Be3 cxd5 15. Qd2 Nc7 16. Na3 d6 17. Nc2 Bf5
{ Black should be fine. Oftentimes he is a bit worse but holding in positions like this one where he only has one weak d-pawn, and now he has a second d-pawn as well, which makes it much harder for White to get anywhere.   Next up he can play Ne6, taking advantage of the hanging c2 knight, and eventually even think of taking c2 and pushing d4. }
18. Nb4 { This looks scary. } 18... Be4 19. f3 a5
{ But the tactics favor Black. A position like this one shows why it is so nice to have two d-pawns. }
20. Nd3 { White should prefer this move, but Black is still very fine. } 20...
d4 21. cxd4 Bc6
{ The position has become symmetrical and simplified, and Black has somewhat more active pieces. }
*

