{ Before anything else, Black should trade off the e5-knight before White can push d2-d4 to take back with the pawn. }
8. Rxe5 O-O
{ Now, if Black is able to play Nd6-e8 and d7-d5, he will equalize easily. White has to do something to try to stop this from happening. }
9. d4
{ This is the main move. White is hoping to advance d4-d5 before Black can play d7-d5 himself. }
9... Bf6
{ It is possible to play Ne8 instead, but I am not convinced that Black will equalize after d4-d5. I like being a bit more direct. }
10. Re1 Re8
{ An important move. Black offers the exchange of rooks, and White doesn't have a great response. Taking on e8 will allow Black to recapture with the knight to get d7-d5 in next, and allowing Rxe1+ instead coule cost him the d4-pawn. }
11. Nc3
{ This is probably White's most challenging option. He brings his pieces out as fast as possible, hoping to take advantage of his lead in development while Black is busy fixing his d6-knight by retreating it to the back rank. }
11... Rxe1 12. Qxe1
{ Now, we are not in time to play the strategically desirable Nd6-e8, as White is too fast with Nc3-d5 in response. So we have to go pawn grabbing. }
12... Bxd4 13. Bf4 Ne8 14. Nd5
{ White is playing very energetically, and it is not too hard to imagine Black getting smashed by some combination of Qe4, Re1, and Bd3. Black should be very careful here. }
14... c6 15. Ne7+
{ 15.Rd1?!  Bc5!  The ship has sailed on Nd5-e7+, and White has to find some funky moves to not become worse. }
15... Kf8 16. Nxc8
{ Now, it looks like all is well in the world for White. Once Black takes back on c8, either Qe4 or Qb4 will recapture the lost pawn and leave him with a crushing position thanks to his lead in development and healthy bishop pair. Black has to play very energetically and precisely to stay in the game, but he is quite fine if he does. }
16... Qf6
{ A very important move. Black activates the queen and makes trouble on f2 before taking back the doomed knight on c8. }
17. Bg3 Rxc8 18. Qb4+ { Otherwise Black will remain a pawn up. } 18... d6 19.
Qxb7 Rc7 20. Qb8 Bxb2
{ White must take on d6 to equalize material, but Black is obviously fine in the resulting position as it is symmetrical and the bishop pair has been halved. }
21. Bxd6+ Qxd6 22. Qxb2 Re7
{ Nf6 comes next and Black hasn't a care in the world. } *

