{ It is important to flick this move in, pushing White's bishop back to g3 with a gain of tempo. Then, he will be able to play d7-d6 and Bd4-e5 without fearing for the bishop's safety after a subsequent f2-f4. }
20. Bg3 d6 21. c3
{ 21.h4  h6  White has nothing better than c2-c3 here, with similar consequences to 21.c3 on the previous move. }
21... Be5
{ Thanks to playing g7-g5, the bishop is safe here. White should force a draw before he ends up a pawn down. }
22. Bxe5 dxe5 23. Qd5 b6 24. Qxe5 Qxe5 25. Rxe5 h6
{ Have to make five more moves before shaking hands. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 12 - Berlin Endgame"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5
8. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ At long last, we are at the Berlin endgame. This is one of the richest endgames in all of chess, and in my opinion, it is also White's best chance to fight for an advantage against this repertoire.    Black has a wide range of plans available to him, but they can be broken down into two subcategories. Plans where his king goes to e8, and plans where his king goes to c8. The former is more solid, and the latter is more double edged.    I like to keep our strategy consistent, so I have chosen to play with Ke8. The only case I think that can be made for Kc8 instead is that it is a better way to play for a win. This may be true, but if your goal is to play for a win on command with Black, the Berlin was a horrible option in the first place. Between 5.Re1, the dxe5 draw line with Qd4-e4, and even some lines in the four knights, White has endless options to just force a draw if he wants it. If your goal is to win on command, I'd direct your attention to the Classical  Sicilian.    There are some key positional themes to know.   First off, Black generally should only agree to exchange dark squared bishops if  White has committed to playing h2-h3. This allows him to clamp the kingside with h7-h5-h4, rendering the pawn majority ineffective in a way it would not otherwise be.   Secondly, he often wants to meet Bc1-f4 with Bf8-e7, as now  Bf4-g5 to try to organize a bishop trade will cost White a tempo.   Thirdly, he often wants to meet Bc1-g5 with Bc8-e6, taking advantage of White's newfound inability to play Nf3-g5.   And finally, Black can often consider a more ambitious development scheme connected with b6, Bc8-b7, and c5 if White ever moves his c3-knight. The knight on c3 is good prophylaxis against this plan as  c6-c5 might be ill advised due to Nc3-d5 or Nc3-b5, attacking the weak c7-pawn,  but once it is gone, this plan becomes more credible.    The endgame is incredibly rich and we will see a lot more than just this in the chapter ahead, but this should be a good start to understanding some of the more important strategic themes. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 12 - Berlin Endgame"]
[Black "Berlin Endgame: 9.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5
8. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ This is the start of the Berlin Endgame, and in my opinion, White's best try to fight for an edge. The position is more unbalanced than the symmetrical structures we frequently come across in other lines, and both sides have their trumps.   Black has a healthy bishop pair and the e5-pawn is overextended, while White enjoys a better long term pawn structure as the 4 on 3 queenside majority is unable to give Black a passed pawn under normal circumstances, and White has a big lead in development. The endgame is very complex, and Black has several plans at his disposal for how to arrange his pieces.   The biggest question is what Black will do with his king, which surely cannot remain on d8. The most double edged plans involve trying to play Bd7 and Kc8, while the most solid ones tend to see Black's king going kingside instead. There's a long list of reasons I chose to recommend a plan with Ke8, but the biggest one is that it is much easier to be consistent and not have to remember a lot of move order tricks.   Generally speaking, the plan for Black is to play Ke8, Be7, and Be6. This may seem a bit risky upon a surface level examination because White will be able to play Bg5, halving the bishop pair.   It is very important to note that the inclusion of h2-h3 and h7-h5 is heavily in Black's favor when the resulting positions arise, and he should be a bit wary of allowing the bishop exchange if White has not included these moves. We will see a lot more strategic ideas later on down the lines, but this is a good place to start. }
9. Nc3
{ This is the old main move, and nothing could be more natural. White brings out a new piece and does not commit to h2-h3, which we will frequently see be a problematic advance for him. But it will be hard to avoid. }
9... Ke8
{ As always, our next move is Ke8. Now, by far White's two main moves are Rf1-d1 and h2-h3, which transpose to the 9.Rd1 and 9.h3 analysis, respectively, but he does have a couple miscellaneous tries. }
10. b3
{ This has been seen from time to time, but I think it represents a poor understanding of the Berlin Endgame from White's point of view. In general, I think the bishop is only well placed on b2 if Black's king has gone to c8 rather than e8, and this is not the case here. }
10... b6
{ I like this ambitious development of the c8-bishop. It will be extremely good on b7, and Black is taking advantage of White's bishop not coming to f4. As a result, he will not have to worry about any e5-e6 advances because the c7-pawn is not hanging. }
11. Bb2 Bb7
{ White's score from this position is atrocious, though I don't think he is worse just yet. Black goes along with his main plan we see in the mainline- some combination of Be7, h5, and Rd8. He need not fear a bishop exchange on g5 for obvious reasons, and the bishop is much better on b7 than it would be on e6. }
*

