[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch. 12 - Berlin Endgame"]
[Black "Berlin Endgame: 9.Rd1+ #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5
8. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ This is the start of the Berlin Endgame, and in my opinion, White's best try to fight for an edge. The position is more unbalanced than the symmetrical structures we frequently come across in other lines, and both sides have their trumps.   Black has a healthy bishop pair and the e5-pawn is overextended, while White enjoys a better long term pawn structure as the 4 on 3 queenside majority is unable to give Black a passed pawn under normal circumstances, and White has a big lead in development. The endgame is very complex, and Black has several plans at his disposal for how to arrange his pieces.   The biggest question is what Black will do with his king, which surely cannot remain on d8. The most double edged plans involve trying to play Bd7 and Kc8, while the most solid ones tend to see Black's king going kingside instead. There's a long list of reasons I chose to recommend a plan with Ke8, but the biggest one is that it is much easier to be consistent and not have to remember a lot of move order tricks.   Generally speaking, the plan for Black is to play Ke8, Be7, and Be6. This may seem a bit risky upon a surface level examination because White will be able to play Bg5, halving the bishop pair.   It is very important to note that the inclusion of h2-h3 and h7-h5 is heavily in Black's favor when the resulting positions arise, and he should be a bit wary of allowing the bishop exchange if White has not included these moves. We will see a lot more strategic ideas later on down the lines, but this is a good place to start. }
9. Rd1+
{ This is a reasonably common move, and a very sensible one if White does not want our king to go to c8. For our repertoire, this is not a real appeal for him since we are going to e8 anyway, but it still has some points to it. }
9... Ke8 10. Nc3
{ Now, Black is in a little bit of a tough spot. Since White has not played h2-h3, I really dislike playing Bf8-e7 and allowing a bishop exchange on g5. I think those positions can be quite dangerous for him if h2-h3 and h7-h5 has not been included. But, he has another option that I quite like. }
10... Ne7
{ Since White has not committed to h3, we have to do a different plan. Luckily, I think this is a very good version for Black. Normally, White's best option against the Ne7-g6 regrouping involves playing Ra1-d1 rather than Rf1-d1, and then he can play moves like Nf3-d4 and f2-f4-f5. Since he already committed the f-rook to d1, that ship has sailed. }
11. Nd4 Ng6 12. f4 Bg4
{ Black gets all of his pieces out with a gain of tempo, and moves like Bc5 and Rd8 could be coming sooner rather than later. White should be careful not to become worse. }
*

