9. Rd1+
{ This is a reasonably common move, and a very sensible one if White does not want our king to go to c8. For our repertoire, this is not a real appeal for him since we are going to e8 anyway, but it still has some points to it. }
9... Ke8 10. Nc3
{ Now, Black is in a little bit of a tough spot. Since White has not played h2-h3, I really dislike playing Bf8-e7 and allowing a bishop exchange on g5. I think those positions can be quite dangerous for him if h2-h3 and h7-h5 has not been included. But, he has another option that I quite like. }
10... Ne7
{ Since White has not committed to h3, we have to do a different plan. Luckily, I think this is a very good version for Black. Normally, White's best option against the Ne7-g6 regrouping involves playing Ra1-d1 rather than Rf1-d1, and then he can play moves like Nf3-d4 and f2-f4-f5. Since he already committed the f-rook to d1, that ship has sailed. }
11. h3
{ Now this move makes perfect sense. Normally, the inclusion of h2-h3 and h7-h5 is double edged, as it weakens the g5-square for Black but also gives him the option of h5-h4 to clamp down on the kingside structure. Now, Black can't quite get away with h7-h5 since Bc1-g5 will cause major problems. But, he should have a fine position all the same. }
11... Ng6 12. Be3
{ This is probably the best move, aiming for a quick Rd2 and Rad1 to get the last piece into the game. Black should be a little careful but I think he is quite fine. }
12... h5
{ I like playing a very similar plan to what we see in the mainline. Black is ready for h5-h4 and then he will be able to exchange dark squared bishops without fear, as he will always have h5-h4 ready to lock up the kingside, and furthermore, the rook on h5 will be put annoying pressure on the e5-pawn. Black is fine. }
