1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5
8. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ This is the start of the Berlin Endgame, and in my opinion, White's best try to fight for an edge. The position is more unbalanced than the symmetrical structures we frequently come across in other lines, and both sides have their trumps.   Black has a healthy bishop pair and the e5-pawn is overextended, while White enjoys a better long term pawn structure as the 4 on 3 queenside majority is unable to give Black a passed pawn under normal circumstances, and White has a big lead in development. The endgame is very complex, and Black has several plans at his disposal for how to arrange his pieces.   The biggest question is what Black will do with his king, which surely cannot remain on d8. The most double edged plans involve trying to play Bd7 and Kc8, while the most solid ones tend to see Black's king going kingside instead. There's a long list of reasons I chose to recommend a plan with Ke8, but the biggest one is that it is much easier to be consistent and not have to remember a lot of move order tricks.   Generally speaking, the plan for Black is to play Ke8, Be7, and Be6. This may seem a bit risky upon a surface level examination because White will be able to play Bg5, halving the bishop pair.   It is very important to note that the inclusion of h2-h3 and h7-h5 is heavily in Black's favor when the resulting positions arise, and he should be a bit wary of allowing the bishop exchange if White has not included these moves. We will see a lot more strategic ideas later on down the lines, but this is a good place to start. }
9. h3
{ In recent years, this has become the main move as it is White's best way to play against Black's plans involving Bd7 and Kc8. That is entirely irrelevant to us as our whole plan is to play with Ke8 anyway. }
9... Ke8
{ Same move every time.   9...h5  There is nothing wrong with this move order either, but I like starting with  Ke8  just for simplicity's sake.  Playing Ke8 against every single move just makes one less thing to remember. }
10. Nc3 h5
{ Black prevents g4, and can look to complete his development with some combination of Be7 and Be6, or potentially b6 and Bb7, depending on what White does.   According to my database, White has tried 12 different moves here. It is senseless to try to memorize all of them. What we need to do instead is look at the most critical ones, understand the subtle differences between moves like Bf4, Bg5, Rd1 first and then Bg5, serious moves like these, and then just trust ourselves to play the positions well once we understand the key themes if White resorts to something silly like Bd2 or a4 without burdening our memory any further. }
11. Ne2
{ This move has been tried from time to time and it makes a fair amount of sense. The knight obviously was not great on c3, and it can become quite good on f4. Furthermore, White is not yet sure where the bishop belongs, and he might want to put it on g5 rather than f4 if Black is too quick to commit to Be7. Still, I think Black is fine, and he can take advantage of the knight leaving. }
11... b6
{ This is a very ambitious development scheme for Black, aiming to bring the bishop to b7, where it will be much more active than it would be on e6. This is partially made possible by the knight leaving c3, which makes it much easier to advance c6-c5 without worry about the knight jumping to b5 or d5. }
12. Bg5
{ This is probably the best move. Black needs to be a bit careful, but he should be fine. }
12... Bb7 13. Rad1 c5 14. Nc3
{ White voluntarily burns two tempi, but is hoping to make use of the weakened b5 and d5 squares to cause concrete problems for Black. }
14... Be7 15. Nd5
{ This is the most challenging move, chopping the bishop pair in half. } 15...
Bxd5 16. Rxd5 Rd8 17. Rxd8+ Bxd8
{ Now, so far only Rd1 has been played here, but in my opinion, it is not best. }
18. Bxd8 Kxd8 19. Rd1+ Ke7 20. g3
{ White managed to get what he wants. He traded off the bishop pair, exchanges a bunch of pieces, and did so while still being able to play g2-g3 before allowing Black to clamp the kingside with h5-h4. Black's position is very difficult if he does not know the next move, which solves his problems directly. }
20... Rg8
{ It turns out that g7-g5-g4 comes just in time to give Black counterplay before White can consolidate. }
21. Kg2 g5 22. g4 hxg4 23. hxg4 Ng7
{ The knight comes to e6 next, and White's majority has been rendered ineffective once again. The last thing Black needs to know is that after }
24. Nxg5 Nh5 { He wins his pawn back and everything is under control. } *

