{ I like this move a lot. The main point is that we want to get the rook off of the d8-square so that Nf7 will not hurt. For example, if White tries to execute his threat and kick our bishop, after }
15. b3
{ White should probably prefer a quiet move like this one, blunting the e6 bishop and waiting for another day to make direct threats, but it is hardly intimidating. }
15... h4 16. Rad1 { Pointing out that a2 is no longer hanging. } 16... Rxd1 17.
Rxd1 Bd5
{ A typical motif. Black often wants to get the bishop to the long diagonal when White puts his knight on e4, and this is a good moment for it. }
18. Re1 Kd7 19. c4 Bxe4 20. Rxe4 Ke6
{ As always, the h4-pawn renders White's kingside majority ineffective, and Black is absolutely fine. White has no plan whatsoever. }
