18. Rd1 { 18.Nxe6+  Rxe6  White must play Rd1, transposing to the mainline. }
18... c5 19. Nxe6+ Rxe6 20. Nb5 Kc8
{ All of this was seen in Vachier-Lagrave against Karjakin at the recent World Cup. White can win a pawn for the moment, but it proves to be not enough against a good defense. }
21. Nxd4 cxd4 22. Rxd4 g5
{ An important move. The bishop is kicked back to a passive square on g3 or h2 to avoid losing the pawn on e5. }
23. Bg3
{ And now that the bishop is passive, Black can go after the weak pawns. }
23... Ra6 24. a4 Rc6 25. c3 Rb6
{ White is unable to keep his pawns defended without the help of the bishop. This is exactly the kind of position where we see why including g7-g5 and Bf4-g3 was so important. Bf4-c1 would be a nice move for White here! }
26. Rd2 { This is the only way White can save his pawns. } 26... Ra6 27. b3 Rb6
28. Rb2 Rc6 29. c4
{ Finally, White has reached a position where all of his pawns are protected, but his pieces are far too passive for him to have any winning chances. }
29... a6
{ This is the easiest. Black gets ready for b5 next, will land his rook on c3, his king on e6, and it is a very easy draw. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Carlsen, M. vs. Karjakin, S., New York WCh 2016"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. d4
{ For the very first illustrative game, I am choosing one where the very first move takes us outside of the scope of our repertoire! The reason is to show the kind of frustration white players can face when bashing their head against the Berlin Wall over and over again.   Magnus was undoubtedly a much stronger player than Karjakin at the time of their match- in fact, he has always been a much stronger player. When a stronger player, who knows he is a stronger player, gets frustrated enough with the Berlin, they can end up making a lot of rash decisions, as Magnus did this game.   I honestly believe that Karjakin's strong preparation in the Berlin and his ability to shut down the greatest player of all time contributed just as much to this victory as the moves he played. }
1... Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3
{ What is this? Already, it's clear that Magnus is tilted. He surely had better ideas to fight for an advantage within 1.d4 than some Colle system.   3.c4  Of course this would have been a more serious move. }
3... e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. b3 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Bb2 b6 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 Bb7 10.
Qe2 Nbd7 11. c4 dxc4 12. Nxc4
{ The position is quite level and boring. The structure is obviously not what we would see in the Berlin, but Karjakin's eventual victory in a dry looking position shows that even when we reach a symmetrical and dull position in our repertoire, it's still a game of chess and things can still happen. }
12... Qe7 13. a3 a5 14. Nd4 Rfd8 15. Rfd1 Rac8 16. Rac1 Nf8 17. Qe1 Ng6 18. Bf1
Ng4 19. Nb5 Bc6 20. a4 Bd5
{ Not much has happened so far. Finally, some incongruent piece trades are coming, but they don't break the balance. }
21. Bd4 Bxc4
{ 21...Bxd4  This was more in line with the 'dry the game up at all costs' strategy that Karjakin often employed during the match, but he has to be given credit for mixing things up when he felt the time was right. }
22. Rxc4 Bxd4 23. Rdxd4 Rxc4
{ This is by far the most notable moment of the game. } 24. bxc4
{ This move is not a huge mistake per se, but obviously a very risky decision. White accepts 2 isolated pawns, and if a knight ever makes it to c5, he will have some major problems to solve.   The machine still claims it is equal, but it shows that Magnus, who is normally a very risk averse player, is starting to make rash decisions. I have to believe the frustration of dealing with the Berlin game in and game out was a big factor in why he chose to make this move. I don't see it happening under more normal circumstances. }
24... Nf6 25. Qd2 Rb8
{ I like this move. Black could not fight back on the d-file without straightening the pawns, and now he is void of any weaknesses and can look to maneuvre one of his knights to c5. }
26. g3 Ne5 27. Bg2 h6 28. f4 Ned7
{ Heading for the promised land. Already Magnus has to be accurate to not become seriously worse. }
29. Na7
{ This is White's only chance. A knight on c5 would have been a nightmare to deal with, and now things get messy. }
29... Qa3 30. Nc6 Rf8 31. h3
{ Magnus makes another seriously risky move.   31.Rxd7!  This was a draw. I'm sure Magnus saw it and evaluated it correctly, but was tilted into taking more risks than was appropriate.  31...Nxd7  32.Qxd7  Qxe3+  33.Kf1  Qc1+  34.Kf2  Qc2+  The game ends with a perpetual check. }
31... Nc5 { Now a4 is fallying and it is up to White to show his counterplay. }
32. Kh2 Nxa4 33. Rd8 g6 34. Qd4 Kg7 35. c5
{ I'm sure Magnus missed 37...Qa4 later on.   35.Rd7  This would have just barely held the balance. After something like  35...Nc5  36.Ra7  White has threats like g4-g5, and reasonable counterplay. The computer screams draw, but anything could happen in human play. }
35... Rxd8 36. Nxd8 Nxc5 37. Qd6
{ Qe7 is a big threat, and Black could have stopped it and won easily. } 37...
Qd3
{ 37...Qa4!  White can't stop the queen from reaching d7, and he may as well resign. No tricks, game over. }
38. Nxe6+ { Well spotted. White is back in the game. } 38... fxe6 39. Qe7+ Kg8
40. Qxf6 a4 41. e4 Qd7 42. Qxg6+ Qg7 43. Qe8+
{ Now White should be making a draw, but he has to be careful. } 43... Qf8 44.
Qc6 Qd8 45. f5 a3 46. fxe6 Kg7 47. e7 Qxe7 48. Qxb6 Nd3 49. Qa5
{ 49.e5  White needed to open the bishop. After  49...Nxe5  50.Bd5=  I can't imagine him losing. }
49... Qc5 50. Qa6 Ne5
{ With the bishop locked in, White looks more or less done for. The machine finds saving resources, but the best human ever was unable. }
51. Qe6 h5 52. h4 a2
{ White resigned rather than face the music after Ng4+ and Qg1. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Rublevsky, S. vs. Adams, M., 31st ECC Open 2015"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6 3. d3 Nc6 4. Nc3 Na5 5. Qf3
{ This strikes me as a bit weird. I don't love the queen on f3, normally she is better placed on d3 after the inevitable capture on c4. In Chapter 2 we faced5.Nf3 and5.Nge2. }
5... c6
{ I like how Adams does not rush to take the bishop. It is not going anywhere. }
6. Nge2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. h3
{ 8.a3  White could have chosen this move to spare himself from what came next, but now of course Black grabs the bishop.  8...Nxc4  9.dxc4  d6  The queen feels misplaced to me and would rather be on d3. Black can hope to expand with Bc8-e6, a7-a6, and b7-b5. He looks a little more comfortable to me but the game goes on. }
8... d5
{ Well spotted. Black takes the entire center and gains a lot of time doing it. }
9. exd5 b5 10. Bb3 b4 11. d6
{ 11.Ne4  Nxd5⩱  f5 is coming next and Black has a nice position with a big center. }
11... Qxd6 12. Nd1 Bb7 13. Ne3 c5
{ Black's pieces are springing to life and he has a much bigger share of the center. Adams still has not touched the b3-bishop, as it still is not threatening to escape. }
14. Qg3 Qd7 15. Ba4
{ Rublevsky finds a little tactic to trade off the bad bishop, but this does not solve his issues.   15.Qxe5  Bd6!  16.Qf5  Qc6  Black's Marshall-esque compensation is through the roof. It is surprisingly difficult to stop the direct threat of Rfe8 and Rxe3. }
15... Qe6
{ 15...Qxa4?  16.Nf5  White wins his piece back, with interest.   15...Bc6  This looked strongest. After  16.Bxc6  Nxc6  Black is a bit better with his extra space. }
16. b3
{ 16.a3!  This needed to be played. White opens the a-file and gets some much needed activity. }
16... Nd5 { Black gets ready for f7-f6, blunting the b2-bishop. } 17. Bb2 f6
18. Rae1 Bd6 19. Nxd5 Qxd5 20. f4
{ White does what he needs to do. Adams' play has been far from perfect and he is a little worse here, but the position remains very solid and his extra space could matter. }
20... Bc6 21. fxe5 Bxe5 22. Nf4 Qd6 23. Bxe5 fxe5 24. Nh5 Rxf1+ 25. Rxf1 Qg6
26. Bxc6 Nxc6 27. Qxg6 hxg6 28. Ng3
{ Despite Black's imperfect play, he never was in any real trouble, and this endgame is not so bad. White's queenside could become weak, and Adams pounces right away. }
28... a5 29. Ne4 Nd4 30. Rf2 a4 31. Nxc5 a3 { Nb5-c3 is on the way. } 32. Nd7
Re8 33. Nb6 Rd8 34. Kf1 Nb5 35. Na4 Rc8 36. Ke1 Nd4 37. Kd1
{ It looks like White is just about consolidated and can look for Nb6-c4 next, but... }
37... Rc6 { Now he can barely move! } 38. h4 g5 39. hxg5 Kh7
{ Funnily enough, despite the two pawns up, White is dead lost. He is entirely paralyzed and none of his piece can move. Black simply brings in the king and takes the kingside. }
40. Kc1 Kg6 41. c3
{ This obviously loses, but what else could he even try? Just wait for Kg3 to come? }
41... bxc3 42. b4 c2 43. Nc5 Rb6 44. Rf1 Rxb4 45. Nb3 Nxb3+ 46. axb3 Rxb3 47.
Kxc2 Rb2+ 48. Kc3 Rxg2 49. Re1 a2 50. Kb3 Kf5 51. Ka3 Rd2 52. Kb3 g6
{ Not a perfect game from Adams by any stretch, but some phases he played extremely well. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Hou, Yifan vs. Carlsen, M., Wijk aan Zee 2013"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3
{ I'm not sure why Hou felt it was a good idea to play a funky sideline against the World Champion, but it did allow Magnus to put on a clinic. }
3... Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. e5 Nd5 6. Bc4 Nb6 7. Bb3 d5
{ I really like this move, and this game was my inspiration for choosing it againstthe 3.c3 line. }
8. cxd4
{ 8.exd6  This was probably the more prudent choice, but already, White is in damage control mode. }
8... Bg4 9. Be3 f6
{ 9...Qd7  Just castling long directly looks more natural to me. Magnus did it soon enough anyway. }
10. O-O Qd7 11. h3 Bh5
{ White is in a tough spot. Leaving the pawn on e5 forever should eventually lead to its capture, pushing it to e6 looks like it will be weak as well, but taking f6 opens the g-file! There are already no good options. }
12. e6 { 12.exf6  gxf6-+  Rg8 and Bd6 are coming. White should get mated. }
12... Qd6 13. Nc3 O-O-O 14. a4 a5
{ Keeping it solid. The e6-pawn is not going anywhere, and there is no need to allow a4-a5. }
15. Nb5 Qxe6 16. Bf4 Rd7 17. Re1 Qf7 18. Rc1
{ Black basically just looks like he is a pawn up. To Hou's credit, she almost managed to make a game out of it. }
18... Bb4 19. Re3 g5 20. Bh2 Nc4
{ This feels a little rushed, but it should not change the result.   20...Bg6  I can't come up with any sensible move for White, or any decent plan to make any progress. In the meantime, the h-pawn is coming. }
21. Bxc4 dxc4 22. Qc2 Bxf3 23. Rxf3 Nxd4 24. Nxd4 Rxd4 25. Be5 Rd2 26. Qf5+ Qd7
27. Qxf6 Re8
{ Now Hou gets some pawns of her own, but Black's will be better. } 28. Bg3 Rd4
29. Rf1 g4 30. hxg4 Rxg4 31. Rf4 h5 32. Rxg4 hxg4 33. Rc1 c3 34. bxc3 Bc5 35.
Qg5 b6
{ Even now, with equal material, the game is still effectively over. White's position is rife with weaknesses and Black's king is much safer. }
36. c4 Re4 37. Qg6 Re2 38. Kf1 Qd2 39. Qxg4+ Kb8 40. Qxe2 Qxc1+ 41. Qe1 Qxc4+
42. Qe2 Qxa4
{ Black will win the race. His pawns are further advanced and White's bishop is getting in the way. }
43. Be5 Bd4 44. Bxd4 Qxd4 45. g4 Qd5 46. Qe8+ Kb7 47. Qa4 b5 48. Qxa5 Qd1+ 49.
Qe1 Qxg4 50. Qe5 Qc4+ 51. Kg2 Qc6+ 52. Kf1 b4
{ Black's b-pawn is much faster than the f-pawn, and the c-pawn shields his king from checks. The game is over. }
53. f4 b3 54. f5 Ka6 55. Qa1+ { 55.f6 } 55... Kb6 56. Qh8 Qc1+ 57. Kg2 Qc2+ 58.
Kh1 b2 59. Qb8+ Ka5 60. Qa7+ Kb4 61. Qb7+ Ka3 62. Qf3+ Qb3 63. Qa8+ Qa4 64.
Qf3+ Ka2 65. Qd5+ Ka1 66. Qe5 c5
{ Finally, the c-pawn has its day. White can't do a thing about Ka1-a2 and then c5-c4. Out of checks and out of luck. }
*

[Event "?"]
