42. Nxd5+ Rxd5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Short, N. vs. Kramnik, V., London Chess Classic 2011"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Nd4 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. e5 dxc3 7. exf6 Qxf6
8. dxc3 Bc5
{ 8...Qe5+  I recommended this movein the course. Kramnik's choice is fine too. }
9. Qe2+ Qe6 10. O-O O-O 11. Qf3 d6 12. Bg5 Qf5
{ The position surely looks boring, and we see a lot of these throughout the course. Black can't be unhappy with equalizing easily, but the dry nature of the resulting positions can be somewhat unappealing to players looking to win despite ceding the first move. Just remember, it is a chess game, and things can happen, as they did right here. }
13. Be7
{ It looks tempting to grab an exchange, but it was a poisoned exchange and now White is already more or less busted.   13.Qxf5  Bxf5  14.Bd3  Something like this should be preferred, and the game remains very level. }
13... Qxf3 14. gxf3 a6 { It turns out the rook is poisoned. } 15. Ba4
{ 15.Bxf8?  axb5  16.Be7  f6!  The bishop is trapped on e7, and will be captured. White is done for.   15.Bd3  This was the last chance, though White is obviously a bit worse after  15...Re8  16.Rfe1  Bh3⩱  The kingside pawn structure is less than appealing. }
15... b5 16. b4 { 16.Bxf8  bxa4  17.Be7  f6  Again, the bishop will be lost. }
16... Re8 17. Rfe1 Bb6 18. Bb3
{ White's position is wretched in any case, but Kramnik found a lovely way to end all discussion. }
18... Bb7 19. Kg2 d5
{ The bishop is entombed forever. White is absolutely done for, and Black can play as if he is a piece up. }
20. Re5 c6 21. Rae1 Bc7 22. R5e2 Bc8 23. a4 Bd7 24. Bh4
{ Step one, trade all the rooks. } 24... Rxe2 25. Rxe2 Re8 26. Rxe8+ Bxe8 27.
Bg3 Bd8 28. Be5 f6 29. Bb8 Bg6 30. axb5 axb5 31. Kf1 Kf7 32. Ke2 Ke6 33. Ke3
Bb6+ 34. Ke2 Bh5 35. Ba2
{ Now, White is reduced to moving his bishop back and forth. It might keep c2 safe, but Black can simply win the game on the kingside as he is effectively a piece up. }
35... g5 36. Bb3 f5 37. Ba2 f4 38. Bb3 Kf5 39. Bd6 g4 40. Kf1 g3 41. fxg3 fxg3
42. Bxg3 Bxf3 43. Ba2 Be3
{ Bf4 comes next, and White will get a pawn endgame down a piece. Of course Short did not have to lose like this, but it goes to show even strong players can go down in these dry positions with just one questionable move. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Kramnik, V. vs. Anand, V., Wijk aan Zee 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. d3
{ Kramnik plays a line that looks pretty toothless, keeping the symmetry, but the game quickly became a huge mess. This one reminds me a bit of Magnus's game with Karjakin- Kramnik knew the Berlin was coming, chose a less than critical line, and soon started making some rash seeming decisions. }
5... a6 6. Nd5 h6 7. c3 d6 8. h3 Ba7
{ Thus far, Anand is followingthe repertoire. } 9. a4 Be6
{ 9...Nxd5  This was fine too.  10.Bxd5  Qf6  Black prevents d4, and he looks fine to me. He could even consider g5 next. }
10. a5 { This is a risky decision. White will struggle to defend the d5 pawn. }
10... Bxd5 11. exd5 Ne7
{ Black gave up the bishop pair, but the bishop on c4 doesn't inspire and the d5-pawn will be hard to defend. }
12. d4 exd4
{ Anand had other options, but there was nothing wrong with this move. } 13.
Nxd4 O-O 14. g4
{ The machines laugh at this move and claim Black is much better. They certainly underestimate the practical danger Black may face and it is not nearly as simple as it may look as g4-g5 is not messing around, but Kramnik had to understand that this was risky, if nothing else.   14.O-O  According to the machine, this was the way. After  14...Nexd5  15.Qf3  Bxd4  16.Bxd5  Nxd5  17.Qxd5  Be5  18.Qxb7  The position looks quite equal. Kramnik probably wanted something more feisty. }
14... Nexd5 15. Kf1 Qd7
{ This is good prophylaxis against g5 because h3 will need defense. } 16. h4
{ 16.g5  hxg5  17.Bxg5  Rae8  Black's attack is stronger than White's. It's a real problem that Rg1 is not possible thanks to the h3-pawn hanging. }
16... Bxd4
{ This move looks a little surprising, but it turns out that White will struggle to deal with the queen landing on c6. }
17. Qxd4 Ne7 18. Be2
{ 18.g5  Good or bad, this had to be played.  18...Nc6!  19.Qd1  Ng4  The machines love Black here, but at least it is getting messy. }
18... Qc6 19. Rh3 Qd5
{ There was no need to be so desperate about trading the queens.   19...d5!  20.g5  Qe6!  White's position is too loose to organize his pieces properly. After something like  21.Qd3  hxg5  22.hxg5  Ne4  It is very hard for White to even move. Bd2, Be3, Bf4 all lose a piece, f3 is not possible... What to do? }
20. Qxd5 Nfxd5 21. Bf3 c6 22. Ra4
{ The bishops offer White some compensation here. Still, a pawn is a pawn, and Vishy is well known to love his knights! }
22... b5 23. axb6 Nxb6 24. Re4 Rfe8 25. g5 hxg5 26. Bxg5 f6 27. Bc1 d5 28. Rg4
Nc4
{ White is hard pressed to make counterplay. Eventually the pawn should count. }
29. Be2 Ne5 30. Rf4 Kf7 31. h5 Rh8 32. Ra4 a5 33. b3 Rab8
{ 33...Nc8  Getting the knight to b6 to force a5-a4 through would have made sense. Black would then get the c4-square for his knights. }
34. Bd1 Rb5 35. Bc2 c5
{ I like this decision. c4 comes next and Black will make a passed pawn. } 36.
Rah4 c4 37. bxc4 Nxc4 38. Kg2 Rc5 39. Rg3 Rcc8 40. Rhg4 Rcg8 41. Rh3 Ra8 42.
Rhg3 Rxh5
{ Vishy declines the draw, and for good reason. The king will be quite safe on e6, and the a-pawn is coming. }
43. Rxg7+ Ke6 44. Ba4 Rah8 45. Bf4 Rh2+ { Now Who is attacking who? } 46. Kf1
{ 46.Kf3  Ne5+  The fork on f5 forces White to take the knight, but after  47.Bxe5  fxe5  Black is absolutely winning. }
46... Rh1+ 47. Ke2 Ra1 48. Bb5 Ra2+ 49. Kf1 Rh1+ 50. Kg2 Raa1
{ White's king is really starting to feel the heat. } 51. Bxc4 Nf5
{ A nice final touch. White is up a piece for the moment but will lose a boatload in the coming moves. Black is threatening mate on h4, and once is it prevented, all of the pieces are hanging. }
52. Bxd5+ Kxd5 53. Kf3 Nxg3 54. fxg3 a4 55. Kg4 a3 56. Ra7 a2 57. Kf5 Rh2
{ A fine effort from Vishy. } *

