[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. d3 Nf6 5. O-O O-O 6. c3 d5 7. exd5 Nxd5 8.
Re1 Bg4 9. Nbd2 Nb6 10. Bb5 Bd6
{ Much like we'll see in theWei-Vidit encounter, White got himself into serious trouble here thanks to Black's pawn center. He really needs counterplay, and Hikaru did not get it. }
11. h3 Bh5 12. Ne4 Re8 { 12...f5!  isour repertoire. } 13. Bg5 f6 14. Be3 a6
15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Ng3 Bf7
{ White is in a tough spot. He has no good way to threaten Black's queenside pawns, and his own d3-pawn could become a serious weakness. You might say, why not push d4? Then, e5-e4 would lead to a central avalanche. }
17. c4
{ Wei also ended up playing this move... because what else can be done? I'm sure Hikaru was not thrilled about it.   17.d4  e4  18.Nd2  Bg6  The f-pawn is coming, and it will cause massive problems sooner rather than later. }
17... Bb4 18. Re2 Bf8 19. b3 c5
{ Black fixes the d3-pawn. White's position is entirely miserable. } 20. Qe1 a5
21. Rd1 a4 22. Nd2 Qd7 23. Nb1 axb3 24. axb3 Bg6 25. f3 Rad8 26. Qf2 Qc6 27.
Red2 Nd7 28. Nc3 h6 29. Kh1 Kh8 30. Nb5 Bh7 31. Ra2 f5 32. Bc1 Nf6 33. Nc3 Qb7
34. Rb2
{ Black has been patiently maneuvreing for awhile, but now it is time to set his pawn mass in motion. }
34... g5 35. Rb1 Qc6 36. Bb2 Kg8
{ White is completely stuck and without any activity. Hikaru's next move did not help matters, but what can be do? Just sit and wait to die as Black doubles on the d-file? }
37. Nf1 Nh5 38. Nd5 Qd6 39. Ng3 c6 40. Nc3 Nf4 41. Qf1 Nxd3
{ It's a testament to Hikaru's resourcefulness that he almost managed to make a game out of this. White is obviously dead to rights. }
42. Nce2 Qe6 43. Bc3 Rd6 44. Rd2 Red8 45. Rbd1 Bg6 46. Nc1 Nxc1 47. Rxd6 Bxd6
48. Rxc1 Rb8 49. Ra1 Rxb3
{ 49...e4  I would think this is an easier route to the full point. Get the pawn to e3 first, ask questions later. }
50. Ra8+ Rb8 51. Ra6 Bf8 52. Qe2 Bg7 53. Ra7 Re8 54. h4 gxh4 55. Nf1 f4
{ This gives White some fortress chances, but Grischuk eventually broke it down all the same.   55...Bf7  Why not this? Grab another pawn, no counterplay, no fortresses. }
56. Nd2 Re7 57. Rxe7 Qxe7 58. Ne4 Bf7 59. Kh2 h3 60. gxh3 Qe6 61. Qg2 Kh7 62.
Qc2 Kh8 63. Qb2 Kh7 64. Qc2 Qg6 65. Qe2 Be6 66. Qf1 Bf5 67. Qe2 Qh5 68. Nf2 Qh4
69. Ne4 Qxh3+ 70. Kg1 Qh5 71. Be1 Bxe4 72. Qxe4+ Qg6+ 73. Kh2 Qxe4 74. fxe4
{ White's king will be annoying on h3, but Black should be able to break through. }
74... Kg6 75. Kh3 Kh5 76. Bh4 f3 77. Bf2 Bf6 78. Be1 Bg5 79. Bf2 Be7 80. Be1
Bd8 81. Bg3 Kg5 { Zugzwang. White must allow the king in. } 82. Bxe5
{ Grabbing a pawn hardly helps.   82.Bh2  f2!  83.Kg2  Bf6  84.Kxf2  Kg4  Black shoves the pawn to h3, and White cannot keep everything together. }
82... Bf6 83. Bd6 f2 84. Kg2 Bd4 85. Kf1
{ 85.e5  Kf5  This pawn is not going anywhere } 85... Kg4 86. Ke2 h5 87. Kf1 h4
88. Bh2 h3 89. Ke2 Be3 { Bf4 comes next, and Hikaru had seen enough. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Sethuraman, S. vs. Wen Yang, Asian Continental 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. O-O O-O 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 Be7 8. Bg3
d6 9. a4
{ Illustrative games can be just as much about showing what not to do as they can be about showing what to do. Black will eventually be worse here if he does not make some kind of counterplay. White should be able to slowly but surely push for d4. I believe Black needs to look for counterplay by playing Kh8, then either Nh7 or Ng8, and f5. }
9... a5
{ 9...Kh8  is the move I recommended inour repertoire; it looks much more natural to me. For example, after  10.a5  a6  11.c3  Nh7  f5 is coming, and Black looks fine. }
10. c3 g6 11. h3 Nh5 12. Bh2
{ Now, White will get d4 in next without allowing f5. Black did not get his necessary counterplay, and the extra space in the center will matter. }
12... Bg5 13. Na3 Bf4 14. d4 Qe7 15. Re1 Kg7
{ 15...Bxh2+  This should have been preferred, but White is undoubtedly still better after  16.Kxh2⩲ }
16. g3
{ A very impressive decision from Sethu. White locks in his own bishop, but he knows it will get out someday. }
16... Bg5 17. Bf1 Kh7 18. Nc4 Ng7 19. Qc2 Bf6 20. Rad1
{ Black really is having trouble moving. His pieces are too clumsy. } 20... Ne8
21. Ne3 Bg7 22. Nd5 Qe6 23. g4
{ The dead bishop woke up once Black's pieces were all beaten backwards. White has all the space and Black still has zero active moves available. }
23... exd4 24. Nxd4 Nxd4 25. cxd4 c6 26. Nb6 Rb8 27. Qd2
{ Black is totally powerless to stop the simplest of threats, such as grabbing the a5-pawn. }
27... Qe7 28. Qxa5 Qc7 29. Qb4 Qd8 30. e5 Be6 31. exd6 Nf6 32. Bg2 h5 33. gxh5
Nxh5 34. d5 cxd5 35. Nxd5 Qg5 36. h4 Qf5 37. Ne7 Qf6 38. Be5 Qxe5 39. Rxe5 Bxe5
40. Bd5 Nf4 41. Bxe6 fxe6 42. Qe4
{ After taking all the space, Sethu put on a clinic. Don't allow yourself to suffer like this! Get f5 in while you can. }
