1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. d3 Nf6 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d5
{ Vidit is well known for being really well prepared, and this was the case some years back well before he broke 2700 as well. He really showed a lot of class this game. }
7. exd5 Nxd5 8. Nbd2 { 8.Re1  I think this is a more challenging move. } 8...
Nb6 { Black chases the bishop on c4. } 9. Bb5 Bd6
{ And he defends the pawn on e5. Sooner or later, it is hard to imagine the b5-bishop not exchanging itself for the c6-knight. The queenside structure will become crippled, but this will hardly matter once Black is getting f7-f5 in and starting the attack. }
10. Re1 Bg4 11. h3 Bh5 12. Ne4 f5 13. Ng3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Qd7
{ This is whereour repertoire line ends. White's position is surprisingly difficult. Black will just go Rae8, get the rooks behind the pawns, and start pushing them at an inupportune moment. And how will White activate his pieces? Bc1 and Ng3 are really lacking and scope. }
15. a4 a6 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. c4
{ This only makes more weaknesses, but what else could White have done? } 17...
Rab8 { Vidit jumps on the weakened b-file. } 18. a5 Nc8 19. c5 Bxc5 20. Rxe5
Bd4 21. Re1 Nd6
{ The machine reads equal, but this seems like a very hard position for White to play thanks to the weak squares on the d-file and b-file, plus the lagging development and stuck bishop on c1. I'm surprised that he is not worse. }
22. Ne2 Rfe8 23. Bf4
{ 23.Rb1  Apparently this sort of held on. One cannot blame Wei Yi for wanting to be a bit more active. }
23... Bxb2 24. Rab1 Nb5 { Well spotted. The tactics favor Black. } 25. Ng3
{ 25.Rxb2?  Nd4!  Black wins material. } 25... Bc3 26. Rxe8+ Rxe8 27. Be3 g6
28. Qd1 Bxa5 29. Ra1 Bb6
{ 29...f4!  This won immediately. I imagine time pressure was involved.  30.Rxa5  fxe3-+ }
30. Bxb6 cxb6 31. Rxa6 f4 32. Ne2
{ 32.Nf1!  This would have been safer. White is almost back in the game. }
32... f3 33. Nf4
{ 33.Ng3  Apparently, this still was holding, though it looks super scary for White. }
33... Nd4 34. Ra1 { 34.Rxb6  Qc7  Black wins a piece. } 34... Rf8
{ Wei had seen enough. The game was not perfect, but it really showed the trouble White can face if Black is able to play d7-d5 in one move and White does not get anything to show for it. }
