1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Be7 6. d4 Na5 7. Bd3 d6 8. dxe5
dxe5 9. Nxe5 Nf6 10. O-O O-O 11. Nd2
{ This move looks really weird to me- the knight seems misplaced. Black already can consider playing for an edge, and I like how Rodshtein managed to eventually make use of his better structure.   11.Qc2  was examined inour repertoire. }
11... Nd7
{ 11...Ng4!?  The machine is a fan of this move, pointing out that the knight is immune from capture thanks to the hanging bishop on d3. }
12. Nxd7 Qxd7 13. Qc2 Rd8 14. Be2 Qc6
{ White's position already looks difficult to me. In the long run, the queenside weaknesses will matter, and I don't really see the kingside majority leading to any kind of attack anytime soon. }
15. f4 b6 16. e5 Bb7 17. Bf3 Qb5 18. Ne4 Bc5+
{ I like forcing this transformation. } 19. Nxc5 Qxc5+ 20. Qf2
{ 20.Kh1  This was preferable, but after  20...Qc4!  With Rd3 on the way, White's position is hardly a bed of roses. }
20... Qxf2+ 21. Kxf2 Bxf3 22. Kxf3 Rd3+ 23. Ke2 Rad8
{ The final accurate move. Black does not bother taking c3- it is not going anywhere. White's queenside pawns are forever weak, the c4-square is a fantastic outpost, and the kingside majority will not offer any attacking chances without queens onboard. }
24. f5 Rxc3 25. Bf4 Rc2+ 26. Kf3 Rd3+ 27. Ke4 Ra3 28. Rad1 Re2+ 29. Kd5 Rc3 30.
Rfe1 Rc5+ { Rodshtein made it look easy. } *

