1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 d5 6. exd5 Qxd5 7. Bc4 Qd6 8. b4
Bb6 9. a4 O-O 10. Nbd2 Bf5 11. Ba3 e4 12. dxe4 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Qxd6 cxd6
15. O-O-O Rac8 16. Bd5 Bxd5 17. Rxd5 Ne5 18. Nxe5 dxe5 19. Kb2
{ Kryvoruchko is a well prepared guy, and he surely know his stuff up to here. Black's position looks very dangerous since White's pawn mass is move advanced, but with a nice tactical resource, he ends up fine. }
19... Rfd8 20. Rxe5 Rxc3 { This is whereour repertoire line ends. } 21. Rd1
{ 21.Kxc3  Bd4+= } 21... Rcc8 22. Rxd8+ Rxd8 23. Re7
{ Now, it looks like Black's queenside is about to collapse, but his bishop is too good. The best White can hope for is to take b7, but then he will not get a7 as well. He will push the 2 on 1 majority, but Black can always sacrifice his bishop for the last pawn. In the meantime, the rook will ransack the kingside. }
23... h5
{ The machine is not impressed with this move, but I think it is good enough. }
24. Rxb7 Bxf2 25. b5 Rd5
{ h4 and Rg5 is coming. White will lose too many pawns to hope to win the game. }
26. Bb4 h4 27. a5 Rg5 28. a6 Rxg2 29. Kb3 Rxh2 30. b6
{ Now, we see the value of the f2-bishop. White was unable to kick it away, and now it can be sacrificed. }
30... Bxb6 31. Rxb6 h3
{ The h3-pawn is super dangerous, but once White takes care of it, he loses a6. }
32. Rb5 Re2 { The easiest. } 33. Rh5 Re6 34. Rxh3 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Kryvoruchko, Y. vs. Bacrot, E., 43rd Olympiad 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 d5 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. O-O dxe4 8.
dxe4 a5 9. Qe2 Qe7
{ Thus far, Bacrot is followingthe repertoire. Black has surely equalized with no trouble, but how do you play for a win in these positions? Basically, show a lot of patience, and maneuvre slowly and wait for your chances. Even very strong players often make mistakes in dry positions like this one. }
10. Ba4 h6
{ 10...Nb8  This would be more consistent with the repertoire. Bacrot eventually executed this regrouping anyway, but there was nothing wrong with doing it immediately. }
11. Nc4 Bd7 12. Ne3 Bxe3 13. Qxe3 Nb8
{ I like it! Black plays consistently with the plan I was hoping for. } 14. Bc2
Na6 15. b3 Rfd8 16. Nh4 Be6 17. Re1 Nb8
{ But this I cannot abide by. Why spend 2 tempi to reroute the knight to a6, and then two more to send it right back to c6?   17...Qc5  This looks much more natural to me. Black has reasonable queenside counterplay, and if the queens get exchanged, the knight will look pretty silly on h4. It's possible Bacrot was worried about Qg3, but after  18.Qg3  Nh5!  19.Qf3  Nf4!  Black is quite fine. }
18. h3 Nc6 19. Bd3
{ 19.a4!  White should have taken this opportunity to get the bishop to a3, fixing one of his last bad pieces. To this point, Black has been totally outplayed- it goes to show that good players can still see very dull and dry looking positions turn south fast, on either side. Things are not always as drawish as they look. }
19... Kh8 20. Bb5 Na7 21. Bf1 Nc6 22. Qf3 Nh7 23. Qg3 Ng5 24. f4 exf4 25. Bxf4
{ The position surely does not look dry anymore! Black has really been outplayed. But, one of the nicest things about the Berlin is that it is so solid that getting outplayed for a bit usually leaves you with a worse position, not a lost one, and Bacrot is not done fighting. }
25... Rd7 26. Kh2 Rc8 27. Bd3 Rcd8 28. Bc2 Qc5 29. Re2 Ne7 30. Rae1 Nh7
{ Black's position looks very scary, but how do you actually break through? The machine claims White is basically winning, but it also is suggesting moves like Rf1 or Bc1... It's not clear how to actually bring the point home. }
31. Nf5 Bxf5 { 31...Ng6  This looks safer. } 32. exf5 Nf6 33. Re5
{ This must have been a miscalculation of some kind. } 33... Qa3 34. Bc1 Qxa2
35. Rxe7 Rxe7
{ 35...Qxc2!  White will have to be careful not to lose immediately. } 36. Rxe7
Qxc2 37. Rxf7 Rg8 38. Bf4 Qxf5
{ I suspect that Kryvoruchko was counting on moving his bishop here and missed Ng4+. The tables have turned. }
39. Kh1 Qb1+ 40. Kh2 Nh5 41. Qg4 Nxf4 42. Qxf4 Qxb3 43. Rxc7 a4 44. Qf3 b5 45.
Ra7 Qe6 46. Qf4 Rd8 47. Qc7 Qf6 48. c4 Rd6 49. Qc8+ Kh7 50. Qg4 Qe5+ 51. Qg3
Qxg3+ 52. Kxg3 bxc4 53. Rxa4 Rc6 54. Ra2 Kg6 55. Kf4 c3 56. Rc2 Rc4+ 57. Ke3
Kg5 58. g3 h5 59. Kf3 Kf5 60. Ke3 Rc7 61. Kd3 Kg5 62. Ke3 Kf5 63. Kd3 Rc6 64.
Ke3 Ke5 65. Kd3 Kd5 66. g4 hxg4 67. hxg4 Ke5 68. Re2+ Kf4 69. Kc2 g5 70. Rg2
Kf3 71. Rg1 Rc5
{ Bacrot certainly did not play a brilliant game, and he was outplayed from the get-go. Still, I think there are two main lessons to learn from this one.   First off, these dry, equal positions remain playable for both sides, and even very strong players can make mistakes and give chances.   Second, it's a huge asset for the Berlin that you tend to only end up worse if you get outplayed, as opposed to lost, as you often will be in a less solid line. }
