[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Nakamura, H. vs. Topalov, V., Hamburg FIDE Grand Prix 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. h3 Nd7
{ I don't love blocking the bishop in. But, what I am really going to show here is again, how much nicer Black's king is on the queenside.   6...Be6  This would be more consistent withour repertoire. }
7. Bg5 f6 8. Be3 Bxe3 9. fxe3 Qe7 10. Nc3 b6
{ This is certainly an unusual development scheme for the bishop, and one we cannot count on it our repertoire if White plays better, but it works like a charm here. The king will be absolutely safe on b8. }
11. O-O Bb7 12. Nh4 g6 13. Qe1 O-O-O 14. a3
{ Hikaru aims to open lins on the queenside. We should already know how well that will work out. }
14... Kb8 15. b4 c5 16. Na4
{ 16.bxc5  Nxc5-+  White's position is rife with weaknesses and Black is dead winning. Note that it is only because of Black's additional pawn in front of his king that this works. For example, after  17.a4  a5!  Black is able to make this move while keeping b6 well defended. An extra pawn around the king is super helpful! }
16... Bc6 17. Nb2 Rhg8
{ White's queenside play is non existant, and Black will slowly but surely prepare f5. }
18. Rd1 Rdf8 19. c4 f5 20. b5 Bb7 21. exf5 gxf5 22. Rd2 Qg5
{ Hikaru's position is almost too ugly to look at. The difference in kign safety is on full display. And what is that knight doing on b2? }
23. e4 fxe4 24. Rxf8+ Nxf8
{ Themes can persist deep into the middlegame. Topalov reroutes the knight to e6. His play in the subsequent moves was not that incisive, but he even if he could have won faster, he never let Hikaru back into the game. }
25. dxe4 Ne6 26. Nf3 Qh5 27. Kh2 Nd4 28. Qe3 Bc8 29. Ne1 Qg6 30. Ned3 Re8 31.
Nd1 Qg8 32. N3b2 Be6 33. Qd3 Rd8 34. Qc3 h5 35. Rf2 h4 36. a4 Qg6 37. Qe3 Rg8
38. Kh1 Qh5 39. a5 Kc8 40. Qe1 Rg3 41. Qf1 Kd7 42. Nd3 Ke7 43. N1b2 Rg8 44. a6
Qg5 45. Qg1 c6
{ I like this move. Black liquidates the doubled pawn, because why not? White has no counterplay, so he may as well maximize his advantages. White's king is unsafe, c4 is weak, and now a6 will be weak too. }
46. bxc6 Nxc6 47. Rf1 Qg3 48. Qf2 Qxf2
{ 48...Bxh3  worked, but this is so much easier and more human. No counterplay whatsoever. }
49. Nxf2 Rd8 50. Nfd1 Rd2 51. Rf2 Rxf2 52. Nxf2 Na5 53. Kh2 Nxc4
{ We're done here. } 54. Na4 Kd6 55. Nc3 Kc6 56. g3 hxg3+ 57. Kxg3 b5 58. Nd3
b4 59. Na4 b3 60. h4 Bf7 61. Kg4 Bg6 62. Nc3 b2 63. Kf3 Kd6 64. Nb5+ Kd7 65.
Nxb2 Nxb2 66. Nxa7 Bh5+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Petrosian, T.L. vs. Hovhannisyan, R., 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O Qe7
{ This is not my recommended move, but White's play let Black transpose into the kind of setup I am aiming for.   6...Bg4  This is therecommended move. }
7. Be3
{ 7.c3!  This move is certainly the most challenging, and I am not convinced Black will equalize. }
7... Bg4 8. Nbd2 Nd7 9. h3 Bh5 10. Qe1 O-O-O
{ Black got the setup I am hoping to achieve- castling long in conjunction with Qe7 and Nd7. Now, White should not be worse yet, but watch how alarmingly unsuccessful a queenside pawn avalanche proves to be. Having 4 pawns in front of the king is super helpful. }
11. a3 Kb8 12. b4 Bxe3 13. fxe3
{ This is asking for trouble.   13.Qxe3  This should be preferred, though Black is surely fine. I'd suggest the typical regrouping maneuvre we often see in this line.  13...Nf8  With f6 and Ne6 coming next, Black looks happy enough. }
13... g5
{ Now the difference in pawn structure is on full display. White's king is much less safe than his Black counterpart, simply due to the quantity of pawns in front of him. }
14. Qg3 f6 15. Rf2 Rdg8 16. Raf1 g4 { Black's position plays itself. } 17. Nh4
gxh3 18. Qxh3 Bg4 19. Nf5 Bxf5
{ This felt unnecessary, but Black is still much better.   19...Qe6  White is toast. Black can even run in and take the queenside if he is so inclined. }
20. Rxf5 h5
{ This one I do not understand.   20...Rg7  Double rooks on the g-file and attack looks easy enough. White still has a lot of problems to solve. }
21. Rxh5 Rxh5 22. Qxh5 Qg7 23. Qf3 Rh8
{ Now White has a pawn for his suffering, and trading off a pair of rooks surely will help his king stay safer. }
24. Kf2 a6 25. Nb3 Rh6 26. Qg3 Rg6 27. Qh3 Rh6 28. Qg3 Rg6 29. Qh3 Rh6 30. Qf5
{ It was a very risky decision to decline the draw.   30.Qg3  This was prudent, though it's normal to get a bit too ambitious if you were worse the whole game and suddenly have a reasonable position. You end up comparing the quality of the position in front of you to the one you had before, rather than looking at the one in front of you at face value. }
30... Qe7 31. Qg4 Ka7 32. Qg8 f5
{ I'm sure these were some time trouble shenanigans. } 33. exf5 Nf6 34. Qc4
{ 34.Qg3!  White is safe enough, and material up. } 34... Qg7
{ Now, the final point to note- even now, going after Black's king is totally useless. The pawns keep him protected. Despite Black's far from perfect play, the white king is the only one that will face issues. }
35. Na5 Ka8 36. Ke2
{ One understands Petrosian's desire to evacuate, but this loses on the spot.   36.Qc5  The machine insists on absolute equality, though I think a draw might be the least likely result. The game goes on. }
36... Qxg2+ 37. Rf2 Qg1
{ Just like that, White is mated. Rh1 will not be prevented. } 38. Qe6 Qg4+ 39.
Ke1 Kb8
{ Taking one tempo off to stop Qc8, with mate. White's king is not going anywhere. }
40. Qxe5 Rh1+ 41. Rf1 Qh4+ 42. Ke2 Rh2+ 43. Kd1 Qg4+
{ White resigned rather than letting the queen to e2. This was a far from perfect game, but I think it clearly illustrates how much less safe White's king is than his black counterpart in the event of castling queenside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Wei Yi vs. Navara, D., Wijk aan Zee 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This game is an example of what not to do. There are ways where Black can play a plan with O-O rather than O-O-O in the d3/Bxc6 lines, but I don't like them. It always feels like White gets some kind of attacking chances, and hopefully this game will traumatize you enough to convince you to castle long! }
1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nbd2 O-O
{ 6...Be6  This ismy recommendation, aiming to castle queenside. } 7. Nc4 Nd7
8. Qe2 Re8 9. Bd2 Bd6 { Things might look normal so far. Until... } 10. h4 c5
11. h5 h6 12. O-O-O Nb8 13. Rdg1 { 13.g4!  This was already possible. } 13...
Nc6
{ 13...Bg4  This was a must, stopping the g4 advance for the moment, but after  14.Ne3  White is surely better. Black will have to let his bishop pair be exchanged and still has a lot of problems to solve. }
14. g4
{ Navara has not played the best moves. We can criticize him all we want, claim that he should have regrouped with Nf8-e6 rather than Nb8-c6, but what he did looked normal enough. Push c6-c5 to increase his central control and reroute the knight towards d4. But, the next thing you know, Black is immediately checkmated. I think his king is much safer on the queenside in these positions. }
14... f6 15. g5 { Of course. } 15... fxg5 16. Nxg5 Nd4 17. Qd1 hxg5 18. Bxg5
Be7 19. Be3 Bf6 20. h6 Re7 21. hxg7 { The rest was unnecessary. } 21... Rxg7
22. Qh5 Be6 23. Bh6 Bf7 24. Bxg7 Bxh5 25. Bxf6+ Kf8 26. Bxd8 Ne2+ 27. Kb1 Nxg1
28. Bxc7
{ It's a miracle Navara did not get mated, but here he ends up down a small amount of material. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Fedoseev, V. vs. Kramnik, V., Wijk aan Zee 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ If we are covering the Berlin, including Kramnik's last classical victory is an absolute must! This was the penultimate round of Tata Steel, his final tournament before retirement. Sadly, he lost to an absolute moron in the final round, but he put on a fine display in game 12. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1 Nxe5 8.
Rxe5 O-O 9. d4 Bf6 10. Re2
{ 10.Re1  This is the more common move, and Black has to react differently to equalize. It does prevent Nc4, for obvious reasons! }
10... Nc4
{ Kramnik was the first player to find this move, which is certainly good enough for equality. White cannot prevent d7-d5 from coming shortly. }
11. b3 Nb6 { We are still followingour repertoire. } 12. c3 d5
{ At low depths, the machines still think White is slightly better here, but they gravitate closer to equality as they run. There is no reason for Black to be worse, and I quite like the regrouping Kramnik played with Be6 and Nc8-e7. }
13. Re1 Re8 14. Rxe8+ Qxe8 15. a4 Be6 16. Na3 Nc8
{ Fixing the bad knight. It will look much better on d6 or e7. } 17. Bf4 Qd7
18. Bd3 c6 19. Nc2 Ne7 20. Qd2 Bf5
{ Black has comfortably equalized. The position looks super dry and boring, but as we will often see in these annotated games, that does not mean it is a dead draw. There is a lot of play left, and even a player as strong as Fedoseev managed to ruin his own position. }
21. Nb4 Ng6 22. Bg3 Re8 23. a5 h5
{ Kramnik gains space on the kingside. Fedoseev may have started regretting putting his knight all the way on b4 and pushing a2-a4-a5, as it looks like the other side of the board will be more relevant. }
24. h3 h4 25. Bh2 Bxd3 26. Nxd3 Qf5 27. a6 b6
{ White has a tough position. Black controls the only open file and can look for Bf6-g5 next. }
28. Bd6
{ 28.Re1  In hindsight, this was surely the better move, but it's not an easy one to make. For example, after  28...Rxe1+  29.Nxe1  Qc8  30.Qe2  b5!  White will have to worry about losing the a6-pawn. The computer claims it is equal, but there is still some fight left. }
28... Bg5 29. Qd1 Qe4 30. Ra2 Qe6 31. Bc7
{ White's position looks a little fragile due to Black's activity, but he has no weaknesses yet. Kramnik changed that right away. }
31... c5
{ The pawn is immune from capture, and Black can consider pushing c5-c4 next to kick away the d3-knight. }
32. Qg4 { 32.dxc5  bxc5  33.Nxc5?  Qc6  Black wins a piece. } 32... Qe7 33.
dxc5 bxc5 34. Ba5
{ 34.Ra1!  According to the machine, this was absolutely the only move. And it's incredibly hard to find! And after  34...Bd2  Black is still better all the same. }
34... Ne5 { Well spotted. } 35. Nxe5 Qxe5
{ Bf4 is coming next and White is in serious danger of getting mated. Fedoseev overprotected the back rank in advance, but it did not save him. }
36. Ra1 Re6
{ So simple. White's bishop has no squares, so saving the a6-pawn turns out to be easier said than done. }
37. Rd1 Bd2 { Fancy, though not totally necessary. } 38. Qxh4 Rxa6 39. g3
{ 39.Qd8+!  Kh7  40.Bc7!  This would have given White some saving chances. I'm sure some time pressure was involved. }
39... f6 { 39...Rf6!  Apparently this was a winner. Qe2 is on the way. } 40.
Bc7
{ 40.Qa4!  White missed a very computerish resource on the last move before time control. Surprisingly, his position holds together here. }
40... Qxc7
{ The dust has settled, time control is reached, and Black's attack is decisive. }
41. Rxd2 Ra1+ 42. Kg2 Qe5 43. Qf4 Qe1 44. Kf3 Qh1+ 45. Kg4 Re1
{ White's king will not survive the coming onslaught. } 46. Qd6 Qe4+ 47. Qf4
Qh1 48. f3 Re5 49. h4 a5
{ A rather sadistic move. White is almost in zugzwang! His queen and king have no moves, his rook cannot leave the defense of d1, and no pawns can move either. }
50. Rd3 { 50.Ra2  Qd1! } 50... Kf7
{ Black overprotects the f6 pawn to get ready for g5. This prevents Re3. } 51.
Qd2 { 51.Re3  g5!  Since White cannot take on f6, he may as well resign. }
51... Kg6 52. Re3 Rg5+
{ When Kramnik is playing well, it is a real delight to witness. He had a rough final tournament, but this was a fantastic game. }
53. Kf4 { 53.hxg5  Taking the rook leads to mate.  53...Qh5+  54.Kf4  Qxg5 }
53... Rf5+ 54. Kg4 Rg5+ 55. Kf4 Qh3
{ Another powerful move. Black threatens mate on both f5 and g3. } 56. g4 Qxh4
{ The attack continues, and Black is up a pawn as well now. } 57. Qc2+ Kf7 58.
Re2 g6 59. Qd1 Re5 { The simplest. Black forces a trivially won pawn ending. }
60. Rxe5 Qh2+ 61. Ke3 Qxe5+ 62. Kd3 d4 63. Qd2 dxc3 64. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 65. Kxc3
{ The extra pawn is easily decisive. } 65... Ke6 66. Kc4 Kd6 67. f4 Kc6 68. f5
gxf5 69. gxf5 Kd6 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Gashimov, V. vs. Nielsen, P. H., FIDE World Cup 2011"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5
8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Rd1+ Ke8 10. Nc3 Be7
{ While this is not a mistake per se, and some strong black players have chosen this move, it is definitely riskier. I really don't like allowing the exchange of dark squared bishops if we don't have h5-h4 against h2-h3.   10...Ne7  This ismy preferred move. }
11. Bg5 h6 12. Bxe7 Nxe7 13. Nd4 Bd7 14. Rd3 Rd8 15. Rad1 Nd5 16. Ne4 Nf4 17.
R3d2 Ke7 18. f3
{ This is exactly the kind of position I am really hoping to avoid. Since White was able to leave his pawn back on h2, he can easily play Kg1-f2, g2-g3, Kf2-e3, and set his majority in motion. The same kind position with h2-h3 and h6-h5-h4 included, as we will often see in the repertoire, is a totally different story as White will not be able to play g2-g3. }
18... Bc8 19. Kf2 Rhe8 20. g3 Nh3+ 21. Ke3 Ng5 22. f4 Nxe4 23. Kxe4
{ Up to this point, Gashimov has played a fine game. His pawn majority is healthy and advancing, Black has no counterplay, and his position generally looks very difficult to me. Still, it is a testament to the solidity of the Berlin that he is only worse here, and not lost yet. }
23... g6
{ 23...Bg4  This looks tempting to me as well. After  24.Nf5+  Bxf5+  25.Kxf5  g6+!  26.Ke4  f5+!  27.Kf3  Rxd2  28.Rxd2  Ke6⩲  White is undoubtedly better, but breaking through will not be easy. }
24. f5 Rxd4+
{ 24...Rd5  The machine prefers this one, but after  25.g4  With Nf3 coming next, White just looks better. I certainly understand why Peter chose to change the character of the game instead. }
25. Kxd4 Bxf5 26. Kc3
{ Black is still solid, but he has no direct counterplay and an exchange is an exchange. Gashimov eventually broke through. }
26... a5 27. a3 Be6 28. Rd4 c5 29. Rf4 h5 30. b4 axb4+ 31. axb4 Ra8 32. bxc5
Ra3+ 33. Kb2 Ra2+ 34. Kb1 Ra5 35. Rb4 Rxc5 36. Rxb7 Bf5 37. Rd2 Be4 38. Ra7 Ke6
39. Re2 Kxe5 40. Ra4 f5
{ Peter has defended very well, but the position remains difficult. some material has left the board, but White has no weaknesses for Black to attack, and he can still hope to get the a4-rook behind the kingside pawns. }
41. Ra6 g5 { 41...c6!  This was a must. } 42. Rg6 g4 43. Rh6
{ Now the kingside starts to fall. } 43... Kd4 44. Rxh5 Bf3 45. Rd2+ Ke3 46.
Rd3+ Kf2 47. Kb2
{ White is ready for Rc3 next, trying to engineer a rook exchange. } 47... Be4
48. Rc3 Rb5+ 49. Kc1 c6 50. Rh8 Kg2 51. Rc4 Re5 52. Rd4 Bf3 53. Rd2+
{ Now h2 is safe and the other rook is free to roam. } 53... Kg1 54. Kb2 Re3
55. Rh7 Be4 56. Rd1+ Kg2 57. Rd2+ Kg1 58. Re7 Kh1
{ It'd hard to defend a miserable position forever.   58...Kf1!  This would still have offered some saving chances. }
59. Rf2 { Black cannot stop Rxf5. } 59... Kg1 60. Rxf5 Bxc2 61. Rf1+
{ The rook was lost anyway, so White makes sure to keep the enemy king as far from his h-pawn as possible. }
61... Kxf1 62. Rxe3 Bd1 63. Kc1 Bf3 64. Re5 Kg1 65. Rh5 Bg2 66. Kd2 Bh3 67. Ke3
Kxh2 68. Kf2 { Just in time. The game is over. } 68... c5 69. Rxc5 Bg2 70. Rc4
Bh3 71. Ra4 Kh1 72. Ra1+ Kh2 73. Rg1
{ The key lesson to take home here is not to exchange dark squared bishops if we have not already gotten h5-h4 in, and if White has not pushed h2-h3. }
