[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Kamsky, G. vs. Shankland, S., Saint Louis 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5
8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Rd1+ Ke8 10. Nc3 Ne7
{ Long before I did the Chessable Lifetime Repertoire, I had decided this was the best way to play against a check on d1. Once Black's knight gets to e6, it becomes super hard for White to make any progress. }
11. h3 Ng6 12. b3 Bd7 { So far, we are still followingour repertoire. } 13. Ne2
Be7 14. Bb2 Nf8 15. c4 Rd8 16. Nfd4 h5
{ It's important for Black to gain this space and prevent g4.   16...Ne6  17.f3  Now White is able to play g4 next, and his majority is healthier. }
17. f4 { 17.f3  h4!  Of course Black does not allow g2-g4. } 17... h4 18. Bc3
Rh5
{ Stopping any hope of f5. From here on out, I basically sat tight in a perfectly solid position, and let Kamsky frustrate himself. }
19. Be1 a6 20. Bf2 Bc8 21. Be3 Rd7 22. Kf2 Rd8 23. Nc3 Ba3 24. Rab1 Be7 25.
Rbc1 Ba3 26. Rb1 Be7 27. Kf3 Ng6
{ 27...f6!?  This could have been tried, and the machine even claims I am a little better. I missed the chance, but we can sort of see how Black often ends up better in the Berlin Endgame by simply sitting solidly and waiting for White to miscoordinate his pieces. }
28. Nde2 Nf8 29. Rxd8+ Bxd8 30. Rd1 Be7 31. Ne4 Ne6 32. Nd4 Nf8 33. Kf2 Bd7 34.
Nf3 Ne6
{ White did not manage to make any progress at any point, and here he allowed an immediate draw. }
35. Nfg5 Nxg5 36. Nxg5 Bxg5 37. fxg5 c5
{ The position is quite dead. I didn't love that I never had any winning chances, but it says a lot that a technical player like Kamsky was completely unable to put me under any pressure at all. }
