[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Navara, D. vs. Karjakin, S., Wijk aan Zee 2012"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5
8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Nc3 Ke8 10. h3 h5 11. Bg5 Be6 12. Rfd1 Be7
{ This is whereour repertoire line ends. Unlike the previous game, here we see that trading the dark squared bishops is okay. It all comes down to h5-h4 coming and making it impossible for White to advance his majority. }
13. b3 h4 14. Rd3 Rd8 15. Rxd8+ Bxd8 16. Rd1 Be7 17. Bf4
{ 17.Bxe7  Trading the bishops doesn't help White. After  17...Kxe7  It proves impossible to advance the g-pawn, thanks in no small part to the h3/h4 pawn structure. }
17... Rg8 18. Ng5 Bc8 19. Nce4 Rh8
{ Rh8-g8-h8 might not look impressive, but White has no plan or any way to break down the position. Now, Karjakin reroutes his bishop to b7. }
20. c4 b6 21. Nf3 Rh5 22. Kf1 Bd8 23. Nfg5 Be7 24. Nf3 Bd8 25. Nfg5 Be7 26. Rd3
{ Navara surely regretted not repeating moves here. } 26... c5 27. Nf3 Bb7
{ All of a sudden, Black's pieces are looking very active. } 28. Nc3 Bxf3 29.
Rxf3
{ This was not strictly necessary, but I like it. Black simplifies the position and leaves White with a bad bishop on f4. }
29... Nd4
{ We often see the knight hope to reroute to e6, sometimes even via e7, g6, f8, and only then e6. Now, Karjakin got there faster! }
30. Rd3 Ne6 31. Bh2 a6 32. f4 c6
{ Black's position is super solid, thanks in no small part to pushing h5-h4. Imagine the pawn back on h6 and the rook back on h8- White would push g2-g4 and f4-f5, and probably win easily. }
33. Kf2 Nd4 34. Ke3 Rh6 35. Ne2 Rg6
{ Now, sadly White is unable to preserve the pawn structure. } 36. Nxd4 cxd4+
37. Kf3 c5 38. g4 hxg3
{ Of course. This is always the move Black is counting on, and here it means he is a little better instead of resigning on the spot. }
39. Bxg3 f5 40. exf6 Rxf6 41. b4
{ White was facing a difficult defense, but this only makes his life worse. }
41... Rh6
{ 41...cxb4!  42.Rxd4  a5  Black should win routinely on the queenside. } 42.
Kg4 Re6 43. Kf3 g6 44. Bf2 Kd7 45. Ra3 cxb4
{ This should have been played earlier, more than once, but Karjakin eventually found the right way. }
46. Rd3 Bf6 47. Bxd4 Rd6 { The easiest. Black forces a winning pawn endgame. }
48. Ke3 Bxd4+ 49. Rxd4 Rxd4 50. Kxd4 Kd6 51. Kd3 a5 52. a3 bxa3 53. Kc3 Kc5 54.
h4 a2 55. Kb2 Kxc4 56. f5 gxf5 57. h5 f4 58. h6 f3 59. h7 f2 60. h8=Q a1=Q+
{ A fine effort from Karjakin. Not only were his moves strong, it showed also how to practically play the Berlin for a win.   Be patient, don't do anything rash, sit tight and solid, and wait for your opponent's frustration to boil over and for them to eventually go off the rails. }
