[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Nepomniachtchi, I. vs. Eljanov, P., Dagomys 2010"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. dxe5 Nxb5 7. a4 Nbd4 8.
Nxd4 d5 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Qd3 Qd7
{ This far, Eljanov is followingthe repertoire. } 11. b3 a5
{ A typical move. Black gains a tempo by threatening Ba6. } 12. Re1 Bb4
{ I like provoking the pawn to c3 before putting the bishop on e7. This leaves b3 as a weakness and denies the c3 square for the white knight.   12...Be7  13.Ba3  c5  14.Nc3  Nice that White has this square! }
13. c3 Be7 14. Ba3 c5 15. f4 O-O 16. Nd2
{ I really don't believe in White's attack here. The control of the light squares is too good. }
16... Rb8
{ 16...Rd8  This would have been my instinct. Overprotect the d5 pawn to make sure we are ready to meet Rf1 with Qf5, stopping any hope of a pawn storm. }
17. Rf1
{ Not a subtle move, but of course Eljanov is not to foolish to allow f5. }
17... g6
{ 17...f5  This was a decent alternative. Just don't let White push f5! } 18.
f5 gxf5
{ Well understood. Black is ready to lift his rook to g6, and then who is attacking who? }
19. Rf3 Rb6
{ Now, Nepo clearly understood the game is not going his way, and he made the right decision to shake things up a bit. }
20. Nf1 Rxb3 21. Ne3
{ It looks a little scary now, but Black is only a couple good mvoes away from a pleasant position. }
21... d4 22. Nxf5 Rxc3 23. Qe4 Kh8
{ 23...Bg5!  This would have been stronger, and White is more or less out of gas.  24.Raf1  Rxf3  25.Rxf3  d3!  I suspect this is the move Eljanov missed. The king is safe enough to survive a few moves as Black goes and makes a new queen. }
24. Nxe7 Qxe7 25. Rxc3 dxc3 26. Qe3 Qe6
{ Black has a nice blockade on the light squares. As long as White cannot get his dark squared bishop into the game, he will not be able to give mate. }
27. Qxc3 Rg8 28. Bb2 c4
{ 28...Bb7!  When playing with opposite bishops, the attack is everything. After  29.g3  Rd8!  Black is ready for Kg8 next to avoid any discovered checks, then the queen comes to the long diagonal. White is crushed. }
29. Rf1 Qb6+ 30. Kh1 Be6
{ Finally he moved! After remaining on c8 all game... } 31. h3 Qc6 32. Qd2 Rg6
33. Kh2 Kg7 34. Bc3 Qxa4 35. Rf4
{ 35.Bxa5  White should have grabbed this pawn, with a probable draw. } 35...
Qb3 { a5 is immune, thanks to the check on g3. } 36. Rd4 Qb1 37. Qf2 a4 38. Rd7
{ White is trying, but Black's defenses are too solid. } 38... Qc1 39. Bb2 Qg5
40. h4 { 40.Rxf7+  Bxf7  41.e6+  Rf6!  Black wins. } 40... Qxg2+
{ An excellent decision. Now we will soon reach an endgame reminiscent of Topalov-Shirov, where Black gives his generally useless opposite colored bishop to get a pawn mass that cannot be held back. }
41. Qxg2 Rxg2+ 42. Kxg2 Bxd7 43. e6+ Kf8 44. exd7
{ 44.exf7!  By some miracle, this is still a draw. The bishop cannot be removed from the long diagonal, keeping all 3 queenside pawns at bay. }
44... Ke7 45. Kf3 Kxd7 { White's bishop is no match for all the pawns. } 46.
Bf6 Ke6 47. Bc3 Kf5 48. Bb2 c6 49. Bc3 a3 50. Bb4 a2 51. Bc3 c5 52. Ba1 Ke6 53.
Ke3 Kd5 54. Bc3 Kc6 55. Bf6 Kb5 56. Kd2 c3+
{ The last finesse. The bishop is forced off of f6, and once Black gets to play f5, his pawns cannot all be blockaded on the same diagonal. }
57. Bxc3 f5 58. Kd3 h5 59. Be5 Kb4 60. Kc2 f4 61. Kb2 f3 62. Bg3 Kc4 63. Bf2
Kd3 64. Kxa2 Ke2 65. Bxc5 f2 66. Bxf2 Kxf2 67. Kb2 Kg3 68. Kc2 Kxh4 69. Kd2 Kg3
