[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Vachier Lagrave, M. vs. Giri, A., London Chess Classic 2015"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5
8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. h3 Ke8 10. Nc3 h5 11. Ne2 b6 12. Rd1 Be7
{ 12...Bb7  This was the move I gave inthe repertoire, and I prefer it to what Anish chose, but I mainly included this game to show the power of the b7-bishop when White lets it get there. }
13. Bg5 Bb7 14. Bxe7 Kxe7 15. Ned4
{ 15.Ng5  The machine claims this is best, but after  15...h4!  Black still looks fine to me. As usual, the h5-h4 push against h2-h3 makes the kingside majority ineffective. }
15... Nxd4 16. Nxd4 c5 { Well spotted. The check on f5 is a non issue. } 17.
Nb5
{ 17.Nf5+?  Ke6!  18.Nxg7+  Kxe5  Black wins a piece. It's quite nice that the h7-h5 advance keeps the white knight from escaping! }
17... Rhc8
{ Everything is nice and solid now, and soon enough the knight will be kicked away, freeing Black's rooks. White's e5-pawn is overextended and he is not able to set his kingside in motion. }
18. f4 Bc6 19. Nc3 Ke6 20. Kf2 h4
{ Typical. Black prevents any hope of g2-g4, and now he can even run the king in and try to take f4. f4 is weak, g2 is weak, the bishop is better than the knight... things are not looking great for White. }
21. a4 Kf5 22. Ke3 Re8 23. Nd5 Rac8 24. Rd2 f6
{ That's the end of that. But what choice did White have? Get the king off of e3 and lose the f4-pawn? His position was just rotten throughout. }
25. Rf1 fxe5 26. fxe5+ Kg5 27. Nc3 Rxe5+ 28. Kf2 Rf8+ 29. Kg1 Rxf1+ 30. Kxf1
{ Anish easily cleaned up from here. } 30... Rf5+ 31. Kg1 Rf4 32. Re2 Kf6 33.
b3 a6 34. Nd1 Bd5 35. c4 Be6 36. a5 Rd4 37. Nf2 Bf5 38. Ra2 Rd6 39. Kf1 Ke5 40.
Re2+ Kf4 41. Ra2 g5 42. Ke1 Re6+ 43. Kf1 Re3 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Maghsoodloo, P. vs. Shankland, S., Tata Steel India Rapid 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Shortly after finishing the Berlin Lifetime Repertoire, I participated in the Tata Steel India Rapid/Blitz tournament.   I think analyzing blitz games is not a useful exercise, but I certainly wanted to include the two rapid games I played where I faced 1.e4. I played the repertoire both times and got quite fine positions. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. d3 Nf6 5. Nc3
{ Parham later told me he thinks this move is much better than it is given credit for. He certainly made a case for White having decent chances in the game, though it has to be said that Black could play better. }
5... a6 6. O-O d6 7. Bg5 h6 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Nd5 Qd8 10. c3 Ba7 11. a4 O-O 12.
Ne3 Ne7
{ Thus far, I am followingthe repertoire completely, playing the same recommended a6/Ba7 and Ne7-g6 maneuvre. But Parham soon changed the nature of the position. }
13. d4 exd4 14. Nxd4
{ 14.cxd4  I had only considered this structure when making the repertoire. Here, I think Black has a pleasant enough position after  14...c6!  When he intends d5 next. }
14... Ng6
{ This was a very poor reaction. I still had the idea to play for c6 at some point, but the position is totally different when White takes with the knight on d4.   14...Nc6!  It's a bit strange to bring the knight right back where it came from, but given that White has taken with the knight on d4, this is definitely best. It would not be so easy to contain the central pressure, and Black is ready for a move like Re8 next. The machine even gives him a slight edge. }
15. Kh1 Re8 16. Qc2
{ The right way to defend the pawn. White is playing very ambitiously, hoping for f2-f4 next.   16.f3  This is much softer. After  16...c6  d5 is annoying to prevent. }
16... c6 17. Rad1 Qf6 18. Ndf5
{ Black did not get the d5 break through and his position is really miserable. It almost reminds me of a colors reversed situation of the bad Italian positions that we saw inWei vs Vidit andNakamura vs Grischuk. The d6 pawn will be forever weak. }
18... Bxf5 19. Nxf5 Rad8 20. f4 { All of a sudden, Nxd6 is a serious threat. }
20... Nh4 21. Ng3
{ 21.Nxd6?  This does not quite work here.  21...Rxd6  22.e5  Rxd1!  23.exf6  Rxf1+  24.Bxf1  Re1  25.Qd3  We see a hidden point of Nh4 now.  25...Nf5!  Just in time. White cannot break the pin before Ne3 ends the game next move. }
21... Qg6 22. Bd3 Qg4 23. Be2 Qe6 24. e5
{ This seems a bit too fancy to me, though White is still much better.   24.f5!  Qe5  25.Qd2!  Black will have a very hard time saving his knight. }
24... Kh8
{ 24...dxe5?  25.f5  White is ready for Ne4 and g3 next, winning a piece. } 25.
Qe4
{ And now I am back in the game.   25.Bh5!  Preventing f5 and increasing the pressure. Black is in big trouble. }
25... f5
{ Well spotted. Now, I will be able to take on e5 without allowing f4-f5 from White. Already the tables are turning and I was feeling very optimistic, although Black is not better just yet. }
26. Qb4 Bc5
{ Distracting the queen.   26...dxe5  Black is not ready for this yet.  27.Rxd8  Rxd8  28.fxe5!  The hanging knight turns out to be a serious issue. }
27. Qxb7 dxe5 28. Nh5 Bf8
{ White's king will soon come under serious fire. The previously horrid knight on h4 becomes a very dangerous attacking piece. }
29. Qxa6 Rxd1 30. Rxd1 exf4 31. Nxf4 Qe3 32. Rf1 Bd6
{ I missed the win, but we were both very low on time at this point.   32...Re4!  33.Qc8  Rxf4  34.Qxf8+  Kh7  35.Rxf4  Qxe2!  Somehow I had only considered taking the rook, which is indeed unclear, but this is mate. }
33. Bh5 Rb8 34. Nd3 Qe4 { White still has a difficult defense ahead. } 35. Bf3
Nxf3 36. Rxf3 Qe2 37. Nb4
{ With the seconds ticking down, I missed a fantastic winning move here. }
37... Qe5
{ 37...Rb5!  This would have won. White's queen is cut off from the f1 square, and Black mates on the back rank. Furthermore, after  38.Qc8+  Kh7  The rook protects f5 as well, avoiding the perpetual. }
38. g3
{ Now White is fine objectively, but Parham soon blundered and lost. It's hard to play on a 5 second increment! }
38... Bxb4 39. cxb4 Qe4 40. Kg2 { 40.Qd3= } 40... Rd8
{ Oops. Qd3 is prevented, Rd2 is a massive threat, and White is crushed. } 41.
Qf1 Rd2+ 42. Kg1 Qd4+ 43. Rf2 Rd1 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
