[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Karthikeyan, M. vs. Shankland, S., Tata Steel India Rapid 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ In my second black game in Kolkata, I got another chance to test the repertoire, this time against Murali Karthikeyan. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Nbd2 O-O 6. Bxc6 bxc6
{ I chose the same enterprising moveI am recommending, offering a pawn for some compensation. I really dislike the dxc6 structures when Black castles short. }
7. Nxe5 Re8 8. Nef3 d5 9. O-O Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 11. Qe2
{ This was the first new move for me. Black has several options, but I quite like what I played. }
11... Nd7
{ Very ambitious. I was looking for moves like Qf6 and Ne5 to come soon.   11...dxe4  12.Nxe4  h6  This is also possible, and Black should be fine as well. It's hard to deal with the pin on the e-file. }
12. Nb3
{ 12.b3  The machine offers this move, but after  12...Qf6!  13.Rb1  Qg6!  Black still has a lot of pressure for his missing pawn. f5 might be coming next. }
12... Bb6 13. Be3 dxe4 14. dxe4
{ Here I saw I could take e4 and thought the position is pretty dry and drawish. It's certainly a decent option but I was already feeling more ambitious. }
14... Qf6 15. Nbd2
{ 15.g4  Bg6  16.Nfd2  The machine claims this is equal, but Black is winning his pawn back and White's kingside is compromised. I find it unsuprising that Karthi did not go for it. }
15... Qxb2
{ Material is equalized and White will struggle to keep Black's activity under control. }
16. Qd3 Bxf3 17. Nxf3 Ne5 18. Nxe5 Qxe5
{ Now, White in a tough spot. There's no good way to save the e4 pawn without taking b6, which changes the pawn structure tremendously in Black's favor. }
19. Bxb6
{ 19.f3  This should have been preferred, but after  19...Rad8  20.Qb3  Rd2!  White's position looks very scary. The computer only barely holds it together. }
19... axb6
{ White's position is rife with weaknesses. From here on out, Karthi defended very well. }
20. Qd7 c5 21. a4 Re7 22. Qb5 Ra5 23. Qd3
{ Nothing is falling off the board just yet, but White still has a lot of work to do to save the game. }
23... g6 24. Rfe1 Kg7
{ 24...Qd4  I should have taken my chance to play this move before White played c3. I saw it but I was unsure about the position after  25.Qxd4  cxd4  26.f3  With Red1 coming next. The computer points out that Black can and should prevent this with  26...f5!  And White is in big trouble. }
25. c3 Re6
{ I was planning Rd6 and c4 with this move, but I completely missed White's next. }
26. Qe3
{ Now f4 is coming, with very real counterplay. Already White is fine - it can be tough to play rapid without mistakes back and forth! }
26... f5
{ I saw some nice tricks with this move, but unfortunately, so did my opponent and he did not fall for them. }
27. Rad1
{ 27.f4  This looks very tempting for White, but after  27...Qxe4  28.Qf2  Rather than allowing some Rxe6 and Re1 with a huge attack on the way, Black has  28...Rxa4!  And White can resign. }
27... fxe4 28. Rd7+ Re7 29. Qxe4 { The simplest. Everything comes off. } 29...
Qxe4 30. Rxe7+ Qxe7 31. Rxe7+ Kg8 32. Rxc7 Rxa4 33. Rb7 Rc4 34. Rxb6 Rxc3
{ While these two rapid games were anything but clean @@StartBracket@@they are rapid after all!@@EndBracket@@ I was very happy with the positions I got from the opening, and with scoring 1.5/2 with the black pieces against some tough guys. }
